<FIRST>u a AM-DrugEnforcement     04-26 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Enforcement,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Calls For More International Cooperation In Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard Richard Thornburgh on
Wednesday night praised a growing emphasis on international
cooperation in the war on drugs, and promised multinational
operations against drug traffickers.
   Thornburgh spoke at the 20-member International Drug Enforcement
Conference, which President Bush is to adress Thursday morning as
part of two-day visit to Florida.
   Thornburgh spoke to reporters before his address to a closed
session of the conference.
   ``Drug trafficking operations cross many national boundries and
are beyond the reach of any one nation,'' he said.
   The attorney general added that during his trip to Latin America
last month, he made plans for more combined efforts against drugs.
   Thornburgh praised the United Nations Drug Convention adopted
last December in Vienna, and called for its early ratification by
the Senate.
   The multilateral agreement by more than 100 drug-producing and
consuming nations is an effort to establish a set of
internationally recognized drug trafficking offenses as guidelines
for domestic law in each country.
   In his speech, released before the closed session, Thornburgh
praised the arrest earlier this month of Manuel Felix Gallardo, who
was thought to control much of the Mexican drug trade.
   ``None of us are naive enough to think that the arrest of one
kingpin will dismantle any cartel,'' Thornburgh said. ``But the
fact that we now have `untouchables' such as Felix Gallardo and
(former Colombian kingpin) Carlos Lehder behind bars sends powerful
signals worldwide.''
   All member nations of the conference have laws on the books or
pending to control drug-processing chemicals, Lawn said.
   Legislation signed into law last November by President Reagan
requires manufacturers to keep sales records and encourages them to
report suspicious purchases of precursor chemicals to the DEA.
   The law drew particular praise from the Colombian delegation,
which maintains its country has been blamed unfairly for the
international drug scourge.
   The seventh annual conference, meeting in the United States for
the first time, has drawn upper-level drug enforcement officials
from Latin America and Canada in an effort to develop a hemispheric
anti-drug strategy.
   On Thursday, Bush is scheduled to participate in a simulated
drug interdiction exercise and to address an opening ceremony at a
high-tech center where the U.S. Customs Service and the Coast Guard
will gather intelligence and coordinate the fight against drug
smugglers throughout the eastern United States.
</TEXT>
