<FIRST>u a AM-SovietDefectors     04-26 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defectors,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Keeps Defectors On Little Diomede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second day of bad weather prevented the Alaska
National Guard from bringing two Soviet defectors to the mainland
from Little Diomede Island, a Guard spokesman said Tuesday.
   Mike Haller said that when weather permits, a Guard helicopter
will fly the men from the island in the Bering Strait to Nome. From
there they will be flown to Anchorage to file formal requests for
political asylum.
   The two sought asylum just hours before officials signed a
protocol aimed at easing travel restrictions between Alaska and
Siberia.
   Their applications will be forwarded to the State Department for
review and a recommendation, said Gary Johnson, district director
of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. The final decision
rests with the INS, he said.
   The process usually takes several weeks, Johnson said.
   Soviet officials are aware of the defections, but ``at this
point we have no comment,'' said Andre Dronov, a Soviet vice consul
based in San Francisco.
   Johnson declined to identify the men or provide additional
information about them. But sources on the island, who asked not to
be identified, said the men were apprentice journalists from Moscow
in their mid-30s. They are staying at the local Guard armory.
   Johnson said they were the first Soviet defectors in his 10
years with the INS in Alaska.
   The men were reported missing when the Soviet delegation
prepared to leave the island by helicopter after a party following
the signing ceremony.
   Other National Guardsmen helped the Soviets search for the two,
said Jim Stimpfle, a Nome Chamber of Commerce official who had
reached the island before the weather turned bad.
   Stimpfle said the guardsmen apparently either didn't know about
the defections or felt it wasn't proper protocol to inform their
Soviet guests.
   Adj. Gen. John Schaeffer, commander of the Alaska National
Guard, said the timing of the defections was embarrassing.
   ``The governor is trying to get along better with the Soviets
and here comes a couple of people who are basically messing up the
operation,'' said Schaffer, ``All of us would have liked to say,
`Sorry guys, let's try next week.'''
   Stimpfle, still weathered in on the island, said the defectors
are being kept under tight security. ``Everything is hush, hush,''
he said. ``They've even got the armory windows blacked out with
ponchos or something.''
</TEXT>
