<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     04-26 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Wins Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC domination of prime-time reached 44 weeks
_ two shy of the record, but ABC's comedy heavyweight ``Roseanne''
beat out ``The Cosby Show'' for the top spot.
   NBC had six of the top 10 shows and ABC had three, while CBS
managed only one.
   NBC's cumulative rating was 13.3, with a 23 share for last week;
CBS was second with an 11.8 rating and a 21 share; ABC 11.6 and 20,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with
televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   Two sitcoms about families _ the blue-collar ``Roseanne'' and
NBC's upper middle-class Huxtables on ``The Bill Cosby Show'' _
placed first and second in the ratings, respectively.
   ``Roseanne'' served as a lead-in for the ABC premiere of the new
series ``Have Faith,'' with a spring debut at No. 3. The show is
about three Roman Catholic priests and a monsignor in a Chicago
parish.
   NBC's ``A Different World'' was fourth, followed by its
``Cheers''; ``The Wonder Years,'' on ABC; ``The Golden Girls,''
NBC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS; and NBC's ``Empty Nest'' and ``Hunter.''
   NBC's ``Nick and Hilary'' made its debut at 18th place. The show
is a half-hour retool of the failed hourlong ``Tattinger's.''
   The made-for-television movie, ``Baywatch: Panic At Malibu
Pier,'' about muscular Southern California lifeguards, was in 11th
place for NBC. The show from former NBC chief Grant Tinker's
production company is a contender for a fall series.
   The ABC-TV movie ``Peter Gunn,'' returning one of television's
most popular detectives to the small screen, was in 21st place,
while NBC's two-part miniseries ``Around The World In 80 Days,''
starring Pierce Brosnan, landed in 30th and 31st places.
   In news, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' took first place for the
week with a 10.0 rating, followed by ``CBS Evening News'' with 9.3
and ``NBC Nightly News'' with 8.9.
   NBC is closing on the 46-week first-place Nielsens run that CBS
achieved in the 1962-1963 season, when the CBS schedule included
``The Andy Griffith Show,'' ``The Beverly Hillbillies,'' ``The Dick
Van Dyke Show'' and ``Perry Mason.''
   Fox Network's ``Married...With Children,'' recently under fire
by groups critical of the show's portrayal of family life, stood in
49th place and was the network's highest-rated show for the week,
followed by ``America's Most Wanted,'' at 58th and ``21 Jump
Street,'' in the 76th spot.
</TEXT>
