<FIRST>r a PM-ANPAOfficers     04-26 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ANPA Officers,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publishers' Association Picks Board Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William H. Cowles III, president and publisher of
two Spokane, Wash., newspapers, has been elected to a one-year term
as chairman of the board of the American Newspaper Publishers
Association.
   Cowles, 57, runs The Spokesman-Review and the Spokane Chronicle.
   Cowles, three other officers, four returning board members and
one new board member were elected by voice vote at the ANPA's
annual meeting Tuesday.
   Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman of The New York Times Co. and
publisher of The New York Times, will become a member of the ANPA
board for one year as its immediate past chairman.
   Other officers elected to one-year terms were Lloyd G. Schermer,
chairman of Lee Enterprises Inc. of Davenport, Iowa, as vice
chairman; Robert F. Erburu, chairman of The Times Mirror Co. of Los
Angeles as secretary; and Frank A. Bennack Jr., president of The
Hearst Corp. of New York as treasurer.
   The new member elected Tuesday to the 22-member board was
William O. Taylor, publisher of The Boston Globe. He will serve for
two years.
   Four board members re-elected to two-year terms, beginning
Wednesday, were Antonio Luis Ferre, president and publisher of El
Nuevo Dia of San Juan, Puerto Rico; Donald E. Newhouse, president
and general manager of The Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J.; Charles S.
Rowe, editor and co-publisher of The Free Lance-Star of
Fredericksburg, Va., and Richard J. Warren, president of the Bangor
Daily News in Maine.
</TEXT>
