<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ANPA     04-26 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ANPA,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishers Urged To Use Technology, Updated Ads, To Thrive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers must use the latest technologies and
updated advertising techniques in order to remain a competitive,
thriving force in their communities, publishers have been told.
   Some newspapers are already following that advice with
impressive results, news executives were told at the American
Newspaper Publishers Association's 103rd annual convention on
Tuesday.
   These papers, for example, are using telephone recordings of
up-to-the-minute sports scores and boldly colored ads in the middle
of their stock listings.
   ``If newspapers are going to be as successful in the future as
they've been in the past, we have to be much more zealous about
getting close to our customers and staying there. Technology can
help us do that,'' said James K. Batten, president of Miami-based
Knight-Ridder
   Batten spoke to more than 500 people gathered for a morning
session at the three-day meeting, which ends today.
   In 1967, he said, 73 percent of American adults said they read a
newspaper every day, while last year, ``everyday readership hit a
new low of 51 percent,'' and sank to 29 percent ``among the group
that is key to our long-term future _ adults between 18 and 29.''
   That decline, as well as the aging of the baby-boom generation,
an increase in two-income households and growing cultural
diversity, must be dealt with through technology, Batten said.
   ``Used intelligently, the telephone and the computer can let us
recreate the kind of personal relationships that newspapers had
with their customers 20 or 25 years ago,'' Batten said.
   He cited the Providence (R.I.) Journal-Bulletin, which offers
telephone recordings of soap-opera updates, publishing an access
code for readers. The code is changed daily, so that those who want
to use the service must read the paper to find it. More than 20,000
calls a month are recorded on the system, Batten said.
   In Colorado, he said, the Boulder Daily Camera gets more than
77,000 calls a month for recordings of sports scores and stories
that come in after the paper has gone to press.
   The systems are relatively inexpensive, requiring little more
than a personal computer, phone lines and tape recordings, Batten
said.
   He said newspapers have little choice but to change with their
readers.
   ``These (changes in readers) are threats, not to our existence
but to our pricing flexibility, to our ability to finance the news
coverage that our communities deserve and that we want to
provide,'' Batten said.
   Other threats include a trend among advertisers toward using
direct mail and other techniques to communicate directly with
consumers, said Frank A. Bennack Jr., president and chief executive
officer of The Hearst Corp.
   Direct mail represents 14 percent of all U.S. advertising and
its growth is expected to outpace traditional media advertising,
Bennack said.
   Newspapers must develop new strategies for capturing
advertisers' dollars, such as updating their television guide
sections and standardizing ad sizes used in the guides, said Jerry
Tillis, marketing vice president at Knight-Ridder and president of
the Detroit Free Press.
   Tillis noted that with the spread of cable television, ``more
promotion dollars are being spent by networks, stations,'' and
others.
   Another recommendation is ``adoption of the `island position' on
the first page of agate stock listings in your financial
sections,'' he said.
   Craig Standen, president of the Newspaper Advertising Bureau,
noted the recent introduction by Portland's Oregonian newspaper of
a boldly colored ad in the middle of its sports scoreboard.
   ``I think the long-term outlook for our business is bright,'' he
said. ``But that future depends on our ability to change and make
new opportunities happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
