<FIRST>u a AM-TrainDerailment     04-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Derailment,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Train Derailment Forces Evacuations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILFORD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten cars on a train hauling potentially
toxic chemicals derailed Tuesday night, forcing evacuation of
residents up to half a mile away, officials said.
   No injuries were reported and no chemicals were believed to have
leaked as result of the accident, which was reported around 7:45
p.m., said Oakland County sheriff's Sgt. Tom Parker.
   It was not known exactly how many people were evacuated, Parker
said. Evacuees were taken to Milford High School.
   The train was hauling chemicals from Dow Chemical Co.'s Midland
plant 80 miles north of here to Freeport, Texas. Milford is about
20 miles northwest of Detroit.
   The derailed cars were described as empty, but Dow spokesman
Patrick Goggin said they may have contained up to 100 gallons of
chemicals.
   At least nine of the other cars on the train that remained on
the tracks carried potentially toxic chemicals, Goggin said from
the company's Midland headquarters.
   The chemicals were styrene monomer, a liquid used in
refrigerator liners and auto interiors; vinyl chloride, a
compressed gas used as an adhesive; and propylene oxide, a liquid
used to make foam for seats and other products, he said.
   The cars were owned or leased by Dow, though the crew was
employed by a rail company, Goggin said. He said he didn't know the
name of the rail company.
</TEXT>
