<DOCNO> AP890426-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ANPA-Minorities     04-26 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ANPA-Minorities,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Minorities Vital To Future Of Newspapers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-ANPA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attracting more minority readers would enable
newspapers to tap into fastest-growing segments of the U.S.
population and could offset flat circulation trends, a publishers'
task force says.
   The group presented a 40-page report, titled ``Cornerstone for
Growth: How Minorities Are Vital to the Future of Newspapers,'' to
news executives at the annual convention of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association on Tuesday.
   The study recommends that newspapers pursue not only minority
readers, but minority employees and advertisers as well.
   ``What we have done, in a very quantifiable way, is to make the
case that what is right and fair is also smart business,'' said
David Lawrence Jr., publisher of the Detroit Free Press and
chairman of the task force.
   Daily newspaper circulation is about 63 million, barely more
than the 62 million of 1970.
   But the task force report noted that 87 percent of the U.S.
population growth between now and the year 2000 will be among
minorities, principally blacks, Hispanics, Asian-Americans and
native Americans.
   Further, the report concluded, more than 56 percent of workers
joining the labor force between now and the year 2000 will be
members of minorities. In order to attract both this advertising
target audience and future employees, newspapers will have to
adjust their sights to better serving minorities, the report said.
   ``This ... is a particularly useful tool for publishers as they
continue to change their newspapers to better meet the needs of
their communities,'' said Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, publisher of The
New York Times and chairman of the ANPA.
   In addition to providing profiles on what some newspapers are
doing to adapt to the changing demographics in their markets, the
report debunks myths about minorities that researchers said have
slowed growth in newspaper readership, circulation and advertising:
   _ Although some have suggested pursuing minority markets is
futile because minorities don't read newspapers, the report found
minorities at higher income and education levels have the same
readership rates as non-minorities _ about 70 percent.
   _ Although some argue that Spanish-speaking and Asian groups
resist English-language newspapers, the report concluded their
children will be among the newspaper's future readers.
   _ Although some argue that minorities can't afford to buy
newspapers or advertise in them, the report found minority income
levels increasing and growing faster than non-minority income.
While non-minorities' disposable household income rose just 18
percent from 1980 to 1986, comparable figures show blacks' income
increasing by 21 percent, Hispanics' by 45 percent and
Asian-Americans' by 58 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
