<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill-Excerpts     04-26 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill-Excerpts,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Radio Conversations In Alaskan Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from radio
conversations taped March 24 after the Exxon Valdez ran aground in
Prince William Sound in the nation's worst oil spill.
   The exchanges timed off automatically and began 23 minutes after
the ship's log indicated the tanker ran aground. The tapes were
obtained under a Freedom of Information Act request filed by the
Anchorage Daily News.
   
   12:27 a.m. AST:
   Exxon Valdez Captain Joseph Hazelwood: ``We've fetched up hard
aground north of Goose Island off Bligh Reef. Evidently we're
leaking some oil and we're going to be here for a while.''
   
   1:07 a.m.
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Steve McCall: ``This is the captain of the
port, Commander McCall. Good evening. Do you have any more of an
estimate as to your situation at this time?''
   Hazelwood:``Ah, not at the present, Steve. Joe Hazelwood here. A
little problem here with the third mate, but we're working our way
off the reef. We've, ah, the vessel has been holed and we're
ascertaining right now, we're trying just to get her off the reef
and we'll get back to you as soon as we can.''
   McCall: ``Take it slow and easy. You know, I'm telling you the
obvious, but take it slow and easy, and we're getting help out as
fast as we can.''
   Hazelwood: ``We're in pretty good shape right now,
stability-wise, and, ah trying to extract her off the shoal here.
You can probably see me on you radar, and, ah, once we get under
way, I'll let you know, do another damage control assessment.''
   McCall: ``Before you make any drastic attempt to get away, make
sure you don't you know, start doing any ripping. You got a rising
tide, you, another , about an hour and a half worth of tide in your
favor, ah, ah, once you hit that max, I wouldn't recommend doing
much wiggling.''
   Hazelwood: ``Major damage has kind of been done and we kind of
rock and rolled over it. We're just kind of hung up on the stern
here. We're just, ah, we'll drift over it. Ah, I'll get back to
you.''
   McCall: ``Captain of the port out.''
   
   1:59 a.m.
   McCall: ``Any update, captain?''
   A new, unidentified voice on the Exxon Valdez: ``We're still
surveying tanks, trying to assess the damage.''
   McCall: ``Roger, do you have capacity on board to internally
transfer if you need to?''
   The Valdez voice: ``Yes, we could do that.''
   McCall: ``OK, that's, obviously you know better than I do, but
that's highly recommended if, once you've determined which tanks
are holed, to drop the head if you can.''
   The Valdez voice: ``Yes, roger that.''
   McCall: ``Are you still working, trying to get off?''
   The Valdez: ``No, our engines are stopped right now. We're going
to wait 'til there's a little more water underneath us.''
   
   3:19
   McCall: ``Have you had a chance to detect whether or not any
noticeable amount of oil has dropped out of any tanks and, if so,
which tanks are they?''
   A voice from the Exxon Valdez: ``Ah, the initial figure is
138,000 and the chief mate's taking another check on it right now.''
   McCall: ``Which tank is that, or tanks?''
   The same Valdez voice: ``Right now, our starboard slop tank, two
starboard wing tanks, and possibly five center.''
   McCall: ``You said starboard?''
   The voice: ``Roger.''
   McCall (gloomily) _ ``Roger on that, and that was barrels,
correct.''
   The voice: ``That's correct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
