<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bush'sVillage     04-26 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush's Village,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Ancestral Village Hopes for Presidential Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MESSING, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the day George Bush took over the
presidency from Ronald Reagan, a phone conversation between two
innkeepers added an Old World footnote to the transition.
   ``Well then,'' said John O'Farrell in Ballyporeen, Ireland, to
David Harris in Messing, England. ``I suppose it's over to you.''
   And so it was. On Jan. 20, one minute before opening time, the
mantle of presidential ancestral village passed from Reagan's
Ballyporeen to Messing, the English hamlet that Bush's forebears
left for the New World in 1631.
   When it comes to the business of presidential roots, it's the
pubs that seem to be first to have greatness thrust upon them.
   A highlight of Reagan's 1984 trip to the town of his
19th-century peasant ancestors was O'Farrell's pub, where he
stopped for a drink.
   Now David and Diane Harris, owners of the Old Crown Inn, are
hoping Bush will visit Messing when he comes to Britain at the end
of May and stop by for a pint of local brew.
   Tucked away in the Essex countryside, one hour's train ride east
of London, Messing is largely a bedroom community, so empty on
weekdays that ``you could shoot a cannon through it and nobody
would notice,'' according to Diane Harris, the innkeeper's wife.
   The prospect of presidential glory isn't universally welcomed.
   ``There are one or two people who are apprehensive of hordes of
tourists arriving and of commercialization and trivialization,''
says Roger Carter, chairman of the parish council.
   But he doubts it will happen. Messing's ``nice old buildings
would look pretty daft if they were all modernized and turned into
gift stores,'' said Carter, an engaging, tousle-haired man of 46
who takes Messing's presidential connection with a healthy sense of
humor.
   With one pub, one restaurant, four streets and 250 inhabitants,
the village is so small that its main street is called simply The
Street.
   But as tourism becomes one of Britain's biggest industries,
Essex county authorities have developed a heritage trail for
American visitors, and Messing wants a piece of the action.
   ``Business-wise, it will certainly be better for us. We die a
death during the week,'' says Mrs. Harris.
   Although there is no Bush ancestral home or family burial place
in Messing, the medieval church and quaint houses offer good photo
opportunities.
   George Bush, says Carter, is the biggest thing to happen to
Messing since an earthquake in 1884 knocked down the pub.
   ``Presumably if he comes the whole thing will be so
fantastically organized that we locals will get totally squeezed
out,'' he says.
   Hugh Peskett, the respected British genealogist who traced
Bush's origins to Messing, says the president is directly descended
from an aristocratic farmer who left for America in 1631.
   Mrs. Harris likes to daydream about the president's ancestor
strolling in for a drink at the very spot where she's now serving
breakfast.
   Messing's native population has dwindled over the centuries, but
it is now being replenished by affluent refugees from London.
   Carter, 46, moved here six years ago and commutes to a senior
post office job in London. The Harrises, who are in their 40s,
arrived in 1986 after six years in Bahrain and Kuwait and bought
the pub.
   Understandably, Messing rooted for Bush in the election, and the
pub served cake and champagne when he won. Carter invited him to
visit.
   Though noncommittal, Bush said in his reply that ``Messing will
always have a special place in our hearts.''
   In Ballyporeen, O'Farrell says he had no regrets about ceding
the crown.
   ``I felt quite good about it because President Reagan had a very
successful tenure and it was good to see someone going out on a
high note, especially when there's so much pessimism about these
days,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   As for Harris, he's just happy that fate has linked his village
with Bush. ``It's nice,'' he said, ``to see a local lad make good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Students     04-26 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Students,0930</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Upper Class Families, Dissent Is Born In China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   They gather by the tens of thousands in the
capital and elsewhere to call for more democracy, the end of
high-level corruption, and freedom of expression. Who are these
students protesting communist methods; what do they want? Here is a
report by an Associated Press correspondent who went among the
students for this story.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They come mostly from the families of
intellectuals. Their parents are government officials, many of them
are Communist Party members and now they want to change China.
   The tens of thousands of students who took to the streets in
Beijing last week and began an unprecedented class boycott Monday
are by no means the downtrodden of this country of 1.1 billion.
   They are its future scientists, writers, teachers and diplomats.
And they are calling for a new China, one that is democratic, with
a free press and respect for human rights.
   Li Qiang, a senior at Beijing Normal University, remembers when
he first began believing something was wrong with his country.
   The son of a county official in China's northwest, Li, a member
of the Communist Party, recalled that ``people were always giving
us presents.''
   ``There were big meals, TV sets. We never paid for anything.
Last month we got a new video, now we have three,'' he said. ``I
didn't think this was strange until I left home and found out that
governments aren't supposed to work like that.''
   It was his first summer vacation from university.
   ``My father wanted to welcome me home with a banquet. We went
out and had a party. But we didn't pay. The hotel manager owed him
a favor because my father gave him state funds to repair his
building.''
   Li asked his father why he did not pay. ``This is China,'' was
the answer.
   ``This is not the China that I want to be a part of,'' Li said,
expressing a belief shared by many protesters.
   Li's classmate, a 24-year-old woman from Inner Mongolia, said
she was brought up to respect individual rights.
   ``My parents are doctors and we've always had a good
relationship. They let me live my life, never reading my private
letters like other parents. I only wish the government would treat
me the same.''
   Although not a member of the 48 million-member Communist Party,
the woman belongs to its Youth League, a training ground for young
communists.
   She said she believes participating in the protest does not
conflict with the Marxism pushed by the league.
   ``Karl Marx was a democrat. I don't pretend to understand the
real socialism that he wrote about, but I know this isn't it,'' she
said.
   Like many students, the woman was unclear about what kind of
government she wants in China.
   ``But I don't see that as a problem. I know I don't understand
democracy. But my worry now is not with the future, it's with the
present. We have a system that is rotten.''
   Indeed, compared to the pro-democracy protests of 1986-87,
student demands _a free press, more funds for education and
publication of the financial records of China's leadership _ are
relatively clear.
   Still, most students expect the protests to fail. They choose to
view their movement in a romantic light, as a glorious but
inevitably futile cause.
   ``When the time comes they will crush us,'' said one young man
as he gazed at thousands of Chinese soldiers during a demonstration
last week. ``I'm not afraid, but they will crush us just the same.''
   Students said China's increasing openness to the West and the
large number of books translated into Chinese also helped spark
their discontent.
   Several students cited the 1957 book, ``The New Class,'' in
which former Yugoslav official Milovan Djilas charged communism has
produced a new class of privileged leaders instead of a classless
society.
   ``It was an enlightenment for me because it comes from a
socialist country and from a top leader there, too,'' said a
20-year-old sophomore studying psychology.
   Many students said they looked up to leaders of Western
democracies.
   ``I read in the paper that Australia's prime minister, Bob
Hawke, admitted he had been a drinker and a bit of a playboy,''
said one student. ``That to me is a wonderful thing. None of our
leaders would ever do that. They lack honesty and guts.''
   Wu Xi, one of the few demonstrators from a peasant background,
said it was not until he took a trip back home after two years at
university that he made up his mind to try and change China.
   ``I remember when I was in high school. We were taught to love
Deng Xiaoping, and really we did love him,'' he said of China's
84-year-old leader who instituted 1978 agricultural reforms
returning land to peasants. ``But this time when I went home my
family could barely feed me. If this is not Deng's fault, then I
don't know who to blame.''
   Many students openly look down on their countrymen, expressing
impatience with their unwillingness to provide more than some
material and spiritual help to the demonstrators. But they also
doubt themselves.
   ``The Chinese people are numb. They are asleep,'' said one
student. ``But I don't know if we can wake them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
