<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Edwin Makoti</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edwin Letsholo Makoti, a founding member
of the Pan Africanist Congress, died Friday after a long illness.
He was 68.
   Makoti spent most of the movement's 30 years in exile.
   He served in various posts for the group, including
administrative secretary, defense secretary and its representative
in Egypt, Ghana and Indonesia.
   Makoti was head of publicity and information.
   The congress is a guerrilla-backed movement, outlawed in South
Africa, formed in 1959 to fight to end South Africa's system of
racial segregation.
