<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--UnusualSentence     04-26 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Unusual Sentence,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protesters Sentenced To Think About Civil Disobedience</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group convicted for trespassing during
an anti-abortion demonstration said they would defy their sentence
of community service. So the judge decided to get tough.
   City Court Judge John Manning Regan on Tuesday sentenced the 11
to prepare two-page reports on civil disobedience after reading
essays by Plato and Henry David Thoreau. They had been convicted in
December of trespassing at a hospital during a demonstration last
May.
   ``I think it's a bold and honorable step on his part to fulfill
his duty under oath to pronounce sentence, yet to honor our
conscientious objections,'' said David Long, leader of Project
Life, a group that has conducted protests at abortion clinics.
   ``He's basically sentencing us to a dialogue with him about why
we do what we do.''
   Long said he and his co-defendants will obey the sentence
because it does not require them to ``repay society for an evil
done.''
   Regan told them he has the ``deepest respect'' for their
objection and ordered the essays sent to the court by June 16.
</TEXT>
