<FIRST>r a AM-RamboKillings     04-26 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rambo Killings,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steiger Guilty on All Counts in Double Slaying; Faces Death Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college student described as obsessed
with war games and sadomasochistic sex was convicted of murder
Tuesday in the 1987 Rambo-style slayings of two men who broke up an
outdoor party he was attending.
   Eric K. Steiger, who could receive the death penalty, stared
impassively as the verdict by a panel of three Superior Court
judges was announced after two days of deliberations.
   Judges Harry Hammer, Thomas V. Keefe Jr. and George W. Ripley
convicted Steiger, 25, of capital felony, two counts of murder and
one count of conspiracy to commit capital murder in the July 11,
1987 slayings of Daniel Seymour, 25, and William Price, 25.
   The judges tentatively set sentencing for June 6.
   Steiger's attorney, F. Mac Buckley, said he would apppeal. He
also said he would file a motion to dispense with the penalty phase
of the trial on grounds that the state's death penalty statute is
unconstitutionally vague.
   The bearded, heavyset Steiger is the great-grandson of the late
Albert Steiger, founder of the Springfield, Mass.-based Steiger's
chain of department stores.
   Seymour and Price broke up a party on a cul-de-sac near the home
Seymour's family had just moved into, authorities said. One of them
allegedly poked Steiger in the nose with an iron bar.
   Steiger, who was among the revelers, left the party, and went to
his home, where he picked up two guns, and put on camouflage
clothing and a black knit ski mask.
   He returned to Seymour's home with two friends and shot Seymour
and Price to death with a 9mm automatic pistol, firing at least 19
armor-piercing bullets at the victims.
   During the four-month trial, Steiger was described as being
obsessed with guns, war games and sadomasochism.
   Buckley conceded that Steiger shot the two men, but argued his
client suffered from mental disease.
   Steiger chose to have his case decided by the judges rather than
a jury.
</TEXT>
