<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WashingtonAuction     04-26 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Auction,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lincoln Letter Brings Top Price At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first newspaper account of George
Washington's inauguration failed to sell at a Sotheby's auction
Tuesday timed to coincide with the bicentennial celebration
surrounding Washington's swearing-in.
   The May 2, 1789 issue of the Gazette was the ``solitary
disappointment'' of the sale, which otherwise brought in $1.4
million _ more than twice the pre-sale expectations, Sotheby's said
in a statement.
   The top item was an 1855 letter from Abraham Lincoln about his
U.S. Senate defeat, which sold for $77,000 to Chicago dealer Ralph
G. Newman. It was expected to bring at least $25,000.
   Newman also bought an autograph letter of Davy Crockett
concerning a ``true history'' of his life for $20,900. Its pre-sale
estimate was between $10,000 and $15,000.
   All prices include Sotheby's 10 percent commission.
   The Gazette account of Washington's April 25, 1789 inauguration
in lower Manhattan was expected to bring at least $10,000, but
bidding stopped at $4,500 and the item was pulled.
   ``The market for early American newspapers at auction is not a
large one,'' said Sotheby's printed book expert, Selby Kiffer.
   Among the other Washington-related items, a 12-page excerpt from
the diary of the man who served as Washington's secretary from 1786
to 1793 sold for $9,350, less than its pre-sale estimate of at
least $15,000.
   It provides, among other entries, a version of Washington's
memories of Benedict Arnold's treason in 1780.
   Two Washington letters also were sold: a 1780 letter to Gen.
Nathanael Greene commending his Revolutionary War service and a
1796 letter to John Marshall.
   Both letters had pre-sale estimates of at least $9,000. The
Greene letter sold for $23,100 to Maurice Neville, a
California-based dealer.
   The Marshall letter sold for $19,800. The name of the buyer was
not available, Sotheby's said.
</TEXT>
