<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedPig     04-26 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Pig,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plight of Grunt the Homeless Half-Ton Pig Tugs at Citizen's Heartstrings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He weighs a half-ton, squeals a lot and
tries to bite the hands that feed him because his eyesight is poor.
   But that hasn't stopped 300 people statewide from offering a
home to Grunt the abandoned pig, Los Angeles County animal control
officials said Tuesday.
   ``We've had everything from a guy in Lomita who lived in an
apartment and thought the pig would be a cute pet to a man in
Northern California with a 400-acre pig farm who wants to use the
pig as a stud. That would be my choice,'' said animal control Sgt.
James Bay.
   Grunt has been at the department's shelter here the past week,
since he was taken from affluent Rolling Hills Estates, where his
owners abandoned him because they were moving.
   They gave their gardener permission to butcher him, but Grunt
was saved from becoming bacon when his frightened squeals alerted
neighbors.
   Since then, the 4-foot Grunt and his girth have appeared in
newspapers and on television, prompting about 300 calls from
Californians wanting to give the 3-year-old porker a home. One
offer included the Los Angeles County Fair, which keeps farm
animals year-round and wanted to exhibit Grunt.
   Bay said supervisors have made a decision on Grunt's fate but
wouldn't be announcing it immediately.
   Until then, ``He's just eating and having a good time.''
</TEXT>
