<DOCNO> AP890426-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Arms     04-26 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Arms,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheating Beats Embargo, But South African Arms Growth Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: EMBARGOED for release at 4 a.m. EDT. Time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 25-year-old arms embargo against
South Africa has been beaten by cheating, smuggling and legal
loopholes but still has stunted the growth of South Africa's
military, a book published today asserts.
   The study by Signe Landgren of the Stockholm International Peace
Research Institute says that although the South African arms
industry claims to be self-sufficient, it ``owes its existence to
foreign technology,'' most of it acquired legally.
   ``Arms and, increasingly, production know-how, have continued to
reach South Africa, coming from the very Western countries that
agreed in the United Nations to abide by the arms embargo
restrictions,'' Landgren says in the book ``Embargo
Disimplemented.''
   The book lists the United States, Britain, West Germany, Japan,
France, Israel and Italy as having been among the most helpful.
   Landgren said that no matter how inefficient, the embargo
remains one of the few military sanctions that can be imposed on
South Africa and is valuable as a statement condemning the
country's apartheid system of racial segregation.
   In the latest example of Pretoria's cloak-and-dagger
acquisitions, French police arrested three members of a Northern
Irish Protestant militia and a U.S. businessman on Saturday. Police
said the four were delivering stolen parts of a British-made
Blowpipe missile launcher to a South African diplomat.
   British news reports said the state-owned Armscor, the Armaments
Corp. of South Africa, apparently supplied small arms or cash to
Protestant extremists in exchange for blueprints of sophisticated
British weaponry.
   The United Nations imposed a voluntary arms embargo on South
Africa on Aug. 7, 1963 and made it mandatory in 1977. Sanctions
were tightened in 1984 with a resolution discouraging countries
from buying South African-produced weapons.
   The ban often was ineffective and had the countereffect of
spurring the South Africans to build up their own arms industry,
the study said.
   But it also deprived Pretoria of updated weapons systems,
restricted its access to new technologies and curtailed the supply
of spare parts.
   The embargo ``has been a limiting factor to some extent in South
Africa's efforts to expand its military strength,'' says the study,
citing U.S. congressional testimony.
   The study also quotes a 1985 U.N. report that says buying
smuggled or black market weapons added 20 to 100 percent to the
country's arms procurement costs.
   Smuggling operations are hidden by creating dummy companies,
using phony labeling, diverting shipments to new destinations at
sea or in midflight, and forging end-user certificates, it says.
   The embargo also is circumvented legally by importing civilian
products which have military applications, such as electronics and
telecommunications gear, the study says.
   Nuclear technology was one area where the embargo failed to stop
South African advances, it says.
   It reports that by the time the United Nations ordered a halt to
nuclear cooperation in 1977, South Africa had acquired
weapons-grade expertise to go with its vast uranium resources, the
world's second largest reserves.
   ``Its possession of nuclear weapons remains an open question,
but its capacity to produce such weapons is equal to that of almost
any industrial nation in Europe,'' the book says.
   Unlike Western restrictions on technology transfers to the
Soviet bloc, no multinational organization exists to monitor the
embargo against South Africa and there is no list of banned goods
to guide enforcement, Landgren wrote.
   The 16-nation, Paris-based Coordinating Committee for
Multinational Export Control _ COCOM _ set up in 1948, has a
300,000-item list of military contraband, which could be applied
against South Africa, Landgren said.
   South Africa's arms production capability was acquired through
licensing agreements and by buying stakes in arms-making
multinational companies, the study says.
   In 1963, South Africa said it had 120 foreign licenses. Before
the embargo became obligatory 14 years later, Pretoria gained
licenses to produce weapons systems like the French Mirage
jetfighter, the Israeli Reshef gunboat and the Scorpion sea
missile, also Israeli.
   Equipped with the technology, the South Africans could continue
production after the franchises were withdrawn.
   One classic case of a clandestine acquisition was the G-5
artillery piece, based on howitzers obtained from the U.S.-owned
Space Research Corp. in Quebec, Canada and the Belgian Poudreries
Reunis de Belgique.
   The G-5 deal involved contacts through a CIA agent and Israeli
intermediaries. South Africa bought a Dutch-based firm and created
dummy companies in Liechtenstein, Barbados and Canada.
   The first shells were bought from West Germany, bound for Spain
and redirected to South Africa. Production lathes for the guns came
from France, and the shell fillings were imported from West Germany
by way of Paraguay and Brazil. The G-5 technology was later
re-exported to Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Firepower     04-26 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Firepower,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians Reported To Have New Missiles In War With Syrians</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main
militia, have obtained six surface-to-surface missiles from Iraq
capable of hitting the Syrian capital of Damascus, Christian
sources report.
   But the Christians, besieged in their coastal enclave north of
Beirut, are not likely to use the Soviet-designed, Frog-7 missiles
except as a last resort lest they bring down the full weight of the
Syrians' formidable firepower.
   The Christians, led by army commander Gen. Michel Aoun, have
been battling the Syrians and their Moslem allies since March 8.
   No independent confirmation could be obtained that the
Christians acquired the missiles.
   But Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, is known to have provided the
Christians with T-54 tanks, multibarreled rocket launchers, armored
personnel carriers and other weapons in hope of bogging Syria down
in the Lebanese quagmire.
   The Christians and their foes have been fighting it out with
heavy artillery, rockets and giant mortars, wreaking widespread
destruction on both sides.
   More than 100,000 shells have rained on Beirut and its environs
at what military experts estimate is a cost of $70 million in
expended ammunition.
   Hundreds of buildings have been hit and, by police count, more
than 270 people killed and nearly 1,000 wounded. Despite Arab
League peace efforts, the carnage shows no sign of ending.
   The Frog missiles carry warheads containing 1,210 pounds of high
explosive and have a range of 43 miles. That's enough to reach
Damascus if the missiles were fired from mobile launchers in the
mountains that form the Christian enclave's eastern flank.
   A high-ranking Christian officer in the Lebanese army conceded
that six missiles ``are not a serious number'' and that the Frog-7s
``can hardly affect the military balance except for a momentary
transfer of the battle to the Syrian capital.''
   A senior source in the 6,000-strong Lebanese Forces noted, ``We
would use the Frogs only when we're completely cornered, because
Syria's retaliation will be one of total obliteration.''
   Both men spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Syrians have about 40,000 troops based in Lebanon, mainly
Moslem sectors, under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Military experts in Beirut say that totals 15 percent of Syrian
military strength and 10 percent of its firepower.
   They estimate that the Syrians have used just 60 percent of
their firepower in Lebanon against the Christians and have not used
their large air force.
   Syria possibly fears aerial clashes with Israel, which patrols
Lebanese airspace at will and conducts retaliatory raids on targets
in Lebanon after attacks against Israeli targets.
   ``If the Syrians really wanted to pulverize the Christians, they
could do it,'' one Western military analyst noted. ``So far, they
have chosen not to. But what they have deployed can wear the
Christians down through attrition.''
   A Lebanese army officer commented, ``Some of the howitzers used
were designed to demolish bunkers and knock out runways.''
   He referred to the Soviet-made, S-23 180mm howitzer with a range
of 26 miles and firing a 187-pound shell.
   The M-1952 240mm Soviet-designed mortars used by the Syrians is
one of the more destructive weapons being employed.
   One 220-pound shell pierced the residence of Spanish Ambassador
Pedro Manuel de Aristegui this month, killing him and several
family members.
   Chief Warrant Officer Youssef Bitar, a veteran army explosives
officer in Lebanon's 14 years of civil war, said: ``The shell
penetrated two stone ceilings leaving a one-meter diameter hole in
each before exploding in the dining room where the family was
sitting.''
   Ordnance experts believe the shell was probably fired from
Syrian positions in Schweifat, two miles south of the ambassador's
residence.
   The Christians probably fear the Syrians' BM-21 ``Stalin
Organs'' the most.
   These mobile rocket launchers can spew out 40 122mm rockets in
20 seconds, enough to blast a whole city block with high explosives.
   ``It's like hell breaking loose on doomsday,'' said Zeina
Sweidan, a 23-year old interior designer, whose home in the
Christian district of Sin el-Fil was bracketed by a BM-21 salvo
recently.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
