<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-WhiteHouse     04-26 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-White House,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brief Cites Drug Arrests of White House Support Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department brief defending the
administration's plan to test more than 1,500 White House employees
for drugs says two workers have been fired in the last 2{ years
because of illegal drugs.
   ``In one case the employee, a motor vehicle operator, tested
positive at a hospital for cocaine,'' says a declaration by Charles
Easley, the security officer for the Office of Administration. ``In
the second instance, an accounting technician was arrested for
possession of cocaine outside the complex shortly after departing
work.''
   Both employees were fired, Easley said in his declaration, which
is part of the Justice Department brief.
   The positions held by the two fired workers would be subject to
random drug testing under a plan originally proposed by the Reagan
White House and now being pursued by President Bush.
   The brief was filed late Monday in the U.S. District Court where
30 employees of the Executive Office of the President filed suit in
January to block the random drug tests as unnecessary and
unconstitutional.
   A hearing on the case is scheduled for May 11.
   There have been revelations earlier that two National Security
Council clerks resigned and there had been two resignations and two
firings in the Uniformed Division of the Secret Service stemming
from a drug investigation that surfaced last May.
   But there had been no previous mention of the two employees in
the Office of Administration the part of the Executive Office of
the President that provides administrative support to the rest.
   The plan calls for random drug testing of 1,520 of the 1,850
employees in the agencies in the Executive Office of the President,
including the Office of Management and Budget, the National
Security Council, the Council of Economic Advisers, the Council on
Environmental Quality and the Office of the U.S. Trade
Representative.
   The Reagan White House announced last June 30 that everyone on
its payroll would be subject to random drug tests in 60 days. But
that program was held up by court challenges.
   The suit by the employees of the White House complex is one of
more than 50 suits filed by employees throughout the government to
stop drug testing.
   ``These are extremely loyal people, loyal to the president and
loyal to government administration,'' their American Civil
Liberties Union attorney, Jeffrey F. Liss, has said. ``They just
think random drug testing is unconstitutional, not justified, an
invasion of their privacy and demeaning.''
   The Justice Department in its brief cited two recent Supreme
Court decisions _ a 7-2 ruling in favor of testing of railroad
crews after accidents and a 5-4 ruling upholding a Customs Service
policy of testing applicants for law enforcement jobs _ in support
of the plan to test the executive office employees.
   The department also noted that those to be tested already had
willingly allowed extensive background checks in order to get their
sensitive jobs, thus voluntarily limited their right to privacy.
   ``The test involved here detracts little from their already
limited privacy rights,'' the brief says.
   The brief notes that the employees ``are the personal staff of
the president of the United States.''
   ``Just about all of these employees designated for random
testing have access to the president and the White House complex
... or to classified and@or sensitive information or to both,'' it
says.
   Their roles as advisers to the president and participants in the
development of domestic and foreign policies ``make random
urinalysis drug testing for such employees reasonable,'' the brief
says. ``Their regular access to highly sensitive or classified
information makes random drug testing a necessity.''
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said March 29 that
President Bush was displeased by the employees' suit, saying the
government must ensure ``a clean workplace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Hull     04-26 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hull,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>American in Costa Rica Said to Use Ranch for Drug, Arms Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug planes used airstrips on the ranch of
John Hull in Costa Rica while the former Indiana resident helped a
secret U.S. operation to aid the Nicaraguan Contras, witnesses told
a Foreign Relations narcotics subcommittee.
   A Senate committee report on international drug trafficking says
five witnesses identified Hull as a participant in international
drug trafficking. Hull, whose property included airstrips, was
charged in Costa Rica last January with drug trafficking and
violating that nation's neutrality.
   The report said that in addition to his drug activities, Hull
also defrauded the Overseas Private Investment Corp. of $375,000
when he pocketed a loan for a wood products factory that never
produced anything.
   The report, obtained Tuesday from Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass.,
said only one of the five witnesses told the panel he personally
witnessed cocaine being loaded, in Hull's presence, onto planes
headed for the United States.
   The witness was identified as Gary Betzner, a drug smuggling
pilot serving a 27-year prison term for running a continuing
criminal enterprise for trafficking in cocaine.
   Another witness, Werner Lotz, said he heard about drug flights
to Hull's ranch from the Colombian and Panamanian pilots who
allegedly flew the planes.
   Lotz described the strips as refueling stops, and told the
subcommittee, according to the report, that Hull ``was paid'' for
allowing their use.
   Lotz, a Costa Rican, was convicted in the United States for
conspiracy to import drugs in 1985 and sentenced to four years in
prison. He was deported at the conclusion of his sentence to Costa
Rica.
   The report also said Hull and two associates applied for the
OPIC loan in 1983, saying they wanted to finance a ``joint venture
wood products factory that would make wheelbarrow and ax handles
for the U.S. market.'' The money was advanced on March 30, 1984.
   By the end of 1985, after one interest payment, the loan lapsed
into default, and OPIC officials ``began to recognize that the
project was a fraud, and that Hull had made false representations
in making the application to OPIC,'' the report said.
   The agency found, according to the report, that the money was
deposited in Hull's Indiana bank account and the funds withdrawn by
Hull in cash. Hull told OPIC that wanted the cash to buy Costa
Rican money on the black market to get a more favorable exchange
rate.
   ``In fact, Costa Rica has a favorable exchange rate for foreign
investment and the excuse Hull offered does not make sense,'' the
report said. ``What appears to have happened is that Hull simply
took the money, inasmuch as no equipment was purchased for the
factory, no products were shipped from it, and Hull's partner ...
testified that he never saw the money.''
   The Justice Department told the panel there's an ongoing
investigation into the loan.
   OPIC eventually tried to sell the property Hull put up for
collateral, but to prevent a sale far below the market price, OPIC
bought its own property for $187,500.
   Later, OPIC negotiated an agreement with a purchaser, who was
required to make no down payment, and to repay OPIC its $187,500
only from future proceeds of the sale of timber cut on the land.
   Hull was the focus of news reports during the unraveling of the
Iran-Contra affair citing the use of his ranch as a conduit for
arms to Nicaragua. There were also published reports at the time
that he was involved in drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
