<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneDoor-Transcript 1stLd-Writethru a07aminer. 04-26
0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Door-Transcript, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0780,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cockpit Recorder Transcript Released From United Flight 811</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Door Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS throughout flight officer name from ``Mark Thompson''
to ``Mark Thomas'' to reflect change in information from United spokesman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crippled United Airlines flight's crew worried
about staying aloft and boosted each other's spirits during the
harrowing return to Honolulu after their plane ripped open in
flight, according to a cockpit recording transcript released
Tuesday.
   The transcript was released as the National Transportation
Safety Board opened a hearing into why United Flight 811's cargo
door blew off, sucking nine passengers to their deaths and knocking
out two engines.
   Speculation has focused on the failure of a latch to work
properly, although the crew at first thought the damage might have
been caused by a bomb.
   The Federal Aviation Administration released its transcript of
recorded radio conversations between the airplane and the Honolulu
control tower earlier this month. The transcript of the cockpit
recording released Tuesday was the first indication of what crew
members said to each other during the 25-minute return to Honolulu.
   The Boeing 747 departed shortly before 2 a.m. HST on Feb. 24
from Honolulu, bound for Sydney, Australia, with 337 passengers and
18 crew. The flight was uneventful until 2:09 a.m., when pilot
David Cronin said: ``What the (expletive) was that?.''
   ``I don't know,'' replied first officer Al Slader, of Langley,
Va.
   Then there is the sound of a loud bang, and power to the
recording unit was interrupted for 21 seconds. There is the sound
of an alarm horn.
   ``Goin' down,'' Cronin of Incline Village, Nev., said, followed
by ``Emergency descent.''
   ``I think we blew a door ... or something,'' Slader says seconds
later.
   ``Tell the PA _ the, ah, flight attendant to get, ah, prepared
for an evacuation,'' Cronin said.
   The crew shut down the damaged No. 3 engine. Flight engineer
Mark Thomas of Albany, Ind., began dumping fuel as the plane limped
back to Honolulu.
   At 2:13 a.m., Cronin said: ``I think we might have some damage
out there.''
   ``We got a control problem here,'' Cronin said seconds later.
   At 2:14, Cronin noted a problem with the No. 4 engine, and the
crew discussed flying the massive plane on just two engines.
   ``Can you maintain 240 (knots)?'' Slader asked.
   ``Yeah, just barely,'' Cronin replied.
   ``Yeah, but we're losing altitude,'' Slader said.
   ``I know it,'' Cronin said.
   At 2:16, Thomas offered to go into the passenger cabin to check
the situation.
   Seconds later, Cronin announced no fuel flow to No. 4 engine.
   ``What a (expletive) of a thing to happen on your, ah, second to
last month,'' Slader told Cronin.
   ``No (expletive),'' Cronin, then 59 and on his second-to-last
flight, replied. Cronin retired 10 days later on reaching the
mandatory retirement age of 60.
   Immediately after, Slader noted a fire on the No. 4 engine.
   ``Go through the procedure, shut down the engine,'' Cronin said.
   ``We're not gonna be able to hold this altitude on two
(engines),'' Slader said.
   At 2:17, eight minutes after the trouble began, Thomas returned
to report the gaping hole.
   ``The right side is gone ... it's just open. You're just lookin
outside,'' Thomas said.
   ``Looks like a bomb,'' he said.
   ``Fuselage?'' Slader asked.
   ``Yes, fuselage, it's just open,'' Thomas said. ``Some people
are probably gone. I don't know.''
   After a six-second silence, the crew turned back to flying the
plane.
   At 2:19, Cronin told the tower they would ``like all the medical
equipment we can get.''
   Thomas warned against flying too fast because of the gaping
hole, and Slader wondered what the minimum airspeed was under the
circumstances.
   ``I wouldn't go below 240,'' he said.
   ``Is there a closer airport than this?'' Slader asked at 2:22.
   At 2:24, Cronin announced he couldn't hold altitude.
   ``OK don't, OK, ah well, we have 24 miles to go and we're
drifting down slowly ... '' Slader replied.
   ``You're gonna make it,'' Thomas said.
   ``Make sure we don't hit any (expletive) hills on the way,''
Slader added.
   At 2:24, Slader reported seeing the lights of the airport.
   ``OK ... we're 21 miles out and we're in good shape,'' Slader
said.
   At 2:25, Thomas began reading off the checklist for a two-engine
approach.
   ``I hear people screaming back there,'' Thomas said at 2:30.
   At 2:33 the plane's wheel touched the runway.
   At 2:34 a.m., Thomas signaled the evacuation of the plane. The
tape ended seconds later.
</TEXT>
