<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     04-26 0966</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private, USDA Forecasters Disagree on Crop Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's an awkward time for crop and weather
forecasters who remember last year's drought and searing heat.
   Some say it's too early to tell what to expect. Others say it's
later than you think.
   Analysts in the Agriculture Department say the U.S. wheat crop
could be significantly larger than last year's drought-reduced
harvest. And they point out that most of this year's corn hasn't
even been planted yet.
   On the other hand, private economist John Schnittker said
Tuesday that poor moisture reserves in much of the nation's
midsection have already taken a bite out of this year's crop
yields. And it could worsen if the rains aren't abundant this
spring.
   Schnittker, head of Schnittker Associates, a Washington-based
agricultural consulting firm, said that the 1988 drought ``remains
the leading force in world agriculture,'' at least until more is
known about this year's crops of wheat and corn.
   Both Schnittker and the USDA project huge declines in world and
U.S. inventories as a result of last year's drought-shriveled
yields in North America.
   By July 1, he said, the global grain inventory going into the
new 1989-90 season will be down to a 61-day supply, compared with
an 87-day reserve last summer. That will be the smallest reserve
since the early 1970s, when global grain stocks were drawn down to
a 57-day supply.
   Speaking to a meeting of the National Association of
Agricultural Journalists, Schnittker said the supply situation puts
the United States ``sort of on the razor's edge'' because of the
uncertainties about 1989 crop conditions.
   Although many areas are dramatically improved from last summer's
drought, parts of the Great Plains and Corn Belt are still woefully
dry. Even in some areas that have moderate surface moisture, the
reserves deep in the subsoil are scant.
   ``And if we do have a second adverse crop-growing season, the
effect will be substantially larger in the commodities markets and
in the consumer food retail markets than they have been the past
year,'' Schnittker said.
   The reduced 1988 harvests forced up market prices for the major
crops as it became apparent that the U.S. granary would be
partially emptied.
   Schnittker said he finds himself ``disagreeing quite a lot''
with USDA's chief meteorologist, Norton Strommen, who told the farm
writers earlier that he was still optimistic about crop conditions
improving and that nationally the United States can have a
productive year.
   Strommen and others maintain that the fate of the U.S. winter
wheat crop will not be known for another month or so and that
farmers still have not planted spring wheat or made much of a dent
in planting corn.
   ``If I seem a little on the optimistic side, it may be that I'm
looking at changes that have occurred and the improvements that
have taken place since the fall of 1988 and the real harshness of
the 1988 drought,'' Strommen said.
   Acknowledging that there are ``pockets'' of drought problems
still around _ Kansas, for example, where about 75 percent of the
winter wheat is reported in very poor or poor condition _ Strommen
said many other sections of the country have had good moisture last
year in recent months.
   ``When you put all of the big parts together, the overall
outlook for the country is much improved over what it was last
year,'' Strommen said. ``But we are still deeply concerned about
the pockets and the problems we have in the western Great Plains
and the central part of the Corn Belt.''
   Schnittker said that Strommen ``may turn out to be right, but it
seems to me, with the extreme ... subsoil drought concentrated on
the central Corn Belt at the moment, that it is prudent for private
forecasters, at least, to reduce the probable corn yield a little
bit.''
   Already, he said, the moisture problems have shaved this year's
average corn yield somewhat. If all had been normal, the yield
trend pointed to an average of about 120 bushels per acre, but
Schnittker says he thinks 115 bushels are more likely.
   That would mean a 1989 corn harvest of about 7.54 billion
bushels, up from 5.1 billion bushels estimated for 1988. The USDA
currently estimates last year's corn harvest at 4.92 billion
bushels but has not projected the 1989 crop.
   Based on April 25 conditions, Schnittker forecast this year's
total U.S. wheat harvest at 2.15 billion bushels, about 300 million
bushels less than the output would be if moisture conditions had
been normal. Last year's wheat harvest was 1.81 billion bushels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Cox and Steve Painter of the Wichita
(Kan.) Eagle-Beacon are this year's winners of the Glenn Cunningham
Agricultural Journalist of the Year award by the National
Association of Agricultural Journalists.
   Cox, Painter and other contest winners were honored Monday night
at the association's 36th annual dinner at the National Press Club.
The annual meeting concluded on Tuesday.
   Winner in specific categories included: farm news, Cox; column,
Kay Ledbetter, Amarillo (Texas) Globe News; features, Dan Looker,
Des Moines (Iowa) Register; series, Painter and Cox; and special
category, Sonja Hillgren and Juan M. Pedraza, AgWeek, Grand Forks,
N.D.
   Kathleen Davis of the Lubbock (Texas) Avalanche Journal, was
elected president of the association, succeeding Galen Moses,
formerly of the Gainesville (Fla.) Sun, who had resigned.
   Other officers of the association, formerly the Newspaper Farm
Editors of America, include: Lee Egerstrom, St. Paul (Minn.)
Dispatch-Pioneer Press, first vice president; and Audrey
Mackiewicz, Huron, Ohio, executive secretary-treasurer.
   Regional vice presidents named were:
   Southeast _ June Sekoll, Farm Chronicle, Culpeper, Va.
   East _ David Beeder, Omaha (Neb.) World Herald, Washington
bureau.
   Midwest _ Dan Looker, Des Moines Register.
   Southwest _ Kay Ledbetter.
   West _ T.J. Gilles, Great Falls (Mont.) Tribune.
</TEXT>
