<FIRST>r w PM-AirTraffic     04-26 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Traffic,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Calls California Facility `Understaffed Pigpen'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal safety board is trying to stop the
workload from increasing at a major southern California air traffic
control center that officials say already has the reputation of an
``understaffed pigpen.''
   The National Transporation Safety Board, after a special
investigation into nine operational errors at the Coast Radar
Approach Control facility in Santa Ana, raised questions Tuesday
about the center's ability to keep airplanes from flying into each
other.
   ``You've got an understaffed pigpen here, by the FAA's own
evaluation,'' said board member Jim Burnett. He referred to a
statement by former Federal Aviation Administration chief Donald
Engen, who in 1986 visited the Santa Ana center and dubbed it ``the
pigpen of the FAA.''
   The board said controllers at the center regularly work six-day
weeks directing half a million flights a year between Los Angeles
and San Diego. Board staff members said there have been reports of
health problems at the center, with employees taking excessive sick
leave and complaining about working conditions.
   Full staff at the facility would be 66, but the FAA has only
been able to find 24 qualified controllers, primarily because of
the high cost of living in the area.
   The board recommended that the FAA seek to hire local military
personnel and others as assistant controllers so regular
controllers at the facility can receive additional training.
   The board, which met for four hours, said it opposed FAA plans
to expand the center and nearly double the workload unless the
staff can also be at least doubled.
   The board also called for a national task force to develop
changes in procedures at the center.
   An investigation began after a British Airways jumbo jet and a
smaller American Airlines jetliner came within 1.9 miles of each
other at the same altitude on Feb. 13 over Westminster, Calif. The
planes were far enough apart to avoid a ``near miss'' incident, but
FAA rules require aircraft in the area to be separated by at least
three miles horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically.
   The board blamed the incident on a controller who was distracted
by other duties at the facility.
   The inquiry was expanded after investigators found there had
been seven other operational errors in the past year. A ninth
occurred April 6. They also recorded several complaints from
officials and employees at the center.
   The board urged that the FAA give a high priority to
consolidation of air traffic control operations now handled by
separate facilities at Santa Ana, Los Angeles, Burbank and Ontario,
Calif. But board members acknowledged it could take five years or
more to build the new center for which a site has not yet been
selected.
   In another safety matter related to air traffic in Southern
California, the board called for a review of pre-arranged or
``silent coordination'' procedure used by controllers in southern
California and some other areas ``to determine if there is any
degradation of safety.'' The procedure, formerly outlawed by the
FAA, allows controllers to send planes from one control area to
another without orally alerting the controller who is to take over
handling of the plane.
   The board inquiry was its first major investigation into an air
traffic control operation since it began recommending upgrading at
Chicago's O`Hare International Airport after operational errors
increased there in 1986.
   The FAA has started a program to give O'Hare controllers extra
pay, and officials have said they expect the center to be up to
full staff by May.
   The pay program was originally intended to apply to several
facilities where the FAA has had difficulty hiring controllers, but
board members said there are moves in Congress to limit the pay
incentive to Chicago.
</TEXT>
