<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-26 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Rebound Sharply, Dollar Up Slightly In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rebounded
sharply after a setback earlier Wednesday, while the U.S. dollar
edged up against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
438.86 points Tuesday, added another 190.15 points, or 0.57
percent, to finish trading at 33,434.93. The index lost 51.39
points during morning trading, but recovered in the afternoon
session.
   The dollar ended at 131.47 yen, up 0.30 yen from Tuesday's
131.17 yen close. It started at 131.38 yen and fluctuated between
131.30 yen and 131.53 yen.
   Stock dealers said the index began to rise when institutional
investors bought issues following the Nikkei's morning plunge to
pick up cheaper issues.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1.3 billion
shares, up from 800 million on Tuesday.
   The currency rate moved little, mainly due to political
uncertainty stemming from the announcement Tuesday that Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita would resign soon and speculation about
interest rate hikes in Japan, traders said.
   Facing opposition calls for his resignation and public distrust
in his government tainted with a stock-profeteering scandal that
surfaced last summer, Takeshita announced Tuesday that he would
step down as soon as Parliament passes the fiscal 1989 budget.
   Also commenting on a possible move by the central bank to raise
its interest rates, a trader with Bank of Tokyo said; ``It's a
matter of timing.''
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a meeting of bank
branch chiefs the previous day that the central bank would promptly
take appropriate measures if prices become unstable.
</TEXT>
