<FIRST>r a PM-DurenbergerInvestigation     04-26 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durenberger Investigation,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Senator Confirms Investigation By Ethics Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Dave Durenberger says his
investigation by the Senate Ethics Committee concerning a lucrative
book contract is leftover from his re-election bid and will come to
nothing.
   ``The only reason there's an investigation is because in the
middle of my campaign, a bunch of Democratic lawyers decided they
wanted to make an issue out of something that was old news,'' the
Minnesota Republican said. ``And the (Ethics Committee) has to
follow up the investigation.''
   Durenberger confirmed Tuesday that the committee was
investigating a complaint that he ``laundered'' $100,000 in
speaking fees in a deal with Piranha Press for books written under
his name on defense and health issues.
   The deal appeared similar to the one that landed House Speaker
Jim Wright in political hot water, but the Senate investigation has
no connection with the House's queries into allegations against the
Texas Democrat.
   ``Mine was a legal arrangement,'' Durenberger said. ``This
coincides with Jim Wright, so it gets to be a little more news. I
can't imagine that there will be any consequences at all.''
   A group of Minnesota attorneys, many of whom are Democratic
officeholders or party activists, filed a complaint in September
with the Ethics Committee about the book-publishing deal.
Durenberger had abandoned the arrangement more than a year earlier
in the face of criticism.
   The complaint alleges that Durenberger collected about $100,000
in personal income by circumventing the Senate's self-imposed limit
on speaking fees. It alleges he redefined his audiences with
various interest groups as ``promotional appearances'' for the sale
of his books.
   The money from those appearances went to a publisher and then
back to Durenberger.
   Senators are paid $89,500 a year and they can keep up to 40
percent more in speaking fees, or $35,800. For 1987, Durenberger
reported an income range of $147,456 - $163,550 with honoraria of
$50,050, of which $15,350 was given to charity.
   In the Wright case, the House Ethics Committee has voted to
charge the speaker with using his book publishing contract to evade
the limits on outside income. The committee said Wright encouraged
groups to buy his book, ``Reflections of a Public Man,'' instead of
paying him a normal speaking fee.
   Durenberger or his staff members have said the senator cleared
his book-promotion arrangement with the Federal Election
Commission. The complaint alleges that the senator may have
misrepresented the exact nature of the deal to the commission.
   The complaint was filed during Durenberger's campaign to retain
his seat against a bid by Democratic state Attorney General Hubert
H. Humphrey III. Humphrey campaign manager Joe Tessmer acknowledged
in September that the campaign provided information to help the
lawyers group prepare the complaint.
   Durenberger said members of his staff have been interviewed by
the Ethics Committee, and said he expects to meet with the
committee. An official for the committee would not confirm or deny
any investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
