<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Iran     04-26 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Iran,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Says Iran Expelled Or Refused To Re-admit 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office said today that Iran has
expelled or refused to re-admit 18 Britons in apparent retaliation
for Britain's expulsion of 18 Iranians in the dispute over Salman
Rushdie's ``The Satanic Verses.''
   A Foreign Office spokesman said Britain has formally protested
the Iranian move through the Swedish Embassy in Tehran.
   Sweden began looking after British interests in Iran when Iran
broke diplomatic ties with London on March 7 after Britain refused
to ban Rushdie's novel. Moslem clerics say the book blasphemes
Islam.
   Iran's spiritual leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, told
Moslems on Feb. 14 to kill Rushdie for writing the novel.
   Rushdie, an Indian-born British citizen, has been in hiding
since Khomeini's threat, which was backed by the offer of a $5.2
million bounty from two Iranian Moslem clergymen.
   The Foreign Office spokesman, who in accordance with British
practice declined to be named, said Iran's deadline for the Britons
to leave expired Tuesday and some were already back in Britain.
   ``We first heard something was happening on April 19,'' the
spokesman said.
   ``As we understand it, some (of the 18) were people who were in
Britain at the time they were expelled and are simply not being
allowed to return.
   ``They appear to have been a pretty random cross-section of the
Britons who are there. Some of them were long-term residents, some
were businessmen, some were academics _ a whole cross-section.
   ``We have told Iran through the Swedish Embassy that the action
is completely unjustified.''
   He could not say what official reason Iran had given for its
action over the 18 Britons.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government said when it
announced the expulsion of the 18 Iranians that they were perceived
as a security threat. Several of the 18 expelled Iranians were
classified as students in Britain who also worked at the Iranian
Embassy in London.
</TEXT>
