<FIRST>r a PM-KmartExplosion     04-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-K mart Explosion,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim Of Bomb at Indianapolis K mart Undergoes Eye Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors removed the lens of the left eye
from the 5-year-old victim of last week's K mart bombing, but they
refused to speculate on whether she would regain at least partial
vision in the eye.
   Erin Bower remained in satisfactory condition after Tuesday's
two-hour operation at Methodist Hospital, where she has been since
the April 17 bombing at a K mart store. Most of her left hand was
blown off and her eye ripped open when she picked up a pump
toothpaste container and detonated a concealed pipe bomb filled
with gunpowder and BB shot.
   The lens had to be removed to avoid inflammation and further
damage, said John Minturn, an eye specialist who operated on Erin.
The lens is located behind the iris and focuses light toward the
back of the eye.
   The blood that was within the left eye is showing signs of
dispersing, Minturn said.
   ``Still, we'll need time and further healing to decide and see
how much vision she'll recover,'' he added.
   The loss of a lens may require her to wear a corrective lens.
   ``If her eye has some potential vision in it, possibly a contact
lens would correct the loss of the normal lens,'' Minturn said at a
hospital news conference.
   Investigators said Tuesday that a woman who telephoned the K
mart to apologize for the bombing likely was not involved.
   ``The kind of statements she made could really be made by
anybody,'' said Detective Earl K. Cooper of the Marion County
Sheriff's Department.
   Of more than 400 calls received by authorities, Monday's call
was the first confessing to the bombing, investigators said.
   Investigators have concentrated their search on two men seen
leaving the store moments after the blast. One of those men, they
believe, might have bought BB shot at the same K mart three days
before the explosion.
</TEXT>
