<HEAD>Vigils Held For Woman Attacked In Central Park; 2 Suspects Attacked
In Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Runners and neighbors of the teens charged with
beating and raping a jogger in Central Park prayed for the comatose
victim as doctors studied discouraging results of tests on her
brain.
   Prayer vigils were held Tuesday for the 28-year-old investment
banker, who was ambushed by a gang of youths April 19, and a
Department of Correction spokeswoman said two of the eight suspects
had been attacked in jail by other inmates.
   Michael Brisco, 17, reported back and neck pain, and Kharey
Wise, 16, complained of an injured thigh after a fight Monday night
at the Rikers Island adolescent center, said the spokeswoman, Ruby
Ryles.
   She said the incident began in a room where Brisco and Wise were
watching television with other inmates.
   Both were put into a segregated area.
   Tenants of the a middle-income apartment complex where four of
the eight suspects live held a noon prayer vigil Tuesday outside
Metropolitan Hospital, where the victim is a patient.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch convened another vigil at the hospital at
6:30 p.m. where a rabbi, a Catholic priest and an Episcopal priest
offered prayers for the victim's recovery and for an end to
violence and racial discord.
   A crowd of 300 blacks, whites and Hispanics, many holding hands
and with their heads bowed, stood in silence as the clergy spoke.
   About 100 joggers ran from the hospital to the park near 102nd
Street where the attack had taken place. They were joined by
another 100 joggers. After observing a minute of silence, several
runners spoke about safety.
   Dr. Robert S. Kurtz, head of the surgical intensive care unit at
Metropolitan Hospital, said the victim was breathing well on her
own after being taken off a ventilator Tuesday.
   But he said an electroencephalogram showed a ``disorganized
pattern'' of brain waves, indicating ``no coordination between
different parts of the brain.''
   ``As a prognostic sign, this is not very happy,'' he said.
