<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     04-26 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Border Fighting Kills 38</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 38 people were killed and 37
wounded today in fighting between groups involved in black market
activities along the Cambodian border, a Western aid official said.
   ``There was a big ambush on the trading route close to Ta
Phraya,'' said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
``So far we have 38 people dead.''
   He said 37 people were wounded, 10 seriously, in the fighting,
which began about 1 p.m. They were taken to the hospital at the
Khao-I-Dang refugee camp run by the International Committee of the
Red Cross.
   The aid official said the dead included Thais but that most were
Cambodians. He had no other details.
   Ta Phraya district is in the province of Prachinburi in eastern
Thailand and about 50 miles north of the Thai town of Aranyaprathet.
   Black market trading and clashes over it are rife along the
Thai-Cambodian border. The trading involves Thais as well as
Cambodian guerrillas and refugees in guerrilla-run camps along the
frontier.
   Also today, gunners continued attacks on Cambodian refugee camps
in Thailand, hitting the Site 2 camp with heavy shells that
seriously injured four refugees, the Western official said. The
injured were taken to the Khao-I-Dang hospital, he said.
   Site 2, with about 180,000 people, is the largest U.N.-aided
Cambodian refugee camp in Thailand. Its outer perimeter is only a
half-mile from the Cambodian border.
   Site 2 is controlled by guerrillas of the Khmer People's
National Liberation Front. The front is one of three guerrilla
groups fighting Vietnamese forces and troops of the Cambodian
government Vietnam installed after invading 10 years ago.
   It was not clear who fired the shells, which forced evacuation
of all but the most essential Western aid workers. The refugees
were not evacuated.
   In the past, shellings along the border escalated as the two
sides maneuvered in advance of diplomatic events. Cambodian
resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk is to hold talks in
Indonesia next week with Hun Sen, premier of the pro-Vietnamese
government.
   Aid officials said some shells passed over Site 2 on Saturday,
and two rounds landed in the camp Sunday, sending one man to the
camp hospital. A refugee was wounded in shelling there April 15.
</TEXT>
