<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Mauritania-Senegal     04-26 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mauritania-Senegal,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rioting Between Mauritanians and Senegalese Leaves At Least 26 Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Widespread rioting that began over
a land dispute between Mauritania and Senegal has left at least 26
people dead and 675 injured, hospital sources said today.
   The sources said they only knew about casualties taken to the
main public hospital of Nouakchott, the Mauritanian capital.
   Violence also has occurred in Dakar, Senegal's capital, and in
many other cities and towns in the two neighborhing West African
countries. But there has been no reliable word on the number of
casualties outside Nouakchott.
   On Tuesday, Mauritanian officials began airlifting their
countrymen out of Dakar to avoid further violence.
   The hospital sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
they had no breakdown of how many of the dead and injured were
Senegalese and how many Mauritanian. They said 20 of the injured
were in serious condition.
   Violence has been spreading for two weeks since a border
incident set off rising tensions over competing claims by
Senegalese and Mauritanians to farm areas along the Senegal River,
which forms the border between the two nations.
   The streets of Nouakchott were calm today. On Tuesday, police
rushed through the streets of the sand-blown capital of 500,000
people and broke up crowds who roamed the poor quarters and
occasionally surged onto the city's main streets to attack
Senegalese and sometimes wreck or burn shops.
   An 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew remained in effect in Nouakchott and
Nouadihbou, Mauriania's main port.
   In Dakar, 375 miles to the south, Mauritanian Ambassador Mokhtar
Ould Zamal said 100 Mauritanian men and women had been airlifted
out of the city Tuesday.
   Officials at the Mauritanian Consulate, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said thousands more Mauritanians had taken refuge at the
main mosque in Dakar.
   Anti-Mauritanian violence was not quelled in the Senegalese
capital until 4 a.m. Tuesday after the army was called out and
police fired tear gas.
   Both countries have reinforced their troops along the Senegal
River as tensions mounted over the land dispute.
   Both nations have tried to calm tensions since Mauritanian
soldiers allegedly killed two Senegalese farmers in Senegal's
Diawara border village April 9. At least two people have died in
violence in Senegal since then.
   Sporadic violence against Mauritanian shopkeepers in Dakar and
Senegalese in Nouakchott grew into widespread fighting on Sunday.
   Mauritania straddles Arab north and black West Africa.
Two-thirds of its 2 million people are Moors of Arab-Berber
extraction. The rest are black, mostly from the southern river
region. Nearly all of Senegal's 7 million people are black.
   The dispute concerns the right of Senegalese to farm on a
Senegal River island. Even before the colonial period, the black
Toucouleur people farmed both sides of the Senegal River. After
both countries became independent from France in 1960, Senegalese
Toucouleur continued to farm the Mauritanian side they had
considered their own for generations.
   Moors to the north, traditionally nomadic herders, did not farm.
   But the recent completion of two dams on the river has opened up
new farmland and spurred Mauritanian interest in agriculture. All
along the border, Senegalese are being forced off the land.
</TEXT>
