<HEAD>Celebrity-Studded Spago Restaurant Bans Paparazzi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spago has ordered paparazzi who
linger like the smell of owner-chef Wolfgang Puck's designer pizza
to keep off the premises and leave the stars alone.
   The trendy eatery, whose regulars include Joan Collins and
Michael Caine and where super-agent Michael Ovitz has been seen
schmoozing with Kevin Costner, has even banned two photographers
for life.
   Puck has hired two plainclothes guards to keep the paparazzi off
the property, ending a nightly Hollywood ritual in which the
photographers creep ever closer from the sidewalk to snap the
patrons.
   Puck said he will also build a back entrance for camera-shy
patrons.
   All this came after a shoving match two months ago between
Puck's staff and photographers Jim Smeal and Ralph Dominguez, who
were trying to get a shot of Goldie Hawn and her boyfriend, Kurt
Russell.
   ``I hope the photographers don't come at all anymore,'' Puck
said. ``If it was up to me they could all go to (rival) Nicky
Blair's.''
   Which just might happen, say the paparazzi. They predict
celebrities will desert Spago's when they find out they won't be
seen at a see-and-be-seen restaurant.
   ``We can live without Spago,'' said photographer Scott Downie.
``But can Spago live without us?''
