<FIRST>r a PM-FirstElectricity     04-26 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-First Electricity,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>69-Year-Old Gets Electricity In His Home For The First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE TOP, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The isolated mountain home of Jack Blevins
had electricity this morning for the first time in his 69 years,
three months after volunteers began negotiating to get a power
company to bend its rules.
   ``It's somethin,' ain't it?'' Blevins said after the power came
on Tuesday afternoon.
   Blevins lives in a North Carolina mountain cove 200 yards from
the Virginia line.
   The only nearby utility, Appalachian Power Co. in Virginia, has
a policy against selling electricity across state lines. But it
agreed last month to route the sale through a North Carolina
electric cooperative.
   The volunteers who negotiated the arrangement celebrated with
Blevins by crowding into the cabin they had built for him and
switching on all the lights, the donated television and the donated
refrigerator at the same time.
   Caseworkers with the Blue Ridge Opportunity Commission
discovered Blevins last fall living with his now-deceased
73-year-old brother, Tom, in a wooden house with gaps in the walls
large enough to walk through.
   Since there was no road, the volunteers reached the house by
easing vehicles along an abandoned railroad bed and across a series
of rickety trestles high over Big Horse Creek.
   Workmen from Appalachian Power ambled toward the cabin from the
Virginia state line to see if all was working properly.
   Blevins stuck his head out the door and grinned.
   ``Come on in,'' he said. ``The power got here before you did.''
</TEXT>
