<DOCNO> AP890426-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietCancer     04-26 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Cancer,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Begin Cancer Studies With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seeking new cancer treatments and patients willing
to try them, American researchers are turning to the Soviet Union.
   Scientists from the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Md.,
and the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston said Tuesday they
are starting the first joint study of experimental cancer therapies
with Soviet hospitals.
   The study will involve tests of new therapies on several hundred
Soviet and American patients over the next two years, said Dr. Emil
Frei III, director of the Dana-Farber institute.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy said the study marks a resumption of
collaboration in cancer research that began in 1972 but ended when
the Soviet army entered Afghanistan in 1979.
   ``It is one more sign that the Cold War is finally behind us,''
said the Massachusetts Democrat, whose son Edward Jr. was treated
for bone cancer at Dana-Farber.
   American researchers have had difficulty enrolling large numbers
of patients in clinical trials, which sometimes involve placebos
and side effects.
   Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr., a former head of the National Cancer
Institute, said last year that doctors' reluctance to put patients
in drug comparison studies was a ``national disgrace'' that slowed
the search for better treatments.
   Frei said the goal of the collaboration is to share expertise.
   ``We're not using them (the Soviets) in any sense,'' he said.
``They will be the primary beneficiaries of both the technology and
the treatments.''
   Hallie Baron, a spokeswoman for the Dana-Farber institute, said
the project was initiated by the Soviets, who are eager to receive
new technology and drugs from American companies.
   ``What the Soviet side is providing, the advantage of the Soviet
health care system, is that it is very centralized, which allows
them to get just the right patients from all over the country and
bring them to Moscow for these studies,'' said Chris Aho, another
spokeswoman for the institute.
   Kennedy said the study may involve exchanging some patients
between the countries.
   Besides the National Cancer Institute and the Dana-Farber
Institute, the American hospitals participating in the study are
the Jonsson Comprehensive Cancer Center in Los Angeles and Roswell
Park Cancer Center in Buffalo, N.Y.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
