<HEAD>Sen. Gore's Son Leaves the Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 6-year-old son of Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. went home from the hospital in a body cast today, three
weeks after being hit by a car.
   Albert Gore III was wheeled from his room at Johns Hopkins
Children's Center and driven home to Arlington, Va., by his parents.
   He suffered a broken rib, fractures of the thigh bone, a
ruptured spleen, bruised lung and a concussion when he ran into the
path of car after attending the Baltimore Orioles' opening day game
April 3.
   Police said the boy let go of his father's hand and was hit when
he ran out into the street near Memorial Stadium. The driver was
charged with a traffic violation.
   Gore ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1988. He and his wife, Tipper, also have three
daughters.
