<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-EthnicStudy     04-26 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethnic Study,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>University of California Approves Ethnic Study Courses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the University of California
at Berkeley will be required to take ethnic study courses beginning
in 1991.
   Students who packed the upper galleries of an auditorium cheered
Tuesday when the faculty approved 227-194 a resolution requiring
every student take a course on race, culture and ethnicity to earn
a bachelor's degree.
   Such courses must draw from three of five major American
cultural groups: African Americans, American Indians, Asian
Americans, Hispanics and European Americans.
   An important change from the original proposal was the addition
of European Americans, said Valli Israels, student body vice
president of academic affairs.
   ``There were a lot of people, many Jews, for instance, who
didn't like their culture being left out,'' she said.
   Whites make up 48.5 percent of the student body of 22,671
undergraduates. Asians constitute 26.5 percent; Hispanics 11.1
percent, and blacks 7 percent.
   ``California has a lot of cultures. A course like this can do a
lot to bring understanding,'' said Eddie LeRoy, a Latin American
student.
   In 1988 the faculty at Stanford University voted to replace a
Western culture course deemed racist by black students with one
that includes the study of women and minorities.
</TEXT>
