<FIRST>r i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   04-26 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0514,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Warns Radicals To Halt Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 9 grafs to ADD government warning on May Day rally.
Pickup 9th pvs, `In another...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders today urged radical
students and workers to halt their protests and said South Korea
could be plunged into political chaos if they don't. Police clashed
with protesters in two cities.
   The leaders of the three main opposition parties also accused
President Roh Tae-woo's government of fomenting unrest with harsh
crackdowns on opponents and by failing to carry out promised
democratic reforms.
   Kim Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam and Kim Jong-pil, in a statement
aimed at radical students and workers, said: ``We warn against an
expansion of leftist forces trying to overthrow our democratic
system through violent revolution.''
   About 5,000 striking workers clashed with riot police for a
third day in Changwon, about 180 miles south of Seoul.
   Workers hurled firebombs and rocks at police and set fire to
drums of oil to hold back charging troopers.
   In another clash, about 600 radical students shouting ``Down
with Roh Tae-woo!'' hurled hundreds of firebombs at riot police at
Hankook University in Seoul. Police used multiple tear gas
launchers to combat the students.
   Police said there were injuries in both cities, but they gave no
details.
   The government issued a warning today against a major rally that
radical workers and students planned Monday to mark the May Day
holiday. The government said police would block the Seoul rally.
   Organizers vowed to defy the warning and said they expected
100,000 people to attend.
   In another development, student leaders announced plans for a
march Friday to the North Korean border for talks with communist
students on reuniting the divided Korean peninsula. Police issued
orders banning the march and a planned rally Sunday in Seoul by
labor groups.
   The United National Democratic Movement, the nation's main
dissident alliance, said the police actions were an ``illegal abuse
of power'' and vowed to go ahead with demonstrations.
   The students and dissidents lack popular support because of
their violence and extreme views and are not seen as a serious
threat to the government. But government leaders say a wave of
strikes for better pay are damaging the economy and could lead to
serious political unrest.
   The Trade and Industry Ministry said today that strikes this
year had so far cost about $3.5 billion in lost production,
including nearly $900 million in exports.
   Two of the nation's three automakers, Hyundai and Kia, have
virtually halted production because of strikes at companies making
components, according to Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   The opposition leaders, known as the three Kims, said they would
try to form a new opposition alliance and demanded the government
keep its promise to punish former officials of the authoritarian
regime of former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Chun went into rural exile last November after apologizing to
the nation for corruption and rights abuses under his rule, but
opposition parties are demanding top Chun lieutenants also be
prosecuted for wrongdoings.
   The three Kims said Roh must keep an election promise to hold a
referendum. Roh called off such a vote in March, saying it would
divide the nation.
   The three opposition leaders have formed alliances in the past,
but they are deeply divided and have often clashed. The last
opposition alliance collapsed earlier this year in a dispute over
whether the government should hold Roh's promised referendum.
   Roh, a former general, won elections in December 1987 after the
three Kims all ran and split the opposition vote. Roh succeeded his
former ally, Chun, who took power with military backing in 1980.
</TEXT>
