<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 04-26 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede PAGO PAGO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle, Australian Leader Discuss Policy Differences</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 16 grafs with details of Quayle-Hawke meeting; picks up
at pvs 4th graf, ``I have; deletes pvs grafs 9-11,``I have ... week;</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle heard
Australian grievances today about U.S. farm subsidies and told
Prime Minister ob Hawke that he must accept the ``political
reality,'' officials said.
   Quayle launched into talks with Hawke soon after he and his wife
Marilyn is arrival on the first leg of a four-nation tour of the
Pacific and the Far East.
   Australian and U.S. officials, briefing reporters, described the
private 90-minute meeting as particularly warm and said the
overriding theme of the talks was that Australian-U.S. relations
are in ``excellent shape.''
   Quayle is to spend five days in Australia representing President
Bush at this year's celebration of Australian-American Friendship
Week.
   Defense issues had been expected to overshadow the talks
following New Zealand Prime Minister David Lange's announcement
Tuesday that he is considering formally ending his country's
participation in the ANZUS military alliance.
   Instead, bilateral economic issues dominated, with Hawke
complaining about U.S. farm subsidies that he said hurt Australian
wheat exports.
   ``There were lengthy discussions on trade,'' said the sources,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Quayle, according to the officials, explained it was not the
U.S. intention to ``deliberately target Australia'' with its Export
Enhancement Program, which is designed to counter the trade
strategy of the European Economic Community.
   They said Hawke provided the vice president with analytical and
statistical evidence about how Australia was suffering from U.S.
trade policies and that Quayle took note of the concerns.
   While both leaders agreed on the need for free trade, Quayle
told Hawke ``that the U.S. farm bill is a political reality,'' the
sources said.
   Quayle and Hawke agreed that Australian-U.S. relations had
``never been in better shape'' and that Australia remains a
steadfast ally.
   New Zealand's Lange said he viewed the viewed the ANZUS defense
pact as dead because of continuing restrictions in its relations
with the United States, which virtually cut off relations because
of New Zealand's refusal to accept port visits by nuclear-capable
ships.
   But Hawke said it was impossible to view Lange's threat further
because ``at this stage it is only hypothetical,'' one official
reported.
   En route here, Quayle made a two-hour stop in sun-drenched
American Somoa, time enough to convince him he liked it and the
``happy campers'' who live there.
   ``Maybe I'll just stay for a few days,'' Quayle told the
islanders who honored him at a native ceremony and showered him
with gifts. As he spoke, a Samoan beauty queen in a sarong dress
shielded him from the hot sun with an umbrella.
   In exchange for the gracious reception, the vice president
proclaimed Tuesday a public holiday for the roughly 38,000 people
here.
   ``I have the power to declare this a holiday ... you can have
the rest of the day off,'' Quayle told a cheering crowd of about
2,000 gathered under palm trees at Tafuna International Airport.
   Townspeople greeted him with sweet-smelling flower leis and a
brass band.
   Later, Quayle told reporters the holiday had been the idea of
Gov. Peter Colema.
   The relaxation in Pago Pago came in sharp contrast to the
grueling pace Quayle had kept for the previous 32 hours.
   In that time, he delivered a speech in Chicago, met with former
President Ronald Reagan in Los Angeles, attended a security
briefing in Honolulu and played basketball at 3 a.m. at Hickam Air
Force Base there.
   Quayle proclaimed tropical American Samoa ``a delightful change
of pace.''
   ``You all look like happy campers to me,'' said Quayle, the
first vice president to visit the territory since Walter Mondale
came to the outpost 11 years ago. ``Happy campers you are, happy
campers you have been and as far as I'm concerned, happy campers
you will always be.''
   Quayle stressed to the islanders the importance of education as
a way of opening opportunities.
   School children waving miniature American flags lined the narrow
road that brought the Quayles to Nu'uli village, a cluster of
houses with corrugated iron roofs and open sides.
   At a traditional ceremony, the Quayles sat on grass mats under a
thatched-roof lodge belonging to the village chief. The Quayles
were presented with 30 cases of canned wahoo tuna, a decorated mat,
wooden jewelry for Mrs. Quayle, several wooden bowls and a basket
purse.
   The Quayles also were to visit Indonesia, Singapore and
Thailand. After returning to the United States they intended to
tour Alaska's Prince William Sound to monitor cleanup efforts from
the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</TEXT>
