<HEAD>With PM-Scotus-Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Spectators Wait as Much as 19 Hours to Witness Abortion Argument</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 6, Twenty-four people, with arrests.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Brad Schranke of Seattle arrived at the
Supreme Court building to begin his 19-hour wait to witness an
argument on abortion rights, police officers told him he was nine
hours early.
   ``I got here at 3 p.m. yesterday,'' Schranke told a reporter
this morning. ``The police did not start giving out numbers for
courtroom seats until midnight but we arranged our own numbering
system.''
   At midnight, Schranke, a transportation engineering student at
the University of Washington, was given No. 1.
   Today's hour-long argument, scheduled from 10 to 11 a.m. EST,
focuses on abortion regulations in Missouri.
   But state officials and the Bush administration are urging the
court to use the case to reverse or curtail its landmark 1973
ruling that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
   Twenty-four people were arrested in protests outside the court
this morning, a court spokesman said. All were charged with
unlawful entry for crossing police lines, a misdemeanor carrying a
maximum penalty of 60 days in jail and $100 fine.
   Schranke said he opposes the earlier ruling. ``I believe that
God is the creator and man has no right to take a life God has
created,'' he said. ``The baby has to have the choice.''
   Dartmouth College sophomores Clay Fong of Alameda, Calif., and
Jordy Green of South Strafford, Vt., were among the earliest
arrivals.
   Fong described himself as a strong supporter of abortion rights.
``If the constitutional right to abortion were taken away it would
have a devastating impact on the country,'' he said. ``American
individual rights are at a crossroads.''
   Green said he was ``neutral'' on the abortion issue and ``trying
to learn more about it.''
   ``Both sides are very articulate in communicating their views,''
Green said, adding that his 16-hour wait in line had proved an
educational experience.
   Maureen Duffy, a Madison, Wis., lawyer, said she had come to the
court ``just because this is part of history.''
   ``I think that's why a lot of people are here,'' she said. ``To
see the court in action and to witness history in the making.''
   Between 150 and 200 members of the public usually can be seated
in the imposing courtroom on a first-come, first-served basis.
   But because the justices and other court officials had reserved
an usually high number of seats for friends and family members,
only 40 to 50 seats were available for the general public, court
spokeswoman Toni House said.
</TEXT>
