<DOCNO> AP890426-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UMassTakeover     04-26 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UMass Takeover,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Arrested While Protesting Defense Department Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student protest that resulted in 52
arrests will not stop military research at the University of
Massachusetts, the chancellor says.
   Police in riot gear Tuesday arrested 29 students camped inside
Memorial Hall on trespassing charges. Twenty-three others were
arrested for lying in front of the police bus to prevent it from
leaving, authorities said.
   Chancellor Joseph D. Duffey issued a statement telling the
students that Pentagon-funded research will continue on the
25,000-student campus.
   ``The policy will not be negotiated with students,'' he said.
``Until faculty and trustees in deliberate process modify these
policies, they remain policies governing faculty research at the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst.''
   The occupation of the campus building began with about 35
students on Monday afternoon. By Tuesday evening, about 300
students stood outside, the chanting and looking on as the students
inside the hall were arrested.
   Christobal Bonifaz, an attorney for the arrested students, said
they refused to give their names to police, identifying themselves
as either ``John Doe'' or ``Abbie Hoffman.''
   UMass spokeswoman Jeanne Hopkins said about 40 students left the
building Tuesday morning after administrators told them they would
be arrested after 5 p.m.
   Graduate students were told they could face suspension, and any
teaching assistants arrested probably would lose their jobs, she
said.
   The takeover was the second against military research at the
campus in a week. Seven protesters were arrested April 19.
   All research at the university is non-classified and researchers
must make their work public under university rules.
   About $11.6 million, or 22 percent of all grant money received
at the university, came from the Defense Department in 1988,
according to the school.
   The local American Friends Service Committee contends that
Army-funded anthrax bacterial research is dangerous to the town,
which the school disputes.
</TEXT>
