<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0435 04-26 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Gas Well Probe Snags When Investors Balk</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Rep. Myers raising possibility of contempt
citations; picks up at pvs 7th graf, The ethics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senior Republican on the House ethics
committee, angered at being snubbed by key witnesses in the case of
House Speaker Jim Wright, suggested today that the panel might cite
the witnesses for contempt.
   ``There are a lot of options. A contempt citation is one,'' said
Rep. John Myers, R-Ind., who returned to Washington from a
fruitless trip to San Antonio, Texas, with ethics committee
Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif.
   ``We're in good faith trying to do what has to be done,'' Myers
said, relating how he and Dixon had waited Tuesday to interview a
group of five investors in a Texas gas well that yielded little gas
but did produce large profits for Wright's blind trust.
   A half-hour after the group failed to appear, a hotel employee
came to inform the investigators that the witnesses weren't coming.
   ``I don't think that's proper treatment for anyone,'' Myers told
reporters. ``We thought we'd get this behind us. But if they don't
want to cooperate, they can slow us down, and they have.''
   Myers said the ethics committee would meet Thursday to discuss
the status of the case, which has left Wright's position as speaker
in jeopardy. He said failure of the Texas witnesses to appear
raised questions about why they did not want to testify.
   ``Maybe there's something more to that,'' Myers said. ``I think
we have to look at this (with) even more scrutiny. Why didn't they
want to appear?''
   In the capital, Wright's colleagues continued to focus on
charges that he sold bulk quantities of his book, ``Reflections of
a Public Man,'' to evade House limits on outside income. The
speaker said he might consider giving the profits to charity if the
ethics panel suggests it.
   The ethics panel issued its findings in the 10-month
investigation last week, formally charging Wright with 69 instances
of violating House rules. The panel said he had improperly received
$145,000 in gifts from a Fort Worth business partner with a direct
interest in legislation, and had used bulk sales of a book he wrote
to evade limits on outside income.
   The panel is considering whether there is ``clear and
convincing'' proof of the 69 alleged violations and, if so, whether
to recommend disciplinary action to the House.
   The committee left open one area of inquiry _ how Wright's blind
trust profited heavily from a one-day investment last May in the
drilling venture at Sabine Lake, near the Texas-Louisiana line.
Wright's investment partnership with developer George Mallick
invested $9,120 cash in the well on May 10, then sold the interest
later that day for a $340,000 profit even though oil and gas flows
at the time had dwindled. The well later was abandoned.
   The committee is studying ``the amount of profit over a few
hours' time,'' Myers said. ``It doesn't look good.''
   But in a letter to the committee, Washington attorney Stanley M.
Brand argued that the panel was ``overreaching'' in commanding the
testimony of five people he represents: San Antonio financier
Morris Jaffe; his son, M.D. (Doug) Jaffe; investors Jeff Prestridge
and Dave Myers; and Marlyn Cherry, Jaffe's bookkeeper.
   The ethics committee said it wanted to determine whether Wright
knew about the well deal, which involved the Jaffes, a West
German-owned firm and the blind trust established for Wright in
1987, said Richard Phelan, the ethics committee's special outside
counsel.
   Wright contends he was ignorant of the deal because it occurred
within his blind trust.
   Brand, in the letter he released, argued that the drilling
venture was outside the scope of the ethics committee's original
resolution of inquiry voted last June 9.
   ``Serious legal questions are raised by the sheer overbreadth of
these subpoenas,'' Brand wrote, adding that his clients were given
just a week to prepare for their testimony.
   The development threw another procedural roadblock in the way of
the case, which already was bogged down in negotiations between
Wright's lawyer, William Oldaker, and committee counsel Phelan over
conditions for Wright to appear before the panel for a personal
defense.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., told reporters many of her
Democratic colleagues have discussed the advisability of Wright
giving back any profits he made from the book deal, which is the
most troubling charge to many of the speaker's colleagues.
   ``We have all said that we thought that restitution made a lot
of sense,'' she said. Wright could say, `OK, I probably stretched
it too far,' and donate the money to charity without admitting
wrongdoing, she said.
   Asked about the suggestion, Wright said, ``If that's what the
committee wants me to do, of course I'd do it.''
   But he defended the book sales, saying, ``I never consciously
considered that ... buying books was payment for my making a
speech.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
