<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0534 04-26 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0534,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed, 37 Injured In Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with another death; army confirming
10 wounded. Pickup 12th pvs, `The alleged collaborator...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and killed two teen-agers and an
8-year-old boy and wounded 37 other Palestinians today in the
occupied lands, Arab officials said. Palestinians killed a West
Bank Arab accused of collaborating with Israel.
   It was the sixth fatal attack in a week on an alleged
collaborator and came after PLO-backed leaders of the uprising
declared today ``a day of accounting for the collaborators.''
   In clashes with Israeli troops, 8-year-old Issam Omar Aniss was
shot in the chest when soldiers opened fire in the occupied West
Bank's Tulkarem refugee camp, Arab reports said.
   A 20-year-old man was shot in the right arm in the same
incident, and the army clamped a curfew on the camp and the
neighboring town of Tulkarem, the reports said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, 16-year-old Sharif El Khatib was
killed when soldiers shot at stone-throwing youths in the Sabra
neighborhood in Gaza City, Arab reports said. Officials at Ahli
Arab Hospitial said he was shot in the chest.
   Three other youths were reported shot in the head in Sabra,
hospital officials said.
   A 17-year-old girl was reported killed in the Shati camp in Gaza
City. She was identified as Ammal Hussein, and officials at Shifa
Hospital said she died of a gunshot wound to the head.
   An army spokesman confirmed the death of the alleged
collaborator. He said the army was checking the other reported
deaths but was having trouble because in at least two cases,
families immediately took the bodies for burial.
   The deaths brought to 451 the number of Palestinians killed in
the 16-month revolt against Israeli occupation. Eighteen Israelis
have died.
   The army confirmed 10 Palestinians were wounded.
   Arab reports said the 37 people wounded included a 2-year-old
girl who was shot in the head with a plastic bullet during a clash
between soldiers and stone-throwing youths in Gaza City. Four other
Palestinians were shot and wounded in the clash, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The alleged collaborator killed today was identified as Fayek
Erar, 40. Residents of Ras Atiya village said he was gunned down at
his home there because he was accused of helping Israeli
authorities.
   To prevent violence during a general strike today, the army
declared curfews on seven Gaza Strip refugee camps and the Sheik
Radwan neighborhood in Gaza City, ordering more than 200,000
Palestinians to stay in their homes.
   Arab reports said curfews also were imposed on most areas of
Hebron, a West Bank city of 79,000 where clashes have occurred for
the past two days between Palestinians and Jews after Israeli cars
or buses were stoned.
   The strike virtually shut down the Gaza Strip, the West Bank and
the Arab eastern sector of Jerusalem.
   Black smoke could be seen rising over Gaza City as Palestinian
youths blocked roads with burning tires.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, dozens of outlawed
Palestinian flags fluttered from electricity lines, and graffiti
painted in Islamic green across walls and shop doors urged stepping
up the uprising.
   The Moslem fundamentalist group Hamas ordered today's strike in
a leaflet calling for a shutdown of the occupied lands on the
anniversary of the capture of Mecca in Saudi Arabia by the Prophet
Mohammed in 630. Mohammed was born in Mecca, but he fled the city
when local leaders resisted his first preaching of Islam. Moslems
throughout the world say their five daily prayers facing Mecca.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
