<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   04-26 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: more dependency.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 19
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on Lech Walesa's Poland:
   Lech Walesa deserves another Nobel Peace Prize. ...
   By peaceful and dogged persistence, he convinced the communist
government of Poland to recognize the outlawed labor union
Solidarity and to hold free elections. ...
   Will Poland set an example to other communist nations? You bet.
...
   Some governments and citizens _ Hungary's for example _ are
openly enthusiastic and excited about setting out on their own with
more political freedom and human rights for the people and a new
economic engine for the nation. ...
   It's no mystery why the Polish government yielded to Solidarity
and Walesa. It wants to gain economic help from the United States
and other Western nations. ...
   President Bush quickly pledged an economic aid package that may
total $1 billion. ...
   We can follow Walesa's example, and let time take its course. We
can quietly help (Soviet leader Mikhail S.) Gorbachev achieve the
reforms in the Soviet Union and in Eastern Europe that the West has
tried for so long to promote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 19
   Burlington County Times, Willingboro, N.J., on Bush and the oil
spill:
   President Bush has been keeping track of the Alaska oil spill.
But his observations have been from afar.
   Why should he take a presidential yacht into the filthy oil
slick, or an old Navy minesweeper, for that matter?
   It is better, the president figured, to permit the cleanup of
the Prudhoe oil without the distraction of a visit from the head of
state.
   And a visit is all it would have been; regardless of the
opportunity to get some good newsreel footage for the next
campaign, there is very little a clean shaven chap from Washington
can do when that oily ring threatens to creep above the shoe tops.
   Actually, the oil spill will probably be fuel for Bush's
opponent when the re-election effort starts. Remembering the
mileage Bush got from the filth of Boston Harbor, the Democrats
would be remiss if they didn't make reference ... to the
administration's hands-off handling of the spill situation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 22
   The Milwaukee Journal on college freshmen and varsity sports:
   Hunter Rawlings, president of the University of Iowa, has
lighted a fire of controversy by saying college freshmen should not
be allowed to participate in varsity sports.
   We agree.
   Rawlings announced his intention to bar freshman athletes from
playing or even practicing varsity sports if a national ban is not
enacted within three years by the National Collegiate Athletic
Association.
   He acknowledged that sports can tie students to a university,
but added that ``it goes too far when it causes a skewing of
priorities.''
   At Iowa, some athletes have taken ``courses'' in water-color
painting, karate, billiards and bowling. Rawlings realizes that the
main business of a university is intellectual, not physical,
training.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 24
   Enterprise-Journal, McComb, Miss., on sports emphasis:
   The emphasis this country and several others puts on athletics
has gotten out of hand. The pressure to succeed, and the dreams of
multimillion dollar professional and endorsement contracts, is
corrupting amateur sports worldwide and having a detrimental effect
on the U.S. education system. ....
   To gain a competitive edge, players and coaches are willing to
bend or break the rules _ using illegal drugs, passing money under
the table, recruiting juvenile delinquents.
   The school also cooperate, giving preferential treatment to
athletes by holding them to lesser academic standards than the rest
of their student.
   Parents have also gotten in the act of trying to skirt the
system by holding back their children in school so they can have an
advantage. ...
   Sports is an after-school activity. Children are in school to
learn how to read and write, not how to throw a pass. ...
   If parents want their children to succeed, they'd be better
advised to focus their attention on books, not baskets.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
