<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Georgia     04-26 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Georgia,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Proceedings Launched in Use of Tear Gas in Georgia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A criminal investigation has been launched into
the use of tear gas by troops who broke up a pro-independence
demonstration in Soviet Georgia, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
today.
   Nineteen people died in the clash April 9 and another person was
shot and killed for violating a curfew imposed to curb further
demonstrations. At least 1,100 people were injured in the melee in
the Georgian capital of Tbilisi.
   Vadim Perfiliev said at a news briefing that the investigation
is being carried out by the chief military prosecutor. ``Due to the
fact that tear gas was used on demonstrators in Tbilisi, a criminal
case has been opened,'' he said.
   Perfiliev denied anyone died as a direct result of tear gas or
any chemical substance used by soldiers to disperse the
demonstrators.
   ``When autopsies were performed, the reasons for death were not
the use of chemical gas or chemical substances,'' he said.
   This contradicted reports by the Georgian minister of health,
Irakli Managarishvili, who said Tuesday that at least two of the
victims died from gas used by troops. Managarishvili also said
several others died from asphyxiation that may have been induced by
the unidentified substance.
   Officials in Moscow have confirmed only that tear gas was used,
but doctors treating injured protesters said the victims were
suffering a paralysis of the central nervous system caused by an
unidentified chemical substance.
   One of the victims, Gilo Oniani, spoke with foreign
correspondents in Tbilisi on Monday during a trip arranged by the
Foreign Ministry.
   Mrs. Oniani, a 34-year-old factory worker who was sprayed in the
face with an aerosol, told reporters was unable to sleep due to
nervous agitation and unable to eat due to pain in her abdomen.
   Manana Gamsakhurdia, the wife of jailed protest organizer Zviad
Gamsakhurdia, said in a telephone interview today that two men came
to Mrs. Oniani's hospital room late Monday and threatened her for
speaking to reporters.
   Perfiliev said a commission made up of top scientists from
Moscow, Leningrad and other major cities had been formed and would
join in the investigation of the clashes.
   ``There are contradictory versions around the events in
Tbilisi,'' he said, including the question of how many gases were
used.
   ``The experts will be able to make their conclusions, and the
public and representatives of the mass media will be informed of
them as soon as possible,'' Perfiliev said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
