<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Wolf     04-26 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wolf,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Villagers Mourn Loss of Wolf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The villagers of Langa on Wednesday
mourned the loss of one of Sweden's last wolves, which had made
friends with villagers' dogs but pillaged reindeer herds.
   The wolf was killed last week, six months after wandering into
the area displaying an unusual lack of fear of humans. A $1,600
reward was offered for the arrest of the killer.
   Police and the Nature Protection Department refused to say how
the animal was killed while the case was being investigated.
Reindeer herdsmen denied responsibility.
   The killing ended a month of squabbling over the wolf's fate and
whether it should be moved to another area.
   The department said it concluded the wolf would try to go back
to its old hunting territory if it was moved, and attempts to scare
it away with rubber bullets failed.
   The 150 villagers in Langa, 240 miles northwest of Stockholm,
said the wolf had caused them no harm. They said it had played with
their dogs, ignored sheep flocks and at times passed within six
yards of humans.
   The wolf's death left only nine known wolves roaming wild in the
valleys and deep forests of Sweden.
   Hunting regulations allow reindeer herders to shoot a wolf only
if it is caught in the act of attacking their herds.
</TEXT>
