<FIRST>r a AM-BusHeist     04-26 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Heist,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Says He Took Bus On Cruise Because He Wanted To Be Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man who told police he
wanted to be jailed took a bus for a cruise and dropped it off at
police headquarters. He got his wish.
   According to police, Samuel Gallezzo, 23, initially tried to get
arrested by tossing a newspaper vending machine through a window
Saturday night, but officers only gave him a summons for
misdemeanor vandalism.
   Then, police said, he walked into police headquarters early
Sunday and told Sgt. Richard Rogalski: ``I want to be arrested.''
   Rogalski asked why. ``For stealing a bus,'' Gallezzo said.
   ``What bus?'' Rogalski asked.
   ``The one parked out front,'' Gallezzo replied.
   Rogalski found a $175,000 bus belonging to Western Massachusetts
Bus Lines parked at the curb and accommodated Gallezzo.
   But Gallezzo was only briefly a guest of the city. After he
pleaded innocent to larceny of a motor vehicle Monday, he was
released on his own recognizance.
   ``If all he wanted was a night in jail there are easier ways he
could have done it,'' said police Chief David Labato. ``And if he
was looking for a place to sleep, he could have just stayed in the
bus or gone to one of several shelters.''
   Director William Nagle said he let Gallezzo stay at the
Northampton Honor Court, a facility for alcoholics, when Gallezzo
told him last week that he was living in a tent, but asked him to
leave Saturday.
   ``He started some trouble with one of my boys, so I sent him
packing,'' Nagle said.
</TEXT>
