<FIRST>r i AM-MappaMundi     04-26 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mappa Mundi,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investors Said to be Eager to Buy Shares in Medieval Map</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors are lining up to become shareholders in
the Mappa Mundi in a plan to keep the 13th-century map at Hereford
Cathedral, organizers said Wednesday.
   A new company called Mappa Mundi PLC is offering the public
7,450 shares at about $1,700 each to raise more than $12 million to
keep the map at Hereford and pay for repairs to cathedral.
   Hereford Cathedral caused a national uproar when it announced
last year it was auctioning off its medieval treasure, possibly to
foreign buyers, to pay for the much-needed repairs.
   It then had hoped to raise $4.3 million selling the 708-year-old
map, which shows Jerusalem at the center of the world and Hereford
at the edge.
   But the Church of England subsequently joined forces with
financiers to launch the unusual privatization.
   The bishop and the dean of Hereford Cathedral said they have
been inundated with more than 100 applications from as far away as
the Indonesian capital of Jakarta and Israel to buy shares in the
map.
   Bishop of Hereford John Eastaugh said he planned to buy a share
for his wife and that many members of the Friends of Hereford
Cathedral also planned to take up the offer.
   Eastaugh said: ``We are asking people to give a particular sum
and to have an actual share in this great treasure which belongs to
the nation.
   ``I feel very excited. I shall feel relieved when we've got the
money in.''
   The offer opens May 3 for a 42-day period and all shareholders
are to receive reproductions of the map, bearing a seal and signed
by the bishop, and the dean, Peter Haynes.
   The idea was dreamed up by marketing specialist Paul Billingham
who was upset when he read about the planned sale in the
newspapers. He approached financiers, who then put the idea to the
bishop and the dean.
   ``I think they had a tough time and it was a difficult decision
for them to make. We had to explain something to them that was
obviously alien, but I'm glad they've gone this route,'' Billingham
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
