<FIRST>u i PM-SoccerClashes 1stLd-Writethru   04-26 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soccer Clashes, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0562,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Battle Soccer Fans Hurling Bricks, Looting Toy Shop</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with eight arrests, injuries; Fans threatening
to storm stadium. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soccer fans hurled bricks, smashed
store windows and looted a toy store today in unrest that broke out
before the Netherlands-West Germany World Cup qualification match,
police said.
   Dutch fans threatened to storm the stadium unless more tickets
were made available.
   Eights fans were arrested and an undetermined number were
injured in the clashes, which began in the afternoon as fans were
arriving for tonight's match in Rotterdam's Feyenoord stadium, said
police spokesman Ger de Jong.
   Police on horseback and officers in riot gear were called in to
disperse the estimated 500 rioting fans. In one case, a police
helicopter suddenly dived to within about 30 feet above a group of
marauding youngsters.
   Dozens of store windows were smashed, De Jong said. Shopkeepers
lowered steel blinds and boarded up windows in an effort to protect
their property.
   ``It's not really clear to us whether there's a confrontation
going on'' between rival Dutch and West German fans, De Jong told
The Associated Press.
   Most fans in the downtown shopping area, where the rioting took
place, appeared to be Dutch because of their orange scarves. Orange
is the color of the Dutch national team.
   Authorities said the Rotterdam stadium, which holds 57,000
people, was sold out except for 5 percent of the tickets, which
were not being sold to avoid overcrowding. Dutch groups said they
would storm the stadium unless more tickets were sold.
   A stampede at a soccer match April 15 in Sheffield, England,
killed 95 people when fans, some apparently without tickets, rushed
into a standing-room-only section of the stadium.
   Police deployed 600 officers, including 250 riot police, to
quell any disturbances during the match.
   Fans will be subject to rigorous ticket checks and be frisked
before being admitted to the stadium, De Jong said.
   Last year, in the semifinal match of the European soccer
championships, the Dutch national team beat West Germany 2-1. That
event sparked widespread street revelry.
   On Monday, the team of West German coach Franz Beckenbauer was
forced to evacuate its hotel in nearby Wassenaar because of a bomb
threat. No bomb was found. An unidentified person claiming to be a
member of West Germany's Red Army Faction terrorist group made the
threat over the telephone.
</TEXT>
