<FIRST>r a PM-Spearfishing     04-26 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spearfishing,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Crowds Jeer Indian Fishermen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSINEE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters jeered and a scuffle
broke out as Chippewa Indians went spearfishing under treaty rights
held since the 1800s.
   Law officers broke up the scuffle Tuesday night at the Big Eau
Pleine Reservoir, which Indian fishermen had reached by driving 100
miles from their reservation in a 30-vehicle convoy escorted by the
State Patrol. No injuries were reported.
   An estimated 400 protesters also gathered at a boat landing at
Lake Nokomis. Three were arrested, two for disorderly conduct and
one for property damage, said George Meyer, state Department of
Natural Resources administrator of enforcement.
   The protesters object to the Chippewa being allowed to leave
their reservations and spear walleyed pike, muskellunge and other
trophy-sized fish before the rod-and-reel season begins. The
spearing season began Sunday.
   The Indians' treaty rights were upheld in 1983 by a federal
court.
   At the reservoir, on the southern fringe of Indian land deeded
to the United States in the 1800s, 120 protesters carried an effigy
with ``Injun Joe'' on its shirt and held signs that read, ``Spear
an Indian, save a walleye,'' ``Equal rights for all Americans'' and
``Stop treaty abuse.''
   The crowd cheered when someone yelled, ``Let's scalp 'em.''
   Spectators were separated from tribal fishermen on a boat
landing by a police ribbon. Many surged forward after a Chippewa
crossed in their direction in response to taunts.
   About half a dozen uniformed officers moved in and separated the
man from the hecklers. He said he was pushed and shoved but
unharmed.
   ``They taunted me to walk across and I walked across,'' said
David Vallier, 29. ``They were just being pretty mean and
name-calling.''
</TEXT>
