<FIRST>r a AM-Super7-PastWinners     04-26 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super 7-Past Winners,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>$46 Million Lottery Winners Play Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Super 7, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda Despot and Donald Woomer are big, big
fans of the Pennsylvania lottery. They bet $100 would get them the
$100 million jackpot in Wednesday's drawing to add to the $46
million they won two years ago.
   ``We want to be part of the action,'' said Woomer, 57, of
Hollidaysburg.
   ``We don't want to be left out,'' said Despot, 38. ``You get
caught up in the excitement of it, so you want to be a part of it.
It's fun.''
   As long as they don't win, that is.
   ``If we win, that's a different story,'' she said.
   ``Nobody would want to play anymore if we won again,'' he said.
   On Oct. 19, 1987, Woomer and Despot claimed a $46 million
jackpot, which was, at the time, the biggest prize in U.S. history.
   The couple, who have been living together for seven years, quit
their jobs, bought a few things _ cars, a farm, a horse _ and threw
a party with fireworks for their central Pennsylvania town on the
first anniversary of their win.
   But for the most part, Despot and Woomer are spending money as
if they've won thousands, not millions. And they say that's the way
it's going to stay.
   ``They say lotteries are the stuff dreams are made of, and
that's what it is if you don't let it get ahead of you,'' Despot
said in a telephone interview Tuesday night.
   ``Money gives you security so that you don't sit and worry about
your bills. But you still have problems. It's not the answer to
everything. It can't buy you your health. If we get sick, we're
sick like everybody else,'' he said.
   Woomer was a self-employed plasterer and Despot a $13,000-a-year
bookkeeper for a car dealership when Woomer's $25 investment in
lottery tickets won them $46 million in the Super 7 game.
   They quit their jobs and now live on annual installments of $1.4
million, with 20 percent deducted for federal taxes. The payments
are spread over 26 years.
   After 18 months, the millionaire lifestyle is slowly catching on.
   They still live in the same two-story, red-brick house in a
development overlooking a section of Hollidaysburg, a town of
6,000. They plan to build a new home soon. Despot's 15-year-old
daughter, Heather, still attends the public high school, and their
neighbors still take care of their goldfish when they're out of
town.
   ``Most people said we haven't changed,'' Woomer said. ``We're
still ourselves, and this is the way we want to stay. This is our
home town, and we decided this is where we want to live.''
   For the first year, unsolicited requests for money came from
every state and dozens of countries. Despot said she reads all the
letters but rarely answers and never sends money.
   ``After so many of those letters, they all sound alike, and you
don't know which are legitimate or not. We can't start it. We can't
save the world,'' she said. ``We'll know if we're to help somebody.
It will happen. I'm not looking, but it will happen.''
</TEXT>
