<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SmokingCampaign     04-26 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking Campaign,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campaign Seeks to Get Physicians to Help Patients Quit Smoking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop on Wednesday
joined the National Cancer Institute and the American Cancer
Society in a campaign to get physicians to help their patients quit
smoking.
   They have put together a brochure outlining basic steps doctors
should take to make smoking advice part of standard medical
practice, and they're sending the pamphlet to 100,000 primary-care
physicians.
   ``Seventy percent of Americans see their doctors at least once a
year,'' Koop said. ``If doctors can get across to their patients
some self-rewarding goal for stopping smoking, I believe the
problem can be nearly licked.''
   About 48 million, or 29 percent, of American adults smoke, and
one in every six deaths in the United States is attributed to the
effects of smoking, according to public health officials.
   The surgeon general, the country's most outspoken public health
official in the fight against smoking, said new clinical trials
conducted by the National Cancer Institute ``show that smokers
whose doctors help them quit are up to six times more likely than
other smokers to kick the habit for good.''
   However, many physicians are reluctant to counsel their patients
on smoking because they are uncomfortable with the subject, don't
believe they can help and feel they are intruding on a patient's
privacy, he said.
   By giving doctors the information they need to help patients
quit and offering training sessions for physicians, Koop believes
doctors will join the campaign and actively work to help their
patients stop smoking.
   ``If only 10 percent of physicians routinely advised smokers to
quit, and succeeded with only one in 20 patients, more than a
million smokers would quit each year'' in addition to the million
or so who already quit annually, said Joseph W. Cullen, deputy
director of the division of cancer prevention and control at the
National Cancer Institute.
   The four-step guidelines, developed by the institute and the
cancer society on the basis of clinical trials, advise physicians
to ask patients about their smoking habits and advise each smoker
to quit.
   Then, doctors are asked to help patients willing to try to quit
by setting a quit date, giving the patient self-help material and
prescribing nicotine gum if needed for heavier smokers. Finally,
they should arrange for follow-up support, including phone calls or
office visits.
   The booklet also advises physicians on how to help patients
manage weight gain and other withdrawal symptoms.
   Nearly half of all American adults who have ever smoked have
stopped, Koop said, noting that physicians have been leading the
way, as less than 10 percent of them smoke.
   ``Now it's time for doctors to act in another way _ to preach
what they practice,'' Koop said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     04-26 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam to Hand Over 21 Sets of Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam on Thursday will return 21 sets
of remains that it believes may be the remains of Americans missing
from the Vietnam War.
   A U.S. military team is to pick up the remains in a ceremony at
Hanoi airport, then fly them to army laboratories in Honolulu for
analysis and identification.
   More than 1,700 Americans are listed as missing in action in
Vietnam while others are missing in Cambodia, Laos and China. The
war ended in April 1975 with a communist victory over the
U.S.-backed South Vietnam government.
   Vietnam has returned large numbers of remains since August 1987,
when it agreed to accelerate cooperation on the issue in exchange
for Washington's help in encouraging private humanitarian aid to
Vietnam.
   Ten U.S. military specialists have been in Vietnam since April
12, working with Vietnamese counterparts in the fifth joint field
investigation on MIAs. They are interviewing villagers who
witnessed plane crashes and seeking other evidence of the missing
men.
   The investigators will work until April 30 in the longest such
project thus far.
   Progress on the MIA and other humanitarian issues between the
United States and Vietnam has been hampered by the lack of
diplomatic relations, blocked by Washington's opposition to Hanoi's
military occupation of Cambodia. Vietnam has announced it will
withdraw all its troops by Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
