<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WineSuit     04-26 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wine Suit,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vineyard to Pay Anheuser-Busch $1.1 Million for Grape Switch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vineyard accused of trying to squeeze too
much profit from Anheuser-Busch by passing off wine made from
cheaper grapes instead of zinfandel has agreed to pay the alcohol
company nearly $1.1 million.
   The settlement, made last month and disclosed in court documents
Tuesday, involved a lawsuit filed in federal court earlier this
year.
   The suit said Anheuser-Busch had contracted to buy 900 tons of
100 percent zinfandel grapes from Bavaro Brothers, a grower in the
San Joaquin Valley town of Escalon. The grapes were to be sent to
Verdugo Vineyards in Acampo for processing into white zinfadel wine.
   But a government inspection found some of the wine delivered to
Master Cellars, an Anheuser-Busch division, was made from as little
as 22.9 percent zinfandel juice. That meant the wine, by law, could
not be sold as white zinfandel.
   ``Instead of having a value of $1 million, it's worth barely
$197,359,'' the suit said.
   Under the agreement approved by U.S. District Judge A. Wallace
Tashima, Bavaro agreed to pay Anheuser-Busch nearly $1.1 million.
In return, Bavaro can try to sell the thousands of gallons of wine
and apply the money to the settlement.
   A ton of zinfandel grapes can sell for $950, compared to $150
for, say, chenin blanc, according to the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
