<HEAD>House Panel Begins Amending Bush S&amp;L Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, After the, to CORRECT name of bank to Frost National
Bank of San Antonio.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee today prayed for
divine guidance to rise above ``narrow self-interest'' as it began
work on savings and loan legislation, and then immediately adopted
a provision designed to favor the hometown bank of a powerful
lawmaker.
   Other amendments to help out two of the nation's largest bank
holding companies _ First Interstate of California and Chemical
Bank of New York _ swiftly followed.
   The votes came as the panel debated legislation recommended by
the Bush administration to bail out the savings and loan industry,
and the thorny issue of what type of capital requirements should be
imposed on S&amp;Ls.
   Both the administration and the two party leaders on the
committee now want to make S&amp;L owners put up $2.25 of their own
money as ``tangible'' capital for every $100 they lend.
   ``If we adopt weak standards _ and allow the kitchen sink to
count as capital _ we are voting to shift the burden to the
taxpayers,'' committee Chairman Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, said in an
opening statement.
   However, Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the panel's
financial institutions subcommittee, said the new standards will
drive healthy, honest S&amp;L operators out of business and precipitate
the need for another taxpayer-financed bailout in the future.
   ``Instead of going in and removing the crooks, we are choosing
to launch a poison gas attack on the industry and adopting the
philosophy of `kill 'em all,''' Annunzio said.
   The unusual opening prayer was offered by Del. Walter Fauntroy,
D-D.C., a Baptist minister, who said that in his 19 years in
Congress he had never felt such a need for divine guidance before.
   After the prayer, the committee approved, 37-11, an amendment
that Gonzalez said was intended to protect from a liability
provision only the Frost National Bank of San Antonio, his hometown.
   Annunzio, who favors less-stringent S&amp;L capital standards than
the administration now wants, led the opposition. ``Your amendement
comes at a bad time,'' he told Gonzalez. ``Everyone is asking for
private legislation.''
   Immediately afterwards, the committee approved an amendment by
Reps. Elizabeth Patterson, D-S.C., Thomas Carper, D-Del., and Steve
Bartlett, R-Texas, exempting First Interstate and Chemical Bank
from financial liability in their acquisition of two institutions
in Texas.
   Both amendments were unopposed by the administration. Several
more calling for similar exemptions were on the committee's
schedule.
   Gonzalez said his, Wylie's and the administration's new desire
for stricter capital standards than first sought are ``the guts of
this whole issue.''
   Anything less, he said, will ``simply mean that we let the
industry, once again, roll the dice with taxpayers' money.''
   However, S&amp;L supporters and even some of the industry's harshest
critics in the past expressed fears that a new demand for a cash
equity infusion that large and that quickly _ by June 1991 _ will
drive 800 to 1,200 of the nation's 2,950 remaining thrifts out of
business.
   ``The Bush administration wants to come in and practice
euthanasia on institutions that are not in trouble,'' complained
Rep. John J. LaFalce, D-N.Y., a past critic of S&amp;L practices.
``These immediate and precipitous demands are going to create a
bank panic that will bring 10 times as much trouble as we need.''
   LaFalce said Bush's initial $90 billion bailout proposal was
built on the premise that roughly 500 S&amp;Ls would fail the capital
test he first sought, instead of the 800 to 1,200 that would be
unable to meet the proposed new $2.25 ``tangible'' standard.
   ``If we drive institutions unnecessarily into insolvency, it is
the American taxpayer who will bear the increased cost _ a far
greater cost than anyone is presently contemplating,'' he said.
   Congressional sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
estimated the cost to the government of liquidating S&amp;Ls that fail
to meet the proposed new ``tangible'' capital standard at $130
billion _ twice what Bush's initial proposal and a Senate-approved
version would cost.
   Bush's initial proposal unveiled in February called for doubling
the capital required of S&amp;Ls from the current 3 percent to 6
percent. But none of that capital under his proposal had to be
``tangible'' _ in the form of stock or retained earnings easily
convertible to cash.
   Theoretically, an S&amp;L could remain in business with no direct
equity investment by its owners under Bush's initial legislative
initiative.
   The House Banking Committee's financial institutions
subcommittee two weeks ago imposed a 1.5 percent ``tangible''
capital requirement, as did the Senate last week.
   Both of those actions were praised by administration officials,
who then decided late last week that even more ``tangible'' capital
should be required, according to congressional and administration
sources.
   Among the 2,700 technically solvent S&amp;Ls at the end of the year,
only about half of their $60 billion in capital was ``tangible.''
   The rest _ $21 billion in so-called ``supervisory good will,''
$4 billion in subordinated debt and $3 billion in deferred loan
losses _ is all the result of what critics call ``smoke and
mirrors'' accounting practices.
   That ``phantom capital'' accounting was greatly expanded by
Congress and the Reagan administration in the early 1980s to
encourage healthy S&amp;Ls to take over sick ones as a way of avoiding
payouts from the federal deposit insurance fund, which is insolvent
itself.
</TEXT>
