<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Clamscam Bjt   04-26 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clamscam, Bjt,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big, Ugly Clam Is Center of Big, Ugly Court Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor calls it the biggest white-collar
crime case in state history, with the main trial expected to last
three months and charges pending in several counties _ and it all
concerns a clam.
   Not just any clam. This is about the world's second-largest
species of clam, a long-necked ugly thing called a geoduck,
pronounced gooey-duck, after an Indian word for ``dig deep.''
   With about 135 workers, Washington's geoduck industry in 1987
generated $1.8 million for the state, which leases tracts for
harvesting in Puget Sound, Hood Canal and other inland marine
waters. State officials said they had no figures on the commercial
value of the harvest.
   At an auction this spring, four of 12 bidders won rights to
seven tracts covering 300 acres at a record average price of 68
cents a pound, said James McKillip of the state Department of
Fisheries. Depending on the catch, the state could realize $1.9
million to $3.5 million, said Bob Hoyser, a state Department of
Natural Resources leasing manager.
   But booming demand also generated ``Clamscam,'' a complex
criminal case against seven people and eight corporations and a
``criminal profiteering'' civil suit against most of the same
parties and a few others.
   The defendants are accused of overharvesting and taking geoducks
from outside their leased tracts since 1970.
   The clams are found along the West Coast from British Columbia
to Southern California and weigh as much as 10 pounds.
   Washington and neighboring British Columbia have the only
noteworthy geoduck industries, with average known harvests of 4.6
million pounds in Washington and 10 million pounds in British
Columbia between 1980 and 1985, said McKillip.
   In the United States geoduck is frequently used in canned and
fast-food chowder and occasionally as an entree in restaurants.
   ``It's got kind of a sweet taste. You can tell'' when it's used
in chowder, said McKillip.
   The succulent flesh also is a sushi superstar and top-quality
live geoducks sell for as much as $12 a pound in Japan.
   But the monster mollusks look, well, odd, with a sinuous brown
neck or siphon that extends from several inches to a few feet out
of a shell six inches or longer, producing disgust, disdain and
occasional titters at seafood stands.
   ``Would you promise me one thing? Please don't call me the
geoduck queen,'' pleaded King County deputy prosecutor Marilyn B.
Brenneman in a telephone interview last week. ``This is the kind of
case that could follow me the rest of my life.''
   Brian D. Hodgson, 50, of Olympia; Carol K. Kondo, 58, of Federal
Way, and Mark E. Pearce, 37, of Olympia, each could face life in
prison if convicted of leading organized crime. Four others,
including Kondo's daughter, Cindy Rommel, face lesser felony
charges.
   As top officers, suppliers and associates of the now-defunct
Washington King Clam Inc. of Fife and related companies, they are
accused of illegally taking more than 1 million pounds of geoducks
worth at least $1.8 million.
   Brenneman called it ``the largest state white-collar crime case
ever tried in Washington courts.''
   Two of the nine people initially charged in the criminal case
have pleaded guilty to reduced charges and agreed to testify for
the state.
   Hodgson, Kondo, Pearce, Rommel and another criminal defendant
also are among those being sued by the state for treble damages, an
amount that could exceed $3 million.
   Brenneman predicted the King County criminal trial will last at
least three months with testimony from 130 to 150 of the 180
potential witnesses she has listed. She also planned to present
1,000 to 2,000 of the 70,000 bank records, shipping receipts and
other documents identified as potential evidence.
   Jury selection began last week and was expected to run at least
through late this week, court officials said.
   Charges involving other areas of Puget Sound and Hood Canal are
pending in Kitsap, Mason, Jefferson and Pierce counties.
   Washington King Clam, formed in 1970 by Hodgson with Kondo
holding a minority interest, led in developing the export trade and
in recent years controlled 90 percent of the state's geoduck
industry, McKillip said.
   Documents filed by Prosecutor Norm Maleng said about 40 former
Washington King Clam employees or business associates told of
illegal harvesting of the brobdingnagian bivalves since the company
was formed.
   Dan Donohoe of the prosecutor's office said the 20-month
investigation unearthed a pattern of crimes that began as far back
as 1970 and continued over the years, with the most recent incident
last October.
   With the filing of charges last fall, the state canceled five
leases to Geoduck Harvest, by then owned by a Japanese company, and
principals in the case were banished from further bidding.
</TEXT>
