<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Rain     04-26 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Rain,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Gets Rain After Residents Offer Prayers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in parts of Bangladesh on
Wednesday after people across the country prayed for an end to a
drought that threatens to destroy almost 50 percent of the rice
crop.
   Hours after the prayer by more than 75,000 Moslems led by
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, it rained in the capital of
Dhaka and three other districts, the weather bureau said.
   The rain, .16 inches to .96 inches, was not enough to ease
drought conditions, but it was a welcome relief.
   Religious Affairs Minister Nizamuddin Al Azad said people knelt
in mosques, temples, churches and pagodas across the nation to pray
for rain. Thousands more could not attend the ceremonies because of
traffic jams.
   About 26 of the country's 63 administrative districts have been
suffering by a lack of rainfall. Agriculture is the main occupation
of most of the country's 110 million people.
   Some areas have irrigation channels and pumps but most of the
canals ran dry when subterranean ground water levels plunged, news
reports said.
   Bangladesh, one of the world's poorest countries with a per
capita annual income of $160, alternates between flood and drought.
Last summer, more than 1,400 people died in floods that submerged
four-fifths of the low-lying nation.
   Bangladesh produces about 17 million tons of grains a year. The
target of the spring rice crop _ which has been affected this year
by the drought _ was 5.6 million tons.
   In addition, Bangladesh imports about 2 million tons of grains a
year to meet the shortfall of 1.5 million tons in production and
build a reserve.
   The drought and the hot weather has also threatened operations
at the country's lone hydroelectric power plant near the southern
port city of Chittagong, about 120 miles southeast of Dhaka. The
project was set up in the mid-1960s by the United States.
   Weather forecasters say there will be no respite from the
drought for another two weeks, and a hot spell will aggravate the
situation in the coming days.
   An Agriculture Ministry official said nearly half the crop would
be destroyed if the drought persisted a few more days.
   ``I fear the crop loss may be 50 percent of the total. No rains
in the next few days may spell disaster for agriculture,'' the
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A senior government official said Monday the government had
sufficient grain reserves to prevent people from starving.
   ``The government is determined that no one will die for want of
food,'' said Relief Minister Sirajul Hussain Khan.
</TEXT>
