<FIRST>r w AM-GasolineTax     04-26 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gasoline Tax,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Use Higher Gas Taxes to Cut Deficit, Say City and County Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the nation's cities and
counties pleaded with Congress Wednesday not to use higher gasoline
taxes to reduce the federal deficit.
   ``The federal gasoline tax has been used to construct a fine
highway system in this country and it should only continue to be
used to improve and enhance this system,'' James J. Snyder,
president of the National Association of Counties and a Cattaraugus
County, N.Y., legislator, told a news conference.
   ``The U.S. Department of Transportation estimates that between
$261 billion and $314 billion in capital investment is needed just
to maintain the nation's urban road network at 1985 levels,'' said
Irving Mager, an Annapolis, Md., alderman speaking for the National
League of Cities.
   ``We must not let a serious problem grow into a calamity by
diverting the funding source that is intended for our vital
transportation needs,'' Mager said.
   Some key members of Congress advocate a hefty increase in the
9.1-cent-a-gallon tax to bring down the budget deficit. The levy
now is earmarked for transportation.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, speaks often in favor of such an increase,
although President Bush has specifically listed a gasoline tax as
one he opposes.
   City and county officials spoke at a news conference sponsored
by The Road Information Program, which is financed by the highway,
energy and insurance industries.
   William M. Wilkins, executive director of the organization, said
a 50-cent increase in the tax would reduce federal, state and local
spending for roads and bridges by more than $28 billion over the
next 10 years.
</TEXT>
