<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PowerMerger     04-26 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Power Merger,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Considering Deal to Create Nation's Biggest Utility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators on Wednesday took a first
step in considering whether to approve a merger of Southern
California Edison and San Diego Gas &amp; Electric, a hotly contested
deal that would create the nation's largest private utility.
   The case has broad implications for the electric power industry,
including a possible impact on legal and political clashes over
utilities' use of their monopolistic powers.
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission voted to send the
proposed California merger to an administrative law judge for
hearings on a limited number of issues. The judge would then
recommend a final action by the commission.
   Last week, stockholders of the two utilities approved the deal,
under which Southern California Edison's parent company, SCEcorp,
based in Rosemead, would acquire San Diego Gas &amp; Electric in a
stock swap valued at about $2.56 billion. The surviving company
would be controlled by SCEcorp.
   The deal requires approval by a variety of regulatory agencies,
including the California Public Utilities Commission and the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
   The San Diego utility serves 1 million customers in San Diego
County and parts of Orange County. Southern California Edison has
3.8 million customers in central and southern California.
   The two utilities have pledged to cut power rates for San Diego
commercial, industrial and agricultural customers by 5 percent, and
to make a 10 percent reduction in rates for residential customers.
This would mean a savings to customers over the next decade of $1.7
billion, the companies have said.
   San Diego and several other California cities, as well as the
state attorney general and some utility industry associations are
opposed to the proposed merger on a variety of grounds, mainly that
it would dimnish competition.
   The city of San Diego has raised especially strong objections.
It has accused Southern California Edison of coercing the San Diego
utility into agreeing to the merger.
   A legal petition by the city includes depositions from two
former members of the San Diego Gas &amp; Electric board of directors
who testified under oath that Southern California Edison
``inflicted transmission access problems'' on its merger target.
The city claims this was done to pressure San Diego Gas &amp; Electric
to agree.
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission earlier said there was
not enough evidence of coercion to formally consider the matter,
but in its order Wednesday the commission said it would allow the
city of San Diego to present more information.
   In its order to the administrative law judge, the commission
rejected a request by a group of California cities, including
Riverside and Anaheim, to deny the merger before holding hearings.
The cities contend the merger is anti-competitive.
   The federal order also rejected a request by the city of San
Diego that the merger's possible environmental implications be made
part of the review process.
   The commission said that based on currently available
information, the proposed merger raised no issues that would
require an environmental impact statement. It added, however, that
it might reconsider the matter if new evidence arose later in the
merger review.
   Among the issues to be considered at the administrative law
hearing are the probable effects of the merger on utility rates and
the expected benefits of integrating the two merging companies'
electrical generation and transmission systems.
   No date was set for the hearings. The companies' merger
agreement of last year sets a deadline of March 31, 1990, for
gaining final regulatory approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
