<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     04-26 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ninth Murder Victim Found Along Massachusetts Highway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from a killer apparently stalking
prostitutes and drug users rose to nine Wednesday as investigators
tentatively identified another body left along a southeastern
Massachusetts highway.
   Authorities said an autopsy on the ninth victim, found Monday
along Interstate 195 in Marion, yielded a preliminary
identification. But they declined to release the name pending
confirmation with dental records.
   Police said the position of the body and other details matched
those of the previous eight victims, all women ages 25 to 36 who
lived in or near the seaport of New Bedford.
   But investigators declined to make the details public, citing a
rash of false confessions.
   ``We have people who have come in here and confessed to these
crimes, but we ask them, `How did you do it? What transpired? How
did you leave the women?' and the information they give is just
very wrong,'' said Jim Martin, a spokesman for the Bristol County
district attorney's office.
   Accounts by a highway worker and others who found the bodies
have led to speculation that the women have been strangled with
their clothing and left face down, or in fetal positions. But
almost any conversation on a New Bedford street is likely to yield
a new theory.
   None of the murders appears to be recent. Forensic experts said
the bodies, all found since July, had been lying along the highways
for months.
   Despite the decomposed state of the bodies, investigators have
been able to identify all of the previous eight as drug users or
prostitutes.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald A. Pina has said he has
several suspects, and a grand jury has been hearing evidence for
months, but no indictments have been issued.
</TEXT>
