<FIRST>r a AM-Saroyan'sAshes     04-26 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saroyan's Ashes,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Over Where to Inter Rest of Author's Ashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's the kind of story William Saroyan
might have written, if he were still alive.
   The plot:
   What to do with the ashes of the late author, that is to say the
half of his ashes that weren't sent to Soviet Armenia after he died
in 1981 at age 72.
   The characters in this ``Human Comedy,'' to borrow the title of
Saroyan's most popular novel:
   _ Friends who want his remaining ashes interred in the local
Armenian cemetery topped by a monument fitting for Fresno's famous
native son.
   _ The William Saroyan Foundation, which isn't certain what
should be done with Saroyan's ashes.
   _ Newspaper columnist Eli Setencich who is having the time of
his life writing about Saroyan's ashes.
   It was Setencich who started the fuss by writing in his Fresno
Bee column last week that half of Saroyan's ashes still were
sitting on a shelf in a local mortuary, and some folks were
thinking of putting them in Ararat Cemetery.
   An Associated Press story about Setencich's musings drew the
attention of Robert Setrakian, president of the William Saroyan
Foundation in San Francisco, which was one of the places Saroyan
spent time when he wasn't in Fresno or Paris.
   Setrakian wrote a letter to Ben Amirkhanian, one of the Fresno
folks who favors a move to the cemetery for Saroyan's ashes, which
are encased in an urn carrying an inscription that calls Saroyan an
``author and humanitarian.''
   ``Frankly, I find this whole article disturbing what with the
apparent cavalier approach by some of Mr. Saroyan's friends, as
well intentioned as they may be,'' Setrakian wrote.
   The letter pointed out that Saroyan directed that upon his death
he be cremated and half of his ashes be taken ``to an appropriate
location in Armenia.''
   The directive quoted by Setrakian makes no mention of any
desired final resting place for the other half of his ashes,
whether on a shelf or wherever.
   Setrakian insisted, however, that the foundation has legal
control of the ashes. He said trustees would consult with Saroyan's
sister, Cosette Saroyan, about her wishes.
   Amirkhanian said Tuesday Saroyan's sister ``thought it was a
wonderful idea'' to build a monument at the cemetery, and he would
work with the foundation in an attempt to locate the ashes there.
   Setencich concluded on Wednesday that Saroyan probably is up
there somewhere enjoying the squabble over his ashes and ``writing
a neat story about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Palestinians     04-26 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Palestinians,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Reject Shamir Election Call, Demand World Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 80 influential Palestinians in the
occupied territories Wednesday turned down Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's plan for elections leading to an interim solution to the
Palestinian-Israeli conflict.
   In their first formal response to the Shamir proposal, the
Palestinian leaders said no elections could be held while Israel
maintained forces in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   They derided the Shamir plan as a stalling tactic aimed at
ending the 16-month-old Palestinian uprising and called for
``negotiations with the PLO within the framework of an
international conference until the establishment of a Palestinian
state.'' Many of the statement's signers are pro-PLO figures.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections to select Palestinians from
the occupied territories to hold talks with Israel on an interim
solution for the troubled region. After two years, discussions
would begin toward a permanent solution.
   Shamir rules out any participation by the PLO, which Israel
considers a terrorist organization, and says there never will be an
independent Palestinian state in the territories.
   The plan, outlined by Shamir during a visit to Washington
earlier this month, won the cautious approval of President Bush.
But the Soviet Union and major Arab states, such as Egypt and
Jordan, have said they favor an international conference under U.N.
auspices.
   Shamir's top spokesmen could not be reached for comment because
of the Passover holiday.
   Alon Liel, Foreign Ministry spokesman, said: ``I realize the
difficulty the Palestinians are having with the fact that Shamir is
speaking about an interim agreement and is not indicating anything
about the final status.'' But he said that Israelis fear the gap
between the two sides is too great to bridge without a phased
approach.
   ``I want to stress that the Israeli thinking is if we start from
the end, we won't have a beginning,'' Liel said. ``This is the idea
behind the step-by-step approach that was accepted by the
Americans.''
   The Palestinians' statement, issued in Arab and English,
described the Shamir plan as ``calculated to appeal to the media,
to end the uprising and to win time.'' It insisted that the PLO is
``the sole legitimate representative of the Palestinian people''
and that any election plan that excluded the PLO was ``an attempt
to divide our people into `inside' and `outside' Palestinians.''
   The statement did not rule out elections entirely but said they
must come in a framework that would lead to formation of a
Palestinian state.
   ``This isolated occurrence of elections does not illustrate how
it will lead to the end of the occupation and to Palestinian
national independence,'' it said.
   The United Nations, it said, should be authorized to administer
the territories during a transitional period to Palestinian
statehood.
   Chief among the 83 signers of the document was Faisal Husseini
of Arab east Jerusalem, who has met with Egyptian officials on the
Shamir plan. He earlier met with Israeli officials on their peace
proposals.
   Husseini is considered the main spokesman for the PLO in the
occupied territories, and he was held in jail without charges for
most of the uprising.
   Others who signed the document included university professor
Sari Nusseibeh of Jerusalem; Haidar Abd al-Shafi, head of the Red
Crescent Society in Gaza; Gabi Baramki, head of Beir Zeit
University; Mayor Hilme Hanoun of Tulkarem; and Audeh al-Ranteesi,
an Anglican priest from Ramallah.
</TEXT>
