<SECOND>AM-BRF-Spokeswoman Arrested,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokeswoman for Southern Command Arrested on Marijuana Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. Southern Command in
Panama was arrested and held in jail for more than 24 hours earlier
this week on charges of possessing marijuana, the command said
Wednesday.
   Mercedes Morris, a civilian employee of the public affairs
office at the Southern Command's headquarters, was arrested Monday
afternoon on returning from a family outing at San Blas Islands,
the command said.
   She was arrested while claiming her baggage at the Paitilla
Airport by Panama Defense Forces officials and taken to a women's
detention center outside Panama City. She was released Tuesday
evening to the custody of American officials.
   The command, in a brief statement, said U.S. officials had filed
a protest with Panama over Morris' treatment, alleging several
violations of the Panama Canal Treaty. They include a failure to
honor the American request for transfer of custody within 10 hours
of detention; not notifying U.S. authorities within two hours of
her detention; not allowing access to Morris by U.S. consular or
military officials, and not allowing Morris legal representation on
request.
   According to defense sources who asked not to be named, U.S.
authorities in Panama have opened an investigation into the
circumstances surrounding Morris' arrest.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said
Wednesday the United States was not ruling out the possibility that
Morris' arrest was part of Panama's ``deliberate campaign to harass
U.S. and Panamanian employees of U.S. agencies in Panama.''
</TEXT>
