<FIRST>r w AM-US-ChineseCaps     04-26 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Chinese Caps,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says U.S. Cap Makers Not Threatened by Chinese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The importation of millions of baseball-style
cloth caps from China does not threaten material injury to the
American headgear industry, the U.S. International Trade Commission
said Wednesday.
   The commission voted 6-0 to reject an ``antidumping'' petition
filed by the Headwear Institute of America, representing 32 U.S.
enterprises. The petition sought to establish that the Chinese caps
were being sold at an unfairly low price that threatened harm to
U.S. producers.
   If the commission had approved the petition, additional duties
of about 20 percent would have been added to the price of
Chinese-made cloth caps, hats and visors.
   The commission found that $367 million worth of the headgear
covered in the case was sold last year in the United States, half
of it imported.
   Chinese shipments last year, representing 28 percent of the
value of all such imports, amounted to 78,468,000 caps and visors
with an import cost of $51.5 million. Even more came from Taiwan,
which accounted for 31 percent of the imports, while 27 percent of
the foreign-made headgear came from South Korea.
   U.S. cap manufacturers, employing 4,895 people, are scattered
about the country, with many concentrated in Missouri, Iowa and
Kansas, the commission said.
</TEXT>
