<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-JaneRoe     04-26 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Jane Roe,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sitting in Courtroom Audience, Jane Roe Says She's Overwhelmed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sitting in the audience as the Supreme Court
heard arguments on abortion Wednesday was Jane Roe, a Texas
cleaning woman whose case brought the 1973 landmark Roe vs. Wade
decision legalizing abortions.
   Roe, whose real name is Norma McCorvey, has emerged from
anonymity to enter the public fight over abortion and to argue that
the decision she won should be preserved.
   ``I'm very overwhelmed,'' she acknowledged, seeming a bit
bewildered as she met with reporters away from the hectic scene of
demonstrators outside the Supreme Court.
   McCorvey, 41, answered questions with great difficulty,
stumbling through a nine-line written statement and later questions.
   But assisted by her attorney, Gloria Allred, McCorvey disputed
suggestions she has been used in the case and said she has stepped
forward at considerable risk because she still believes in the
cause of a woman's right to an abortion.
   ``Our law is in jeopardy for all the women of the United
States,'' she said. ``... I have to protect Roe vs. Wade.''
   Allred, a feminist lawyer from Los Angeles, said McCorvey has
been in hiding in Los Angeles since April 4, when someone fired
three shotgun blasts into her Dallas home as she slept, hitting
windows and the front door.
   ``Norma feels that it is likely that the attack was made by a
person or persons who oppose the Roe vs. Wade decision and who wish
to frighten her out of speaking about the issue,'' she said. ``She
has also in the past been subjected to other forms of harassment.''
   As a result, McCorvey was accompanied by security guards who
checked credentials and searched some bags of reporters meeting
with her.
   McCorvey, as Jane Roe, said she agreed to become a test case in
the legal challenge of anti-abortion laws when she became pregnant
with a second child in 1970. She said she considered an illegal
abortion and was revolted by conditions at a visit to a back-alley
abortionist.
   But she didn't have an abortion. Instead she gave birth and put
her child up for adoption _ without knowing even its gender. Her
lawyer said McCorvey considered the experience ``far more traumatic
to her than an abortion would have been.''
   Yet McCorvey said she has recently begun efforts to locate that
adopted child, whose conception triggered the landmark case.
   Allred, who says she is not assisting in that search, insists
there's no irony or inconsistency there. ``The whole point is it's
about a woman's right to choose,'' she said.
   So what would Norma McCorvey, once Jane Roe, say to this child?
   ``Well, I obviously wouldn't discuss politics right away,'' she
said. ``I'd just say, `I'm your mom. How about a hug.'''
   Allred said McCorvey has only a modest income, cleans other
people's homes for a living, and has a 10th grade education. A
movie is being made of her life, and she is receiving money as a
consultant on the project. She has also set up a Jane Roe
Foundation, to finance her security and conduct pro-choice
activities.
</TEXT>
