<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     04-26 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dozens Killed in Black Market Fighting on Cambodian Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting broke out Wednesday between
groups involved in black market activities along the Cambodian
border, and Western aid officials said at least 38 people were
killed and 37 wounded.
   ``There was a big ambush on the trading route close to Ta
Phraya,'' said one official, speaking anonymously.
   Another official said a group of traders was ambushed as it
returned to the Thai district from Cambodia. ``While many of them
were running away from the gunfire, they found they were in the
middle of a minefield. They got blown up by the mines,'' he said.
   The officials said 37 of the wounded were hurt seriously.
   ``We have truckloads of wounded and we haven't seen the end
yet,'' said Urs Boegli, head of the Red Cross delegation in
Thailand. The injured were taken to a hospital at the Khao-I-Dang
refugee camp run by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Boegli said the Red Cross recalled a third surgical team for the
crisis and had blood brought up from Bangkok.
   Officials said the casualties included Thais, but most were
Cambodians living on the other side of the border.
   It was one of the most serious clashes along the border since
the devastating 1984-85 Vietnamese offensive on the Cambodian
resistance camps.
   Other details were not available.
   Ta Phraya district is in the eastern border province of
Prachinburi and about 50 miles north of the key Thai border town of
Aranyaprathet.
   Black market trading and clashes over it are rife along the
border and involve Thais as well as Cambodian guerrillas and
refugees in guerrilla-run camps. Three Cambodian guerrilla groups
based along the frontier are fighting Vietnamese forces and troops
of the government Vietnam installed there after invading the
country 10 years ago.
   Also Wednesday, gunners continued recent attacks on Cambodian
refugee camps just inside Thailand, hitting the Site 2 camp with
heavy shells that seriously injured four refugees, a Western
official said.
   Site 2 is along the border in Prachinburi province and with
180,000 people it is the largest U.N.-aided Cambodian refugee camp
in Thailand.
   It was not clear who fired the shells, which forced the
evacuation of all but the most essential Western aid workers. The
camp is controlled by guerrillas of the Khmer People's National
Liberation Front.
   In the past, shellings of the camps escalated as the two sides
maneuvered in advance of diplomatic events.
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk is to hold
talks in Indonesia next week with Hun Sen, premier of the
pro-Vietnamese government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
