<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-TheJustices     04-26 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The Justices,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the views of each
Supreme Court member on the court's 1973 decision, reached by a 7-2
vote, that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SUPPORTERS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Justice Harry A. Blackmun, 80. He authored the landmark Roe vs.
Wade opinion and is its most impassioned champion on the court. He
told a law school audience last fall the court might reverse the
1973 ruling this term. ``You can count the votes,'' he said.
   _Justice William J. Brennan, 82. A Roman Catholic, he reportedly
steered the court's closed-door deliberations that led to the 1973
ruling and joined in Blackmun's majority opinion.
   _Justice Thurgood Marshall, 80. He is the third remaining member
of the Roe vs. Wade majority.
   _Justice John Paul Stevens, 69. Since joining the court in 1975,
he consistently has voted to uphold the abortion right.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>OPPONENTS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, 64. He was a dissenter in
1973 and, in subsequent abortion rulings, has voted to give states
far greater authority to regulate abortions.
   _Justice Byron R. White, 71. Also a dissenter from Roe vs. Wade,
he said in subsequent abortion opinions that the 1973 decision
``essentially created something out of nothing.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>SWING VOTES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, 59. In a dissenting vote in 1986,
she favored giving states more authority in regulating abortions
and criticized the legal approach taken by Blackmun in 1973. But
she never has said that women do not have such a constitutional
right.
   _Justice Antonin Scalia, 53. He never participated in an
abortion case as a federal appeals court judge, and since joining
the high court in 1986 has taken no public stand on abortion.
   _Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, 52. Although a federal appeals
court judge for 12 years before joining the high court last year,
he never has ruled in an abortion case nor stated his views
publicly on the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
