<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritania     04-26 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritania,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 26 Die, 675 Injured in Anti-Sengalese Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-Senegalese violence in the
Mauritanian capital has killed at least 26 people and injured 675
in the past two days, a hospital source said Wednesday. Soldiers
patrolled the streets.
   Clashes stemming from a land dispute between the West African
neighbors also have broken out in Dakar, Senegal's capital, and in
many other cities and towns.
   But there has been no reliable word on the number of casualties
outside Nouakchott.
   The roving mobs of shouting, club-wielding Mauritanians
disappeared from Nouakchott's streets Wednesday as army units
patrolled the city.
   Mauritanian officials said residents respected the 8 p.m. to 6
a.m. curfew imposed by President Maaouiya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya and
there were no incidents overnight. It was not known when the
curfew, imposed Tuesday, would be lifted.
   Interior Minister Gibril Ould Abdallahy on Tuesday condemned the
violence and called attacks on Mauritania's Senegalese residents
unacceptable.
   A source at Nouakchott's main public hospital, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said 26 Senegalese and Mauritanians had
died and 675 were injured.
   He said others may have died or been treated for injuries at the
capital's other clinics and medical facilities.
   Other unofficial sources confirmed more than two dozen deaths
and hundreds of injured. The government said it had no casualty
report on the riots that exploded Monday and Tuesday.
   Violence has been spreading for two weeks since a border
incident set off rising tensions over competing claims by
Senegalese and Mauritanians to farm areas along the Senegal River,
which forms the border between the two nations.
   On Monday and Tuesday, angry crowds in the capital of 500,000
hunted down Senegelese citizens and beat them. Their shops and
homes were sacked and burned.
   Police broke up the rioting with tear gas and clubs.
   The Mauritanians were angered by similar treatment of their
compatriots in Senegal.
   In Dakar, 375 miles to the south, Mauritanian Ambassador Mokhtar
Ould Zamal said 100 Mauritanian men and women had been airlifted
out of the city Tuesday.
   Soliders and police using tear gas quelled anti-Mauritanian
violence in the Senegalese capital early Tuesday.
   Both countries have reinforced their troops along the Senegal
River as tensions mounted over the land dispute.
   Diplomatic observers said the clashes have shaken both
governments.
   ``Neither of these governments can be comfortable with these
events, and I'm talking about their stability,'' said one senior
diplomat on condition of anonymity.
   Both nations have tried to calm tensions since Mauritanian
soldiers allegedly killed two Senegalese farmers in Senegal's
Diawara border village April 9. At least two people have died in
violence in Senegal since then.
   Mauritania straddles Arab north and black West Africa.
Two-thirds of its 2 million people are Moors of Arab-Berber
extraction. The rest are black, mostly from the southern river
region. Nearly all of Senegal's 7 million people are black.
   The dispute concerns the right of Senegalese to farm on a
Senegal River island. After both countries became independent from
France in 1960, the black Toucouleur people of Senegal continued to
farm the Mauritanian side they had considered their own for
generations.
   Moors to the north, traditionally nomadic herders, did not farm.
   But the recent completion of two dams on the river has opened up
new farmland, spurred Mauritanian interest in agriculture and
prompted them to force Senegalese off the land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
