<DOCNO> AP890426-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Chernobyl     04-26 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chernobyl,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientific Center Planned For Chernobyl, But Atomic Data Still Withheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television on Wednesday said a research
center would be built near the site of the Chernobyl nuclear
disaster, but a scientist said officials are withholding data on
atomic energy three years after the disaster.
   In Kiev, people gathered in the main soccer stadium Wednesday
night to mark the anniversary of the April 26, 1986 reactor fire
and explosion, which sent a plume of radioactive debris into the
atmosphere and killed at least 31 people.
   The mass meeting in the Ukrainian capital, 80 miles from the
nuclear plant, was entitled ``Chernobyl should not be repeated.''
   The evening news show Vremya announced that scientists worldwide
would study at the new research center near Chernobyl. It did not
say when the center would be built or specify its exact location.
   Izvestia reported Wednesday that energy authorities still
routinely censor sensitive information about the number of
accidents, fires, fatalities and pollution of the atmosphere.
   Despite President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost,
strict limits remain on what can be disclosed about the nuclear
power program, Boris Paton, president of the Ukrainian Academy of
Sciences, told the government newspaper.
   ``We cannot obtain information about atomic and conventional
energy, the number of accidents and fires at stations, breakage of
equipment which causes material damage, losses of human life and
even about the catastrophic pollution of the environment,'' he said.
   Paton said he wanted to publish excerpts of an Energy Ministry
decree in connection with the anniversary of the disaster, but the
decree carried a notice banning publication of its contents ``in
non-confidential correspondence, telegraph messages and those
materials printed in the regular press or destined to be taken
abroad.''
   Paton criticized the policy that allowed ministry officials to
determine what was secret.
   In an accompanying editorial, Izvestia called on energy
officials to end secrecy but noted: ``Unfortunately, and scientists
confirm it with conviction, it is too early to speak about full
glasnost in the field of atomic energy and the consequences of the
(Chernobyl) accident.''
   The newspaper said 116,000 people were moved from their homes in
the contaminated area and $8 billion was spent in cleanup
operations.
   ``Loss of human life, which cannot be evaluated, and loss of
faith in atomic energy are just the top layer of problems which we
all face after the tragedy,'' Izvestia said.
   A deputy to the chairman of the Ukraine Council of Ministers, E.
Kachalovsky, told Izvestia, ``there is still not enough reliable
information (about Chernobyl) and existing information is often
distorted.''
   The effects of the Chernobyl explosion are still being felt in
the region surrounding the nuclear plant, which still has four
reactors in operation.
   The weekly Moscow News said there were widespread rumors that
people living in the region of Chernobyl would be allowed to buy
individual Geiger-counters, but so far no such devices are on sale.
   ``In short, to stop all these rumors about the high rate of
radioactivity, Geiger counters should be available to everyone,''
the newspaper said.
   ``Any new project of building an atomic power station, even the
existence of old ones, raises doubts of the people,'' it said.
``Only in the conditions of total glasnost and under public control
can such tragic events like what happened in Chernobyl can be
prevented. That has to be remembered by everybody who is connected
with the atomic energy field.''
   A group of foreigners visiting Chernobyl Wednesday was told that
scientists believe the destroyed reactor is cooling down, the
television said. The report said a repaired section of the atomic
station is scheduled to resume functioning on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
