<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldStocks     04-26 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Stocks,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Philippine Stocks Gave World's Best Returns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor looking for a place to put $1,000
in 1984 might not have thought of the Manila stock market, but if
he had taken the plunge he would have found the average return on
his investment at the end of last year to be $14,880, said a study
published Wednesday.
   On U.S. markets, the average return for the four years _ the
value of the stocks themselves plus dividents _ would have been a
tame $1,910.
   Manila showed the best average return worldwide in a study by
the International Finance Corporation, which looked at stock
markets in both major money centers and 31 Third World countries.
   The corporation, owned by 133 governments, is the agency of the
World Bank that lends to private industry.
   The corporation's Charles O. Sethness said the large gain in the
value of stocks on the stocks on the Manila exchange ``was all due
to the instability until (former President Ferdinand) Marcos left.''
   The Manila exchange jogged along through 1985 without much
change, despite the violent political campaign that led to the
victory of President Corazon Aquino, but took off after Marcos flew
to exile in Hawaii in February 1986.
   By June 1987, the average return on stocks had reached a level
nearly 16 times the level of 1985.
   There was a sharp drop in Manila when markets worldwide crashed
in October 1987. But, by the end of last year, total returns were
back almost to their peak.
   Returns on stock in the Third World seem to have little to do
with a country's prosperity. According to the World Bank, the
average Filipino had an annual income of only $590 in 1987, a
slight increase after a decline of several years. The country has
an active Communist insurgency and a $30 billion debt.
   An investor in the market of relatively prosperous South Korea
would have done well, but only a little more than half as well as
in the Philippines. His $1,000 would have turned into $7,890 in the
four years.
   In the southern African republic of Zimbabwe headed by President
Robert Mogabe, a professed Marxist, the return would have been only
a little less, $7,320.
   The survey does not cover other countries where governments call
themselves socialist but are experimenting with capitalism.
Sethness said a market in Shanghai deals only in what he considers
preferred stocks, while in Budapest the trading has been largely in
bonds. He reported that the Yugoslav government has been consulting
with the corporation on the possibiity of opening a market but has
not yet done so.
   Brazil turned in the best market performance in 1988 although
the country has the Third World's largest debt and inflation was
running at more than 1,000 percent by the end of the year. The
hottest stock was Acesita, a steel company, which chalked up a
return of $8,313 for shares worth $1,000 at the start of the year.
   As in any market, investors can lose their shirts on Third World
exchanges. Stock prices were mostly down last year in southern
Europe and Africa, by 37 percent in Turkey and Venezuela and by 25
percent in Portugal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MeterMaidAttacks     04-26 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meter Maid Attacks,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meter Maid Attacks Increase; Weapons Include Beer Bottles and Watermelon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attacks on the city's meter maids more than
doubled last year, and now average about three assaults per week.
They have been punched, spit on, pelted with beer bottles and run
over.
   One angry parking violator smashed a watermelon over a ticket
writer's head.
   A popular bumper sticker reads ``Meter Maids Eat Their Young.''
   The hostility is palpable in this city where car owners feel the
Boston Tea Party led to an inalienable right to park where they
please as long as they want. The problem is compounded by office
towers that have shot up, bringing in more drivers, while the
number of legal parking spaces has stayed the same.
   But city officials are cracking down on meter maid abuse. The
134 meter maids _ 30 of whom are men and all of whom prefer to be
called ``parking enforcement officers'' _ are being trained to walk
away from irate motorists, and are told to use their walkie-talkies
to call for help. And the city is aggressively prosecuting
offenders.
   ``Slowly but surely, the word's getting out that people can't
beat up on meter maids any more,'' said Investigator Edward T.
Oliver, 34, one of eight officers assigned to protect the
ticket-writers.
   Still, Oliver's tales would discourage job applicants. On
Friday, while a meter maid was writing a ticket, the driver looked
straight at her, backed up over her foot and drove off leaving her
prone on the sidewalk, he said. A few minutes later, the suspect
came back without his car and was arrested, he said.
   ``It turned out he owed over $400 worth of parking tickets,''
Oliver said.
   He also recalled a drunk who swung a beer bottle at a meter
maid, a motorist who ran over a meter man and sent him to the
hospital, and the man with the watermelon.
   ``We had a couple of kids from a local college, after knocking a
woman to the ground and hitting her, they spat on her and left,''
he said. ``I found this woman old enough to be my mother sitting on
the sidewalk crying, with saliva dripping off her face. It was
terrible.''
   Transportation Commissioner Richard Dimino refused to allow
meter maids to be interviewed for this article because ``they've
had an awful lot of bad press'' in the past, a spokeswoman said.
   But one meter maid buttonholed while she was shooing away a
double-parked car Wednesday said she is harassed and insulted
``about 30 times a day.''
   ``Just now a guy called me a bad name,'' she said, adding that
once a man ``threatened to shoot me.''
   The woman, who refused to give her name, said more police
protection is needed.
   About 250 people have been prosecuted for verbal or physical
abuse in the last two years, and the conviction rate has been close
to 100 percent, said Robert Francis, the city's director of
municipal security.
   Francis attributed some of the increase in assaults, from 50 in
1987 to 134 in 1988, to stepped up enforcement, including
round-the-clock parking patrols begun last year.
   The statistics also may be inflated by better record-keeping and
increased reporting from meter maids, who for the first time are
seeing their tormentors punished, Francis said.
   Deputy Transportation Commissioner Rina Cutler said the number
of tickets written has increased only slightly. She blamed the
attacks on more cars fighting for the available parking spaces, a
problem that will only get worse when reconstruction of the city's
Central Artery begins.
   ``There will never be enough parking spaces in Boston for
everyone who wants to bring their car in,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
