<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-R&amp;DWorkforce     04-26 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-R&amp;D Workforce,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation Needs to Improve Scientific Workforce, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the U.S. research and development
community on Wednesday issued a five-part plan they said would
improve the country's scientific and technical workforce and its
competitive status.
   The group, called CORETECH, said the nation's technological
development and commercialization efforts are threatened by an
erosion of that workforce and said training of future scientists
and engineers has been neglected.
   CORETECH recommended the following:
   _Bolster elementary and secondary math and science education.
   _Substantially increase federal support for undergraduate and
graduate education.
   _Increase the percentage of women and minorities in the
scientific and technical workforce.
   _Support and stimulate career-long continuing education
opportunities.
   _Foster collaboration among government, industrial and
educational partners.
   CORETECH has 162 corporate, university, research institute and
association members. It is chaired by Roland W. Schmitt, president
of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute. Its vice chairman is B.R.
Inman, chief executive officer of Westmark Systems, Inc.
</TEXT>
