<SECOND>AM-PLO-Elections,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says PLO Insists On Israeli Withdrawal Before Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior PLO leader said Wednesday that
the Palestine Liberation Organization will accept elections in the
occupied territories only after Israeli troops withdraw and only
under international supervision.
   ``The PLO does not accept elections in the shadow of the
occupation,'' said Salah Khalaf, No. 2 to Yasser Arafat in the
PLO's largest component group, Fatah.
   The statement from Khalaf, better known as Abu Iyad, was issued
by the PLO Information Department. It was described as a
``reaction'' to a report quoting him as saying the PLO modified its
position to accept elections possibly before a complete Israeli
troop withdrawal from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Khalaf said in the statement, ``The elections must be conceived
in the framework of a plan ... which includes both an intermediary
and a definitive period allowing the Palestinian people to decide
their fate and define their independent status.''
   Khalaf said the elections must be held ``under international
supervision and after the evacuation of Israeli forces.''
   He said the plan for such elections should be defined through
consultations with the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council ``and in the framework of an international peace
conference,'' by the five members and concerned parties, including
the PLO.
   The five permanent Security Council members are the United
States, the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
