<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Ball-Reax     04-26 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ball-Reax,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans, Friends Say Goodbye To Lucy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For baby boomers who watched her in reruns, for
fellow comics who sought her counsel, for former presidents and
television executives still in awe of her, Wednesday was the day to
say it once more:
   ``I Love Lucy.''
   Lucille Ball, 77, died unexpectedly at Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center eight days after surgery to repair a ruptured aorta near her
heart. She was recovering well, eating, taking small walks and, of
course, joking.
   But the aorta ruptured again in a different spot and Miss Ball
died despite efforts by intensive care unit doctors and nurses at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   On Hollywood Boulevard's Walk of Fame, flowers were placed on
Miss Ball's star.
   Gale Gordon, who worked with Miss Ball on three television
series _ ``Here's Lucy,'' ``The Lucy Show,'' and ``Life With Lucy''
_ reflected on how many mourners Miss Ball had.
   ``I think my grief, although it is deep ... is nothing compared
to the grief her family must feel, and in her case, the entire
world,'' said Gordon, who was in Edmonton, Alberta.
   ``Oh, what a blow! What a shame! Damn!'' lamented fellow
comedian Dick Van Dyke. ``She didn't deal in jokes. She dealt in
human behavior. She was a great physical mime with all the
instincts of a (Charlie) Chaplin.''
   Comedian George Burns, 93, said he shared the shock, and related
her death in show business terms: ``What can you do? When the guy
knocks on your door and gives you back your pictures, you gotta
go.''
   ``To baby boomers, a happy chunk of our childhood is missing,''
said ``Saturday Night Live'' comedian Victoria Jackson, who at 30
was born two years after the ``I Love Lucy'' show went off the air
as a regular series. ``She didn't make me laugh out loud, I
remember, she just made me happy about life.''
   ``No matter how many tears we shed today, the laughs outnumber
them. I love Lucy,'' said actress Betty White of ``Golden Girls.''
   Bob Rosati, a neighbor who stood for a few moments outside the
Beverly Hills home Miss Ball shared with husband Gary Morton, said
he was watching a rerun of ``I Love Lucy'' on Wednesday morning
when the screen went black and the words ``In Memory of Lucille
Ball, 1911-1989'' appeared.
   ``I felt I had lost someone in my family,'' said Rosati, 40.
   Television and film actor Danny DeVito recalled getting a
personal congratulation from Miss Ball in 1981 when he won an Emmy
for his work on the TV series ``Taxi.''
   ``It made it like it had been blessed,'' he recalled.
   ``Working with Lucy was like receiving an M.A. or a Ph.d. in
comedy,'' Joan Rivers recalled in a statement. ``What she forgot
about comic timing and delivery is more than most of us will ever
learn in a lifetime.''
   Danny Thomas, whose ``Make Room for Daddy'' series was shot on
the Desilu lot, traded guest appearances with Miss Ball for decades.
   ``She was the best female clown that ever lived, no question.
... Lucy did everything _ jumping in a barrel of cement, light her
nose, eat candy off the conveyer belt.''
   Actress-comedian Jane Curtin, costar of the ``Kate and Allie''
series, said she was among the scores of comics influenced by Miss
Ball.
   ``Probably a lot of what she did rubbed off on what I do, but it
couldn't be helped, because I memorized her shows,'' Ms. Curtin
said in a statement.
   ``She set a standard of television comedy for everyone to
follow,'' said ``Tonight Show'' host Johnny Carson.
   Many took comfort in preservation of Miss Ball's talent through
television reruns.
   ``God has her now and, thanks to television, we'll have her
forever,'' said comedian and longtime friend Bob Hope.
   ``Lucy is gone, but she'll always be with us,'' said Burns.
   ``All those wonderful things they did together ... those
wonderful TV shows ... are still available,'' said comic Tim Conway
in Detroit.
   ``Lucy will always have a special place in our heart, and she
will live on forever,'' former President Reagan and his wife Nancy
said in a statement.
   ``Nobody is going to take her place and nobody can compare with
her, really,'' said actor Art Carney.
   Miss Ball ``will always be the first lady of CBS,'' said CBS
chairman William Paley, who headed the network when it began
running ``I Love Lucy'' in 1951.
   Burns, ending a short meeting with reporters, said:
   ``I Love Lucy. Everybody loves Lucy.''
</TEXT>
