<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Georgia 1stLd-Writethru a0672 04-26 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Criminal Proceedings Started Against Use of Tear Gas in Georgia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf, `At least ...' to UPDATE with
Gorbachev's comments. Pickup 5th graf, `Perfiliev told ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have launched a criminal investigation
into the use of tear gas by soldiers who rushed thousands of people
demonstrating for independence in Soviet Georgia, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman said Wednesday.
   But the spokesman, Vadim Perfiliev, denied that tear gas or any
other chemical substance used by the soldiers killed anyone in the
April 9 clash in the southern republic's capital of Tbilisi.
   The denial contradicted reports by the Georgian minister of
health, Irakli Managarishvili, that at least two of the 20 victims
died from the gas and several others died from asphyxiation that
may have been induced by the unidentified substance.
   At least 1,100 people were injured in the melee, in which
soldiers charged the rally with sharpened shovels.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, in remarks carried Wednesday by
the news agency Tass, said the ruling Politburo ordered ``that
everything that happened (in the clash) be thoroughly
investigated.''
   ``But it's already clear now that we should all use political
methods and the force of law not to permit a repetition of anything
similar,'' Gorbachev said in the closing speech at a meeting
Tuesday of the policy-setting Central Committee.
   In his first direct statement on the Georgian clash, Gorbachev
said the incident showed that party leaders must improve their
communication with the masses.
   Perfiliev told a news briefing that the investigation is being
carried out by the chief military prosecutor. ``Due to the fact
that tear gas was used on demonstrators in Tbilisi, a criminal case
has been opened,'' he said.
   He said none of the victims had died from tear gas or other
chemicals.
   ``When autopsies were performed, the reasons for death were not
the use of chemical gas or chemical substances,'' he said.
   The announcement of the inquiry came one day after the United
States denounced the use of poison gas on demonstrators and urged
the Soviets to investigate what happened during the confrontation.
   Officials in Moscow have confirmed only that tear gas was used,
but doctors treating injured protesters in Tbilisi said they were
suffering from a paralysis of the central nervous system caused by
an unidentified chemical substance.
   One of the victims, Gilo Oniani, spoke with foreign
correspondents in Tbilisi on Monday on a trip arranged by the
Foreign Ministry.
   Mrs. Oniani, a 34-year-old mother and factory worker who was
sprayed in the face with an aerosol, told reporters she was unable
to sleep due to nervous agitation and unable to eat due to pain in
her abdomen.
   Manana Gamsakhurdia, wife of jailed protest organizer Zviad
Gamsakhurdia, said in a telephone interview Wednesday night that
two men came to Mrs. Oniani's room late Monday and threatened her
for speaking to reporters.
   Perfiliev said a commission made up of scientists from Moscow,
Leningrad and other major cities had been formed and would join in
the investigation of the clashes.
   Perfiliev said the the inquiry would take some time. ``There are
contradictory versions around the events in Tbilisi,'' he said,
including the question of how many gases were used.
   On Tuesday, Givi Gumbaridze, chief of the Georgian Communist
Party, acknowledged that soldiers used a harmful gas and said
``some people died from poisoning.''
   The Defense Ministry newspaper Red Star on Saturday identified a
chemical used against the protesters as an incapacitating agent
dubbed ``cheremukha.''
   Its main ingredient is chloroacetophenone, the newspaper said. A
Western military attache in Moscow said the substance was similar
to but stronger than tear gas.
   Demonstrations in Georgia first began April 4 when protesters
criticized calls from members of the republic's ethnic Abkhazian
minority to break away because of alleged discrimination by
Georgians.
   Other protesters have demanded Georgia secede from the Soviet
Union because of alleged interference from the central government.
   The republic's senior party official, Dzhumber Patiashvili, took
responsibility for the April 9 attack and resigned.
</TEXT>
