<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-ICBM     04-26 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-ICBM,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Assail Bush MX-Midgetman Missile Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's plan to develop both
the MX and Midgetman missiles came under attack Wednesday from
House Democrats, with a handful directing their criticism at the
Armed Services Committee chairman for dealing with the White House
without their consultation.
   Lawmakers said the Pentagon proposal of $1.2 billion funding in
fiscal 1990 for the rail-based version of the multiple-warhead, MX
nuclear missile and $100 million on the single-warhead Midgetman
sounds the death knell for the latter program.
   ``It's not a two-missile package in reality. It's really a
one-missile package,'' said Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., who referred
to the plan as ``a sucker deal.''
   ``If you go through with those figures you might as well kiss
the Midgetman missile good-bye,'' said Rep. Nicholas Mavroules,
D-Mass.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney had recommended moving the
nation's 50 MX missiles from silos to deployment on railroad cars
rather than developing the Midgetman. Former President Reagan and
scores of congressional Republicans have favored the MX.
   But President Bush chose quick deployment of the MX and
research-and-development funding for the Midgetman.
   Democrats, including Senate Armed Services Chairman Sam Nunn of
Georgia and House Armed Services Chairman Les Aspin of Wisconsin,
supported the Midgetman and urged Cheney to include funding for the
missile in the Pentagon budget.
   About a dozen House Democrats met with Aspin to express their
opposition to the MX-Midgetman plan and their displeasure with his
efforts to arrange a deal without their advice.
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., charged that when Aspin worked out a
deal on strategic weapons with Cheney he was not representing the
``united Democratic opinion.''
   Another Massachusetts Democrat, Rep. Edward Markey, said a
``deal of this nature should not have been cut without full
consultation of the Democrats.''
   ``We are grandstand observers,'' he said.
   Aspin, chairman of the Armed Services Committee since 1985, said
he was ``speaking for myself. I was talking for my own point of
view.''
   The Wisconsin Democrat said he sought assurances from Cheney
when the defense secretary testified Tuesday before the committee
that the Midgetman would not be ``squeezed out.''
   Aspin argued that U.S. arms control negotiators need both the MX
and Midgetman as a bargaining chip with the Soviet Union in
strategic talks, and said he made that point with his colleagues
after Frank left the meeting.
   The Massachusetts Democrat claimed the position was a brand new
one for Aspin.
   The Armed Services chairman played down the meeting, rejecting
suggestions that the session was ``cantankerous.'' Mavroules called
the session ``healthy ... there might have been some
disagreements.''
   But Frank said the meeting was ``loud'' and AuCoin indicated
that when members told the Armed Services chairman that
``consultation is different than notification,'' there was ``some
testiness on that point.''
   Frank, asked if the meeting signals a rebellion among the party,
said: ``It is not a rebellion. It is a reminder to him (Aspin) that
he was never authorized to make this kind of deal.''
   Aspin, chairman of the Armed Services Committee since 1985, was
voted out of his post in 1987 by House Democrats angered by the
Wisconsin congressman's support of the MX missile and aid to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   He later rallied and won back his chairmanship. Frank was one of
the liberal Democrats who supported Aspin.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee who attended the meeting, said those in
attendance, which included members who have worked on arms control
and Aspin's selection, were unhappy with the chairman's failure to
consult them.
   ``Nobody thought we were given a proxy for this. We were very
upset that there was arrogance that they had this deal,'' Schroeder
said.
   The Colorado Democrat, who has expressed an interest in the
chairmanship, said the ``tom toms are beating.''
</TEXT>
