<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     04-26 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Calls Opposition Traitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega called
the political opposition in Panama traitors on Wednesday.
   Noriega, head of the Defense Forces and as such de facto leader
of Panama, is not running for president in May 7 elections, but is
actively campaigning for the government coalition.
   While talking to hundreds of local leaders Wednesday, Noriega
quoted an article in U.S. News &amp; World Report as saying the U.S.
government is spending $10 million to help the opposition in the
Panamanian elections.
   The story, appearing in this week's edition of the
Washington-based weekly newsmagazine, said President Bush ordered
the expenditure. U.S. officials have declined comment.
   Noriega said accepting the money amounts to ``betrayal by the
unpatriotic Panamanians.''
   The official news agency Panapress said Wednesday the $10
million is part of a $120 million program the U.S. government has
promised to the opposition.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara has denied
the reports of U.S. financing.
   ``We have not asked for, nor received, nor will we ever receive
any money from foreigners in the United States or any other
power,'' Endara said.
   According to Noriega, ``Now none of them (opposition) can say
that they haven't received $10 million. We don't know to whom they
gave it, but we know they have it.''
   Noriega said in answering a reporter's question that differences
with the United States are ``no more than the reincarnation of
provocations since we signed that wretched treaty'' for the Panama
Canal in 1904.
   Noriega pressed Panamanians not to retreat from the 1977
agreement with the United States under which control of the
waterway reverts to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   ``Not one step back,'' the general declared.
   He insists that problems with the United States are based on
U.S. plans to break that treaty and refuse to turn over the canal.
   U.S.-Panamanian relations have been poor since February 1988,
when Noriega orchestrated the ouster of President Eric Arturo
Delvalle. The United States still recognizes Delvalle as Panama's
head of state.
   Delvalle had tried to fire Noriega after a federal grand jury in
Florida indicted him on drug smuggling and money laundering
charges. Noriega denied the charges.
   American election observers have announced their intention to
watch the Panamanian balloting, but Panama has complained about
their presence.
</TEXT>
