<FIRST>r w AM-SovietJews 1stLd-Writethru a0671 04-26 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jews, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to delete reference to vote being along party
lines.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panel Backs Bill To Overturn Restrictive Policy On Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel on Wednesday endorsed
legislation that would ease the way for Soviet Jews and
Pentecostalists seeking refugee status in the United States.
   The legislation seeks to undo a change in Justice Department
policy last summer that substituted case-by-case review for the
previous practice of allowing into the United States all Soviet
Jews and evangelical Christians on the grounds they were suffering
from religious persecution.
   The bill's author, Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., said he hoped
the Bush administration would act on its own to undo the action of
then-Attorney General Edwin K. Meese III.
   But, if Attorney General Dick Thornburgh doesn't act, Morrison
said, ``We'll push the bill through.'' The committee approved the
legislation on a 5-4 vote.
   The legislation states that both Jews and Pentecostalists have
been persecuted by the Soviet government and should be granted
refugee status automatically.
   The bill, which would be valid for only 17 months, to give time
for a longer-term solution to be devised, would also grant
automatic refugee status to residents of Laos, Vietnam and Cambodia
wishing to enter the United States.
   Meese restricted the refugee flow to deal with a growing flood
of Soviet Jews, Armenians and Pentecostalists taking advantage of
the Kremlin's liberalized emigration policies.
   Morrison, chairman of the House subcommittee on immigration,
refugees and judicial reform, called Meese's decision ``an
overkill'' that placed unnecessary hardships on thousands of Soviet
citizens wanting to come to the United States.
   About 5,000 of an estimated 30,000 Soviets who have applied
since Oct. 1 for refugee status have been turned down. The
rejections, as well as an unprecedented number of applicants, have
created a backlog of more than 20,000 Soviets waiting to enter the
United States.
   To counter the growing backlog and respond to the increasing
number of applicants, Thornburgh proposed legislation earlier this
month that would allow the administration to admit 30,000 people as
special immigrants to the United States every year.
   Jewish groups contend Thornburgh's proposal would absolve the
administration of having to pay for the Soviets' resettlement _ as
must be done for refugees _ and would send a signal to the Soviet
leadership that the United States now accepts Soviet human rights
policy.
   ``We have people suffering, waiting in Moscow and wondering if
Gorbachev is going to change his mind,'' said Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass. He said the matter was ``obviously not a high priority for
the administration.''
   But Rep. Lamar Smith of Texas, one of four Republicans to vote
against the bill, argued that the administration was nearing the
start of consultations with Congress on raising the ceiling of
refugees allowed into the country.
   The administration has been saying since February that it would
ask Congress for additional refugee slots beyond the 94,000
approved for this fiscal year to take care of some of the Soviet
overflow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Murdoch-Cross-Ownership     04-26 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murdoch-Cross-Ownership,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Rules on Murdoch's Ownership of Boston Newspaper, TV Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Wednesday granted media executive Rupert Murdoch's request to
transfer his Boston TV station to a trust in order to comply with
FCC rules barring ownership of a broadcast station and newspaper in
the same city.
   The FCC, in a 3-0 vote, said Murdoch's Twentieth Holdings Corp.
could turn over UHF station WFXT in Boston, where Murdoch's News
America Publishing owns the Boston Herald, to trustees Edward W.
Brooke, the former U.S. senator from Massachusetts, and Hugh L.
Carey, the former New York governor.
   But the commission said that in order to assure the station was
properly ``insulated'' from Murdoch and his affiliate companies,
which include the 20th Century Fox film and TV operations,
Twentieth Holdings could not have approval of any possible sale of
the station.
   The commission also said the station could have ``no
communications'' _ that is, it could not use _ Fox programming or
be an affiliate of the Fox TV network of stations.
   At the same time, the commission denied two competing
applications for the license of WFXT.
   The commission said its no-communications standard for broadcast
trusts ``was well established when Twentieth bought the station (in
1986) and that any communication between the trustees and any
Twentieth affiliate, no matter how limited, is prohibited.''
   However, the commission allowed the station to use syndicated
programs for which it previously had contracted until the existing
contracts expire.
   ``This action, as a practical matter, will end the station's
ability to remain a Fox affiliate and to acquire programming from
Fox on an on-going basis,'' the commission said.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick called the provision barring
continued affiliation ``a harsh result,'' but said precedent was
well established regarding the overall provisions of trust
transfers.
   Twentieth Holdings has 60 days to comply. It also could ask the
FCC to reconsider, appeal to the courts or ask for a commission
hearing on the conditions. Or it could divest the property.
   Attorneys for Murdoch did not immediately return a call seeking
comment.
   Under terms of the transfer, Murdoch will relinquish control but
still receive any profits. The trust will expire if WFXT shares are
sold, if the station stops operations or if the Boston Herald is
sold. If the station is sold, the trustees must try to sell the
shares to one buyer and the price must exceed $35 million.
   The station has been valued at between $30 million and $50
million.
   Murdoch engaged in a bitter battle with Congress in 1987 over
his ownership of the two Boston media outlets, as well as his
ownership of the New York Post and WNYW-TV in New York.
   Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., had
pushed a measure through Congress late in 1987 prohibiting the FCC
from eliminating or modifying the cross-ownership rules and barring
it from extending any waivers to the rules.
   The Herald at the time, which had been editorializing against
Kennedy, called his congressional action ``a vendetta.''
   The FCC had given Murdoch a waiver allowing him to own both
Boston outlets until June 30, 1988.
   A federal appeals court overturned the congressional action, but
Murdoch decided to seek FCC permission to transfer the station to
the trust. The FCC gave him another extension while it considered
the request.
   Murdoch, through his Australian-based News Corp., owns extensive
newspaper holdings in Europe, North America and Australia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-AbortionQuotes     04-26 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Abortion Quotes,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Scotus-Abortion Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at some of the comments
made Wednesday during Supreme Court arguments in a case in which
the justices are being asked to overturn the court's 1973 decision
that said women have a constitutional right to abortion.
   ``First, we are not asking the court to unravel the fabric of
unenumerated and privacy rights which this court has woven in
(previous) cases.... Rather we are asking the court to pull this
one thread,'' said Charles Fried, for the Bush administration.
   Frank Susman, for those who challenged the Missouri law,
disagreed, saying: ``... he (Fried) does not seek to unravel the
whole cloth of procreational rights but merely to pull a thread. It
has always been my personal experience that when I pull a thread my
sleeve falls off. There is no stopping. It is not a thread he is
after. It is the full range of procreational rights and choices
that constitute the fundamental right that has been recognized by
this court.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Susman said: ``I think the basic question ... whether this is a
human life or whether human life begins at conception, is not
something that is verifiable as a fact. .... Both sides would agree
as to when a heartbeat can first be detected. Both sides would
agree as to when brain waves can first be detected. But when you
try to place the emotional labels on what you call that collection
of physiological facts, that is where people part company.''
</TEXT>
