<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerClashes     04-26 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Clashes,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soccer Fans Run Amok, 23 Injured, 40 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of rival soccer fans
battled each other and attacked police Wednesday during riots on
the day of the Netherlands-West Germany World Cup qualifier. At
least 23 people were reported injured.
   Fans also rampaged downtown before the game, hurling bricks at
police and smashing windows.
   Police said they arrested 40 fans, mostly during fights outside
the Feyenoord Stadium while the two teams were playing inside,
according to police spokeswoman Ellen Peeters. She said rival fans
attacked each other and battled police who intervened.
   About 1,500 fans were involved in that disorder, police said.
   Authorities deployed 600 officers, including 250 riot police,
during the match for fear of a repeat of the stadium disaster in
Sheffield, Britain, on April 15, when 95 people were killed in the
crush of the crowd.
   Dutch fans had threatened to storm the 57,000-capacity stadium
on Wednesday unless more tickets became available for the sold-out
game. Some people believe such a stampede is what caused the deaths
in Sheffield.
   Earlier Wednesday, police battled about 500 fans, some of whom
hurled bricks and wooden sticks, in a downtown shopping
neighborhood, police said. They said the rioters also looted a toy
store and smashed dozens of shop windows.
   Police on horseback and riot officers with batons broke up the
crowds. In one case, a police helicopter dived to within about 30
feet of a group of marauding youngsters.
   Dutch television said 40 people were injured, including three
policemen. The discrepancy with police figures could not be
resolved immediately.
   Wednesday's game ended in a 1-1 tie.
   After least year's European championship semifinal against West
Germany, Dutch fans cheered their country's 2-1 victory with street
revelry and open hostility toward the Germans. Some saw the win as
revenge for Nazi Germany's occupation of the Netherlands in World
War II.
</TEXT>
