<FIRST>u w AM-Budget 3rdLd-Writethru a0715 04-26 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0715,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Money Bill Pulled Off Floor After House Rejects Democratic
Amendment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts 1st 2 grafs; picks up 4th graf pvs bgng: House Majority
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democratic leaders pulled a $4.7 billion
spending bill off the floor Wednesday after rebellious lawmakers
rejected a plan to cut $1 billion from the Pentagon budget to
strengthen the war on drugs and finance other domestic programs.
   House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas, responding to defeat in the
first budget test of the year, pledged ``corrective surgery'' that
would satisfy disgruntled Democrats and Republicans.
   Leaders wanted to pay for the spending in the bill by curtailing
defense, foreign aid and many domestic programs by $1.4 billion.
But the effort failed when minority Republicans were joined by
Democrats seeking to protect their favorite programs from
across-the-board cuts.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., who offered the
spending-cut amendment, said the vote was a sign of the
divisiveness of budget issues and not a signal that the Democratic
leadership was weakened by the controversy surrounding Wright and
his personal finances.
   ``I don't think it reflects on leadership problems,'' Foley
said. ``This is not a vote of confidence issue.''
   One of the 92 Democrats who voted against their leaders' plan
was Rep. Robert Roe, D-N.J., chairman of the House Science, Space
and Technology Committee. Roe said he opposed the across-the-board
cuts because they would have sliced too deeply into the programs he
oversees.
   ``From our point of view, we were battling the loss of about
$100 million from science and space,'' he said.
   Foley's proposal would have produced $1.4 billion in savings by
shaving .57 percent off most government programs. The provision
would have produced cuts this year of $1 billion in defense, $353
million in domestic programs and $43 million in foreign aid.
   White House budget director Richard Darman had sent lawmakers a
policy statement in which he said he would urge President Bush to
veto the ``fiscally irresponsible'' measure.
   And in a letter to House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill.,
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the defense cuts would force the
Pentagon to stop paying re-enlistment bonuses, reduce training
hours, eliminate five to 10 construction projects, lay off
scientists and engineers and curtail weapons testing.
   ``This would have very serious consequences for the manning of
our forces,'' he wrote, adding that he, too, would seek a veto.
   But loyal Democrats countered that the spending cuts were slight
and could be dealt with by federal agencies.
   ``All we're talking about are revisions of .57 percent so we can
cover some of the priorities we in Congress think are needed,''
said Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa.
   Looming over the battle was the veto threat from the Bush
administration, which labeled the overall bill ``fiscally
irresponsible'' and said the Democrats' proposed $1 billion in
defense cuts would be too harsh.
   The legislation, deemed a ``dire emergency'' by its supporters,
would provide money for the 1989 fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30.
Included would be $1.2 billion for veterans programs, $892 million
for guaranteed student loans, $822 million for anti-drug efforts,
$600 million for last year's forest fire costs.
   Republicans complained that the legislation would leave spending
levels well above limits agreed to in a 1987 budget pact between
Congress and then-President Reagan. They also said it would push
this year's deficit even further beyond the $135 billion limit set
in the budget. The 1989 shortfall is expected to surpass $163
billion, without counting this measure.
   ``If a satirist wanted a perfect lampoon about how the Congress
of the United States makes economic policy, if a cartoonist was
looking for the biggest blubbering whale in the ocean to harpoon,
if he wanted a model of a turkey, they need to look no further''
than this bill, said Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass.
   The legislation was endowed with symbolic importance because of
the recently concluded agreement between Bush and congressional
leaders on next year's budget.
   Republicans argued that with work on 1990 deficit reduction just
beginning, it looked bad for Congress to begin its work this year
by boosting the 1989 shortfall. The ranking Republican on the House
Budget Committee, Rep. Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, called the
legislation ``the moral equivalent of banana republic fiscal
policy.''
   Democrats used some of the bill's spending _ such as its funds
for new prisons, training for new law officers and other anti-drug
measures _ as a test of Bush's willingness to pursue initiatives he
has endorsed.
   ``If you're serious about dealing with the drug problem in this
country, you'll vote yes,'' said Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the
deputy House whip.
   But Republicans argued that the drug expenditures, and other
parts of the bill, could have waited until next year.
   ``It makes a good show, great charade, `I'm for drug abatement
and against abuse and all of that sort of thing,''' said Michel.
``But I tell you folks, they've got more money now than they can
spend.''
   The $4.7 billion measure would also provide $423 million for
state foster care programs, $250 million for reparations for
Japanese-Americans who were interned during World War II, $154
million for the homeless, $127 million for unemployment assistance,
$100 million for refugee assistance, and $88 million for public
housing.
   The Senate has yet to consider the spending bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
