<FIRST>r w AM-CleanSweep     04-26 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Sweep,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Team Taking Over in State Bureau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five senior State Department officials are
being replaced in a major overhaul of the bureau that deals with
the Arab-Israeli dispute and India and Pakistan.
   A U.S. official, insisting on anonymity, confirmed on Wednesday
a Washington Times report that the five had been notified by John
Kelly, who is awaiting Senate confirmation to head the bureau, that
they should seek new jobs elsewhere in the foreign service.
   Kelly told them at a meeting at the department last Friday that
he wanted to make a ``fresh start,'' the official said. Kelly is
recalling James P. Covey, the U.S. deputy ambassador to Egypt, to
serve as his principal deputy in the Bureau of Near Eastern and
South Asian Affairs.
   The five officials being reassigned include Paul J. Hare, who is
running the bureau while Kelly awaits confirmation by the Senate.
   Hare, a former U.S. ambassador to Zambia, played a key role in
the meetings President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker
III held here this month with three visiting Middle Eastern
leaders, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir and King Hussein of Jordan.
   Hare, son of Raymod Hare, a former U.S. ambassador to Egypt, is
considered primarily a specialist in African affairs. The four
others being reassigned are Howard Schaffer, A. Peter Burleigh,
William A. Kirby and Edward S. Walker.
   The bureau, one of the most complex in the State Department,
deals with the Middle East, the Persian Gulf and the Indian
subcontinent. Schaffer has specialized in India, Pakistan and
Afghanistan, Burleigh in the Gulf and Kirby and Walker on
Arab-Israeli issues.
   Covey, a protege of former Secretary of State Henry A.
Kissinger, has served in Israel and Egypt. Kelly, meanwhile, is a
former U.S. ambassador to Lebanon who was publicly criticized by
former Secretary of State George P. Shultz for not informing him of
instructions he had received from the National Security Council
during the surreptitious sale of U.S. weapons to Iran.
   Whether Kelly will play a dominant role in shaping U.S. policy
in the Middle East is not apparent. Dennis Ross, who heads the
Policy Planning Staff, is a specialist on the subject and one of
Baker's closest advisers. Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger also is deeply interested in the area.
</TEXT>
