<FIRST>r i AM-NATODispute     04-26 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO Dispute,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Defends Position on Short-range Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government declared its support
for the strained NATO alliance Wednesday in a rebuttal of U.S. and
British officials dismayed by its call for early superpower talks
on short-range nuclear arms.
   ``There has never been a German intention to pursue an
independent course,'' chief government spokesman Hans Klein said at
a Bonn news conference. ``It is not our intention to jeopardize the
alliance.''
   U.S. and British officials have harshly criticized Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's decision to press for prompt superpower talks to
reduce the number of short-range nuclear weapons.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney described such negotiations
as a ``dangerous trap.'' He said it would be a mistake to risk
cutbacks in this kind of weapon while the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
holds an advantage in conventional forces in Europe.
   Referring to criticism from British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, Klein said Kohl would restate his government's position
when the two leaders meet in West Germany on Sunday.
   ``The chancellor will endeavor to explain the West German
position again in an atmosphere of trust and friendship,'' Klein
said.
   Mrs. Thatcher on Tuesday harshly rejected Kohl's proposal. She
said short-range missiles are part of NATO strategy, which ``cannot
be undermined by any one country.''
   However, the West German government, responding to domestic
pressure and overtures from Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
contends the climate is right to step up arms control efforts with
the Soviet bloc.
   West Germany has said NATO should postpone a planned upgrading
of short-range missiles while pursuing negotiations on reducing
their number.
   In Copenhagen, Denmark, the Danish government on Wednesday
joined several other NATO allies that have backed West Germany's
stand on the short-range missiles.
   ``There is no need to decide on the modernization of NATO's
short-range missiles in Europe until the beginning of the 1990s,''
Danish Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen told visiting Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany.
</TEXT>
