<FIRST>r w AM-Fusion 2ndLd-Writethru a0687 04-26 1213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0687,1160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say They'll Prove Themselves to Government Scientists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``Pons told...'' to correct spelling
of deuterium; picks up 13th graf pvs, bgng: ``He said.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two researchers who say they've used ordinary
lab equipment to master fusion, the process that powers the sun and
the stars, told Congress Wednesday they will duplicate their
experiments for government scientists in hopes of quieting skeptics.
   ``We have 19 experiments being set up now,'' University of Utah
chemist Stanley Pons told the House Science Committee, including a
demonstration of room-temperature fusion for scientists from the
Los Alamos National Laboratory.
   Pons said the federal scientists will monitor the experiment at
Utah, then dismantle it and take it to the national laboratory in
New Mexico for further tests.
   Pons and his collaborator, Martin Fleischmann, of the University
of South Hampton in England, are making the arrangement to silence
some of the skepticism about their claim to have discovered a way
to achieve fusion using ordinary lab equipment assembled on a table
top.
   Their announcement of cooperation with Los Alamos came after
Rep. Sid Morrision, R-Wash., questioned them closely about why so
many other laboratories have not been able to duplicate their
results and asked if they would perform the experiment before
independent observers.
   ``We are very happy to tell people how we have been able to do
it,'' said Fleischmann, but he added that those who can't duplicate
the process should ``publish in full'' reports of their failures.
Several other researchers have said their experiments appeared to
confirm the Utah scientists' endeavors.
   Rep. Marilyn Lloyd, D-Tenn., said reports on the fusion process
indicated that the energy levels achieved were low. She asked Pons
and Fleischmann if they had actually achieved a ``useful
temperature'' with the reaction.
   ``We've had a cell warm up to the boiling point,'' said
Fleischmann, adding, however, that scaling the process up to a
useful level, ``raises many new problems.
   ``We think it's feasible, but it will require a very high
effort.''
   Pons and Fleishmann announced their discovery March 23, stunning
nuclear physicists around the world who have attempted to achieve
fusion for 25 years using multimillion-dollar machines.
   The hearing was jammed with journalists, scientists and
industrial representatives anxious to learn more about a reaction
that some predict could produce plentiful electric power with
little environmental pollution or threat.
   Pons told the committee how he and Fleischmann had inserted
electrodes of platinum and palladium in a flask containing
deuterium oxide, or heavy water. Electrical current was applied to
the platinum electrode, Pons said, forcing deuterium atoms into the
crystal lattice of the palladium.
   He said that after the experiment ran for several hours, the
deuterium became compressed and fused, giving off heat almost four
times as great as the energy the experiment had consumed.
   The Utah researchers said they built their initial experiment
for about $100,000, but Fleischmann said that ``production of a
scale-up device will cost about 10 times that'' and that the next
phase, producing enough energy to be useful, ``would cost
millions.''
   Chase Peterson, president of the University of Utah, appeared
with Pons and urged the committee to respond quickly to the fusion
discovery by pushing for federal aid to establish a fusion research
center at the university.
   Peterson said that the Utah legislature had allocated $5 million
for the project and had collected more than $1 million in private
donations.
   ``What level of funding do you believe is needed,'' asked Rep.
George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif.
   ``The figure that comes to mind is $25 million,'' said Peterson.
   Several committee members reacted favorably to his suggestion,
but added that coming up with the money would be difficult in a
climate of budgetary restraint.
   Other scientists who testified urged the committee not to rush
to support of the Utah research.
   ``We (scientists) need at least two months to evaluate the
significance of this process,'' said Steven Jones, a Brigham Young
University fusion researcher.
   George Miley, a fusion researcher at the University of Illinois,
told the committee that putting millions of dollars into the Utah
experiment now could hurt energy research in general.
   ``A failure could set fusion research back by years,'' he said.
``I urge us to no overeact and put all our eggs in one basket.''
   Mike Saltmarsh, head of the fusion energy program at the Oak
Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee, said his lab and other
federal facilities have all tried to duplicate the Utah process.
   ``The results have all been negative,'' he said. ``We have seen
no heat'' generated by the process.
   Saltmarsh told the committee, ``It would be a real mistake to
try to dray firm conclusions at this point.''
   He said many questions about the Utah experiment still need to
be answered before it is understood.
   One of the elements to be investigated, said Fleischmann, is the
metal that can be used in cold fusion. The palladium used by the
Utak researchers is an expensive metal that is available in only a
few places on Earth.
   Fleischmann said other experiments are under way to find if
other metals can be used. ``Palladium may be the best choice but
there may be also other possible choices,'' he said.
   Researchers in Texas, California and Washington have reported
what may be fusion reactions, but many other laboratories have
reported failed efforts. Scientists in the Soviet Union and Hungary
reported experiments with reactions that may be fusion.
   Fleischmann said follow-up articles detailing how the experiment
is being conducted will be published in scientific journals.
   Pons said part of the controversy revolves around the different
way in which chemists and physicists announce the results of their
work. The Utah experiments have come under heavy criticism from
fusion experts because the precise details needed for duplication
of the work have not been released.
   Pons said that physicists typically circulate a pre-publication
copy of their research to colleagues for informal review.
   ``For chemists, it is done in a different way,'' he said. ``The
review is left up to the journal.''
   The March 23 announcement stunned the international physics
community, which has spent millions of dollars over the last
quarter century attempting to achieve fusion using massive machines
filled with plasmas heated to temperatures of up to 100 million
degrees.
   Many experts believe fusion to be the ultimate energy source.
The nuclear process is the opposite of the fission reaction that
now powers atomic generating plants. Fission occurs by splitting
atoms and the process leaves behind highly radioactive spent fuel.
   Fusion derives its energy by forcing atoms of deuterium or
hydrogen together. The reaction produces an atom of helium, a burst
of energy and a neutron. Experts believe fusion energy would
produce a much smaller amount of radioactive waste, and that fusion
power plants could be operated with deuterium oxide, or heavy
water, a chemical that can easily be extracted from seawater.
   Natural fusion energy is the power that causes the sun and the
stars to shine. Stellar fusion is created when the massive force of
gravity in stars forces hydrogen atoms to fuse, giving off heat,
light and helium. Most ``hot'' fusion research is an attempt to
duplicate the pressure and heat process seen on the sun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
