<FIRST>u a AM-Eliana-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0676 04-26 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eliana-AIDS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: AIDS Child May Attend Public School, Without `Glass Cage'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 5th graf, ``All she ..., to UPDATE with
further comment from lawyers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED GOODALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An incontinent, retarded 7-year-old with AIDS
may attend public school and sit at a desk alongside other mentally
disabled children her age, a federal judge ruled Wednesday.
   Eliana Martinez had been told she could attend class only if she
remained isolated inside a glass booth. Her adoptive mother, Rosa
Martinez, took her battle to court, saying she would not send her
daughter to school to sit in a ``glass cage.''
   Eliana won't have to be separated from her 10 classmates under
the ruling by U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kvachevich, which the
child's attorney thinks will have effects around the country.
   ``And she will be at class Thursday with bells on,'' said the
attorney, Steve Hanlon, after Ms. Kovachevich ruled the child posed
no significant health risk to other children.
   ``All she understands is she will be going in to play with some
little people. She doesn't know what school is; she hasn't been to
it,'' said her mother.
   ``The judge has finally entered a ruling. I am recommending it
be followed,'' said school board attorney Crosby Few. ``The
partition is a moot question now. There won't be one. She will be
in the classroom just like the other kids. I hope this is the end
of it''
   Few said school officials had hoped to have a couple of days
before Eliana attended class. ``We had hoped to be able to educate
the parents first ... to answer all their questions and inquiries
before hand. The education will just have to come later.''
   ``It's been a difficult time for all of us,'' said Hanlon. He
said he thinks school officials ``will be as glad as we are to put
this matter behind us.''
   ``There's been a great deal of misinformation in the case,'' he
said, adding that he approved of a court requirement that the
school system educate pupils and parents at Eliana's school about
AIDS.
   The judge also noted that Mrs. Martinez didn't object to a
one-on-one aide for Eliana or a daily examination by a school nurse
to determine if attendance is advisable that day.
   In December, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals sent the
case back to Ms. Kovachevich, saying the child must be placed in a
regular classroom unless evidence proves Eliana posed a significant
risk to other children through bodily secretions.
   Through affidavits and sworn statements, Ms. Kovachevich said
she learned Eliana is ``capable of being instructed not to suck or
mouth her fingers and that she is well on her way to being fully
toilet-trained.''
   The judge said she took that into consideration in making her
decision as well as two other factors. The child's doctor told the
court he doesn't think the risk merits such precautions as
isolation, and the pediatric association now makes no
recommendation for a restricted environment for youngsters who
cannot control bodily secretions.
   Initially, Ms. Kovachevich ruled Aug. 8 than Eliania could
attend Manhattan Elementary School but had to remain inside an
enclosed plexiglass partition until she was toilet-trained and
learned to stop sucking her fingers.
   Hillsborough County school officials fought attempts to admit
her. They feared she might transmit the deadly, incurable acquired
immune deficiency syndrome virus through bodily fluids.
   But Hanlon and Mrs. Martinez, a nurse who adopted Eliana as an
infant in her native Puerto Rico, isisted that to develop fully
Eliana needed to be with other children.
</TEXT>
