<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Conflict     04-26 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Conflict,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Official Denies Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former senior federal housing official on
Wednesday denied violating any ethics or conflict of interest laws
when she became a consultant on U.S. commercial trade activity with
the Soviet Union shortly after leaving her government post.
   Appearing before the House Government Operations subcommittee on
employment and housing, June Koch, former assistant secretary of
Housing and Urban Development, described her contacts with her
former colleagues at HUD as ``distinctly and definitely
informational.''
   She said her contacts with agency officials were not an attempt
to influence their decisions concerning visits by Soviets in
connection with a cooperation agreement in the field of housing and
other construction.
   Koch served as HUD's assistant secretary for policy development
and research from July 1984 until she resigned in October 1987.
   She was appointed in 1985 to direct commercial trade activities
with the Soviets in connection with the agreement, making her
responsible for organizing and managing an international trade show
``Stroyindustriya '87'' in Moscow.
   HUD sponsored about 110 U.S. companies at the event at a cost of
$1.6 million which the Government Operations panel last year called
``misguided, mismanaged and misspent.''
   During the panel's probe, several companies complained of being
``misled and pressured'' to participate in the show and questions
arose about the propriety of the former housing official allegedly
trying to solicit them as clients after leaving HUD.
   After leaving the housing agency Koch became president of
Construction, Marketing and Trading Inc., a consulting firm
providing assistance to U.S. companies wanting to do business with
the Soviet Union.
   She also was hired as a HUD consultant for six months, an
agreement the GAO said was extended twice and terminated in January
1989. Koch contended that she ``worked for HUD consulting all of
five or six days.''
   ``This is not a case of a revolving door at HUD. Rather it
appears that the door at HUD was never closed to June Koch,''
Lantos said as he opened the hearing.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee, said
Wednesday that he asked the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, to investigate Koch's actions and
business activities after leaving the government.
   Koch said that while still a HUD assistant secretary and a
member of a HUD delegation accompanying then-Housing Secretary
Samuel Pierce to Moscow in early October 1987 she discussed with
Soviet officials her impending resignation.
   She said the Soviets wanted her to arrange meetings with U.S.
business representatives that could provide construction products
and services.
   GAO determined that Koch's contacts with HUD were not
informational but ``for the purpose of securing meetings and
receptions on behalf of herself and her clients with members of the
visiting Soviet delegations,'' said John Ols, a GAO official.
   GAO criticized HUD's monitoring of Koch's post-government
activities and recommended the matter be referred to the Justice
Department for further investigation. Lantos said would decide soon
whether to follow the GAO recommendation.
</TEXT>
