<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Quake     04-26 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Quake,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repair Crews Work On Earthquake Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews worked Wednesday to repair cracks in an
aqueduct one day after it was damaged in an earthquake that killed
one person and shook an area from the capital to the Pacific coast
resort of Acapulco.
   Four people were injured in Tuesday's quake, which measured 6.8
on the Richter scale, but little major damage was reported.
   Cracks appeared in buildings in Mexico City and Acapulco, and
telephone, electrical and subway service in the capital were
interrupted.
   The tremor felled a power line just north of the city center
that electrocuted a man of about 30, said Maria Cortina Benitez, a
city police spokeswoman.
   Water was being trucked to neighborhoods in the southeastern
part of the city that were left without service because of the
aqueduct damage. Officials said said residents of affected areas
should have clean water again by Friday.
   Inspectors checked schools and some high-rise office buildings
for damage.
   The movement set off landslides on a rural road near Acapulco,
the Excelsior news service said.
   The epicenter of Tuesday's quake was 40 miles east of Acapulco,
about 200 miles south of Mexico City, said the U.S. National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.
   The tremor terrified people who recalled a 1985 quake that
crumbled many buildings in the capital and killed at least 9,500
people.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in populated
areas. A quake of magnitude 7 is considered a major earthquake,
capable of widespread, heavy damage in populated areas.
</TEXT>
