<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     04-26 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politician, Family Slain in Peru Highlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers shot and killed a leftist
politician, his wife and their 8-year-old daughter as they slept at
home Wednesday in a highland city, and an anti-rebel death squad
was suspected, police said.
   Police said the politician, Benigno Ayala, was an official in
the local branch of the United Left Party, a Marxist coalition and
Peru's second strongest party. Ayala had been suggested as a
candidate in congressional elections set for 1990.
   The shooting occurred in Cangallo, about 250 miles southeast of
Lima. The impoverished highlands around nearby Ayacucho are a
stronghold of the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla group, whose
nine-year insurgency has claimed more than 14,000 lives.
   Police said the newly formed Rodrigo Franco Command is suspected
in Wednesday's attack.
   The group is named after a member of the governing center-left
Aprista Party, who was shot to death by the Shining Path. The
Franco Command has vowed to kill people it considers leftist
guerrillas or their supporters.
   The government has denied any links to the Franco Command.
