<HEAD>Syrians Shell Ports in Lebanon; Peace Talks Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `An Arab...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with league
official calling for cease-fire. Pick up 14th pvs, `Aoun has...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian soldiers fired rockets at the
coast north of Beirut on Wednesday, sending a ship fleeing from
port and blocking the only escape routes for thousands of
beleaguered Christians, police said.
   The sporadic bombardment coincided with renewed efforts by the
Arab League to halt the latest round in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil
war and arrange political reforms to give Moslems an equal share of
power with the Christians.
   Police said the Syrians and militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party fired their multibarreled
rocket launchers from hilltop positions around Beirut overnight and
during the day.
   Their fire targeted a 10-mile coastal stretch between Jounieh
and Byblos, the main ports of the besieged 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   An unidentified commercial ship docked in Amsheet harbor just
north of Byblos sailed quickly out to sea when shells fell around
it, police said.
   Army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly Christian forces struck
back with 155mm artillery fire at Syrian and Druse positions around
Moslem west Beirut.
   No casualties were reported on either side.
   At least 272 people have been killed and 991 wounded, by police
count, since the current round of civil war fighting broke out
March 8.
   Two Cypriot-flagged ferry boats had been running the gantlet of
Syrian and Druse shellfire in the past five weeks to evacuate more
than 13,000 Christians from the blockaded enclave through Jounieh.
   But sailings by the Larnaca Rose and the Baroness M were
suspended Monday in a shipping ban imposed by Aoun so that a French
navy tanker could unload 6,000 tons of fuel needed to reactivate
Lebanon's shuttered power plants.
   Power was restored in Beirut on Tuesday for two hours a day,
ending a 10-day blackout caused by lack of fuel at the capital's
main power plants.
   A convoy of 10 trucks carrying 35 tons of medical supplies from
Kuwait rolled into west Beirut on Wednesday, completing a three-day
journey across Iraq, Jordan and Syria. Dr. Mohammed Mohanna, a
senior Health Ministry official, said the aid would be split
between Moslem and Christian areas to ease an acute shortage of
medicines in hospitals throughout Lebanon.
   In Tunis, Arab League foreign ministers opened an emergency
meeting on Lebanon, and Secretary-General Chedli Klibi said a
cease-fire must take effect before the country's problems can be
solved.
   The ministers are discussing a peace plan for Lebanon that would
include sending a multinational observer force of at least 200 Arab
officers to monitor a cease-fire.
   Aoun has given tacit approval to the dispatch of an Arab
observer force ``as a first step'' toward ending the fighting. But
he said he still intends to end ``the Syrian and Israeli occupation
of Lebanese territory.''
   Syria maintains 40,000 troops in Moslem areas under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League. Israel occupies a border
strip in south Lebanon as a buffer zone against cross-border raids
by Palestinian guerrillas.
   Hoss also declared support for the Arab League peace plan,
saying in statement released Wednesday that an ``immediate end
should be put to the horrific cycle of violence gripping Lebanon.''
   But Shiite Moslem militia leader Nabih Berri, a major Syrian
ally, rejected the proposal for an Arab observer force.
</TEXT>
