<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     04-26 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Cabinet Reshuffled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Miklos Nemeth proposed six new
ministers to the Presidential Council for approval in a major
Cabinet reshuffle, the state news agency MTI reported Wednesday.
   Nemeth, a 41-year-old economist, announced plans to revamp the
government on April 14, two days after changes were made in the
Communist Party's ruling Politburo.
   He was quoted as complaining then that his government lacked ``a
necessary harmony in outlook and unity of action,'' leading to
``delays, vacillations and hurried acts.''
   MTI said Foreign Minister Peter Varkonyi will become Hungary's
ambassador in Washington and Gyula Horn, secretary of state at the
Foreign Ministry, will become foreign minister.
   In other changes: deputy minister Laszlo Bekesi will replace
Miklos Vilanyi as finance minister; Ferenc Horvath, secretary of
state in the Industry Ministry will replace Frigyes Berecz as
industry minister; Csaba Hutter, president of an agricultural
cooperative at Szecseny, will succeed Jenoe Vancsa as agriculture
minister; historian Ferenc Glatz will succeed Tibor Czibere as
minister of education and culture, and Ernoe Kemenes, secretary of
state of the National Planning Office, will replace Janos Hoos as
planning chief.
   Parliament is to approve the new ministers at its next session
on May 10.
   Under the constitution, Parliament has supreme power. It elects
a Presidential Council, which exercises the functions of Parliament
between sessions.
   Imre Pozsgay, Hungary's leading Politburo reformer, said
Wednesday that he hopes elections with competing parties will be
held in Hungary next year.
   Interviewed by Channel 4 News in London, Pozsgay said he favored
advancing the limited election planned for 1995 and expanding it to
a fully contested election.
   ``I think it could be that we will bring forward the free
elections and it's possible that the Hungarian Socialist Workers
Party (the ruling Communist party) will come out as winner of this
election,'' he said.
   Pozsgay, who held talks on Tuesday with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, said he would like to see Hungary adopt some aspects of
her free-market, monetarist economic principles.
   Pozsgay is visiting Britain as patron of a Hungarian arts and
music festival that opens in London on Oct. 25.
</TEXT>
