<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-26 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damaging Thunderstorms in Iowa; Record Highs in the Southeast, Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Flooding forced hundreds of West Virginians out of their homes
Wednesday, and intense thunderstorms pummeled Iowa with winds up to
75 mph and hail as big as golf balls.
   High-temperature records were set or tied in 12 cities in the
Midwest and Southeast, while up to 8 inches of spring snow fell in
the mountains of the West.
   Heavy overnight rains in central West Virginia caused floods
that forced at least 200 people out of their homes Wednesday
morning and closed schools in four counties, officials said.
   Widely scattered light rain and drizzle fell across sections of
the state during the day, but most small streams receded to normal
levels and evacuees returned to their homes in the afternoon.
   Some rivers continued to rise. The Little Kanawaha River was
expected to rise 3 to 4 feet above flood stage at Creston, W.Va.
   Northern Iowa's storms blew a roof off a barn and destroyed a
hog barn near Little Rock. Winds gusted to 75 mph and golf
ball-size hail fell in Spirit Lake and gusts were clocked at 70 mph
in West Okoboji. In the Estherville area, dime-size hail and
three-fourths of an inch of rain fell in just 20 minutes.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in southern Minnesota,
western Wyoming and central Montana. Rain showers were scattered
across eastern Washington state.
   Snow fell at higher elevations of northwest Wyoming, southeast
Idaho. About 8 inches of snow has fallen at the Alta, Utah, ski
area.
   The snow was expected to spread across the Montana Rockies. A
winter storm watch was in effect for Wednesday night and Thursday
in the mountains and foothills of Montana and for Thursday in
south-central Montana.
   Record heat that baked the western Plains earlier this week
spread Wednesday to the Mississippi Valley and the southern
Atlantic Coast. Temperatures were in the 80s and 90s from the
southern Plains and Kansas to the middle and lower Mississippi
Valley, the western lower Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, the
Gulf Coast states, the southern Atlantic Coast and Florida.
   High-temperature records for the date were set in eight cities
and tied in four.
   Nashville, Tenn., tied its all-time high temperature for April,
set in 1980, with a reading of 90 degrees.
   Other records included Lincoln, Neb., where the reading of 94
degrees exceeded the old mark set in 1987 by 2 degrees; Topeka,
Kan., (93, 92 in 1987); Evansville, Ind. (89, 87 in 1981); Paducah,
Ky. (87, 85 in 1986) and Charleston, S.C. (90, 88 in 1984).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Jackson and Cody, Wyo., to 95 degrees at Medicine Lodge,
Kan. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 15 degrees in Truckee,
Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the Plains to the middle and upper Mississippi
Valley and rain showers in parts of the northern and central
Rockies, with snow in higher elevations of the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s and 50s from eastern
portions of the north-central Intermountain region to the northern
and central Rockies, much of the northern Plains, northern
Minnesota, the northern Great Lakes region and New England; the 80s
and low 90s from the central and southern Plains to the middle and
lower Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley, the Gulf Coast
states, Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast; the 80s in the
desert Southwest; and generally in the 60s and 70s in the rest of
the nation.
</TEXT>
