<FIRST>r i AM-PragueSpring     04-26 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prague Spring,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek Appears On Hungarian TV Despite Prague Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian television ignored a protest
from Prague on Wednesday and broadcast a second excerpt of a
three-hour interview with Alexander Dubcek, leader of
Czechoslovakia's 1968 ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   It was the first official Soviet bloc interview with Dubcek
since he was ousted as Czechoslovak Communist Party leader in April
1969.
   The 40-minute excerpt showed Dubcek making a spirited attack on
Leonid I. Brezhnev, who was Soviet president at the time. Brezhnev
died in 1982.
   ``It was Brezhnev's dogmatism that endangered socialism,''
Dubcek said, recalling a meeting three weeks before the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact invasion in August 1968.
   Dubcek said he rejected Kremlin pressure to halt his reforms.
   ``I could not become the gravedigger of our new policies,'' he
said. ``I told the Russians that we have the overwhelming support
of the people.''
   ``I want to make it clear that there was no counterrevolutionary
threat,'' Dubcek said, contradicting the Kremlin's justification
for the invasion. ``Yet they keep teaching this lie.''
   He was referring to Czechoslovak history books still in use
today.
   Czechoslovakia's current president, Gustav Husak, and current
party leader, Milos Jakes, were among those most active in crushing
Dubcek's reforms.
   Many of the reforms initiated by Dubcek are similar to those now
under way in the Soviet Union, Hungary and Poland.
   While Hungary is slowly rehabilitating the leaders of Hungary's
1956 anti-communist revolt, Jakes last week ruled out Dubcek's
rehabilitation.
   The first installment of the Dubcek interview was shown on April
17.
   On Wednesday, Czechoslovak media reported that Prague's
ambassador to Hungary, Vlastimil Ehrenberger, formally protested
the April 17 broadcast, in which Dubcek attacked former Hungarian
and Polish leaders for not doing more to prevent the 1968 invasion.
   Dubcek spoke in Slovak, dubbed over in Hungarian and translated
into English by The Associated Press.
   Hungarian TV is widely received in southern Slovakia, home to
about 700,000 ethnic Hungarians.
   Czechoslovakia was invaded by Warsaw Pact forces of the Soviet
Union, Hungary, Poland, Bulgaria and East Germany in August 1968.
   Wednesday's late-night broadcast also contained an interview
with Yugoslav dissident Milovan Djilas, who was jailed in the 1950s
and ousted from his senior Communist Party positions after
challenging then Yugoslav leader Josip Broz Tito.
   He spoke mostly on the ethnic tension in Yugoslavia, saying a
system with competing political parties would not necessarily solve
the conflicts and might even foster more nationalism.
</TEXT>
