<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Afghanistan     04-26 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Soviet Union in Bitter Debate Over Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and the United States
traded charges of hypocrisy, lies and bad faith Wednesday in one of
their most acrimonious public exchanges about Afghanistan before
the Security Council.
   Ambassador Patricia Byrne, U.S. representative to the council,
and Soviet Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov, council president
this month, clashed over the issue of U.S. and Pakistani support to
Afghan rebels and Soviet support to the Kabul government.
   Each side accused the other of violating the U.N.-mediated
Geneva accords agreeing to non-interference in the affairs of
Afghanistan and Pakistan. The United States and the Soviet Union
were co-guarantors.
   ``It is the height, or depth of hypocrisy for the representative
of the Soviet Union to claim that the regime in Kabul and the
U.S.S.R. are fulfilling their obligations under the Geneva accords,
and that the United States and Pakistan have failed to do so,''
Ambassador Byrne told the council.
   Belonogov responded: ``As for the nonparliamentary response by
the United States about lies and hypocrisy, it seems to me that the
world community ... has formed a very clear idea about who is
hypocritical and who has been lying in this hall.''
   The council held its seventh meeting in more than two weeks to
hear Afghanistan's complaint that Pakistan is violating the
agreements by arming and training Afghan rebels, sending their arms
to Afghanistan and deploying its own army, intelligence services,
logistics units and militia to fight the Afghan army.
   Pakistan denied the charges, but Ambassador S. Shah Nawaz, in a
scathing speech, would not say from where the arms came or how they
were transported to Afghanistan.
   The United States is known to supply the rebels with Stinger and
Blowpipe missiles and other arms. The Soviet Union supplies the
Kabul government with Scud missiles and other sophisticated weapons.
   The meeting was adjourned without a date being set for another
meeting. No vote or statement was expected.
   Pakistan, which openly aides the Moslem, anti-government rebels,
says it is not directly involved in the conflict. Afghanistan and
the Soviet Union have cited numerous alleged instances of Pakistan
sending armed men and weapons into Afghanistan.
   The Afghan rebels were not party to the Geneva accords and have
rejected it. The Soviet Union has called on the United States to
agree to a joint cut-off in aid to their respective sides, but
Washington has refused.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 to help the Marxist
government battle the Moslem rebels. More than 100,000 Soviet
soldiers were in the country before the withdrawal began in May
1988. The last soldiers left in February.
   Earlier, Pakistan, responding to an Afghan threat, warned the
Security Council it would retaliate against any Afghan aggression
and accused the Soviet Union and Kabul of turning Afghanistan into
a new ``killing fields.''
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, the acting permanent U.N.
representative, told the council: ``The Kabul regime is desperately
clinging to power by force of arms _ through extensive and ongoing
imports of foreign (Soviet) arms _ against the will of the vast
majority of its people.''
   He said the current debate has not furthered either the cause of
peace or the self-determination of the Afghan people.
   ``It is ridiculous to expect the Afghan people to accept as
their freely chosen leader a former secret police chief (Najib) who
was installed by a foreign power,'' Okun said.
   ``The Kabul regime, even with outside help, will inevitably fail
... Pakistan is not and never has been the aggressor.''
</TEXT>
