<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0726 04-26 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Calls on Soviets to Reduce Military Tension in Pacific</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to include speech text; picks up 5th graf
pvs, bgng: ``The two...''; TRIMS at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle on Thursday
challenged the Soviet Union to move from ``rhetoric to reality'' by
taking concrete steps to lessen military tensions in the Pacific.
   Quayle, in his first major address since arriving here less than
24 hours ago, said communism has failed and the world's democracies
must ``capitalize on this triumph.''
   ``We should, because we are strong and prudent, continue to ask
hard questions such as when are the Soviets going to move their
troops out of the northern territories of Japan,'' Quayle said in
remarks prepared for delivery to the National Press Club.
   ``When are the Soviets going to stop providing more modern arms
to North Korea and when will the Soviets actually decrease rather
than increase their military aid to Hanoi to promote peace in
Southeast Asia?'' Quayle said.
   Quayle's first trip to the Pacific comes against a backdrop of
the upcoming Sino-Soviet summit. Next month Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev travels to China for the first summit between the two
countries in 20 years.
   But Quayle said, ``We must challenge the Soviets to move from
rhetoric to reality, from pledges about tension reduction to real
tension-reducing measures.''
   On Thursday, Quayle met with Australian Defense Minister Kim
Beazley and Australia's foreign affairs minister, Gareth Evans.
   Earlier, the vice president held a 90-minute session with Prime
Minister Bob Hawke at which the two discussed economic and defense
issues and the common strains with New Zealand.
   In his speech, Quayle said any minor economic frictions should
not be allowed to harm the strong alliance that has developed
between the United States and Australia.
   The two discussed New Zealand's threat to withdraw from the
ANZUS Council as well as economic issues, according to U.S. and
Australian officials who briefed reporters but refused to be quoted
by name.
   Quayle's visit, timed to coincide with Australian-American
Friendship Week, comes at a time when the relationship between the
allies is in ``excellent shape,'' the Australian official said. He
categorized the discussions as ``very friendly indeed,'' and said
the two might try to hold additional talks before Quayle leaves the
city on Thursday.
   Of concern to the leaders, however, was the threat by New
Zealand Prime Minister David Lange to withdraw from the
Australian-New Zealand-U.S. defense alliance, known as ANZUS. Lange
made his comments in the United States earlier this week.
   New Zealand has been excluded from the ANZUS Council since Lange
announced in 1984 that his government would not allow nuclear ships
to visit New Zealand ports. However, that country has not formally
withdrawn from the ministerial council.
   Quayle raised the issue of New Zealand in an attempt to gauge
the seriousness of New Zealand's threat, but Hawke was unable to
tell him whether Lange's speech amounted to a fundamental shift in
New Zealand policy, the U.S. and Australian officials said.
   Hawke also talked about initiatives for greater Pacific regional
cooperation on economic matters, ones that Quayle said the United
States supported, the officials said.
   The vice president also told Hawke that the U.S. decision to
subsidize grain exports was not designed to hurt Australia. The
Australians have complained that such subsidies hurt their wheat
exports.
</TEXT>
