<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Eskimos     04-26 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Eskimos,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Round up Eskimos at Anti-NATO Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOOSE BAY, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military and federal police
dragged about 50 Eskimos from a runway at an air base Wednesday to
break up a protest against low-level NATO flights, a military
spokesman said.
   For the past seven months, the Eskimos have mounted a series of
such protests at the Goose Bay air base, which they say is built on
their ancestral hunting grounds.
   The Innu Eskimos got onto the base Wednesday by cutting through
a gate, said Lt. Col. Robert Jodoin, a Canadian Forces spokesman.
He said the men, women, and children then fanned out across a
runway, yelling, ``We don't want NATO!''
   They were herded into military buses and police cars. The chief
of the local Innu, Daniel Ashini, was among those rounded up, a
spokesman for the protesters said on condition of anonymity.
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police could not say afterward how
many demostrators were kept in custody.
   Those arrested will be charged under military regulations with
trespassing, Jodoin said.
   The demonstration followed last week's acquittal by a provincial
court of four Eskimos who were charged with public mischief for
protesting last fall at the base on this Canadian island province
in the Atlantic Ocean.
   In his landmark ruling, Judge James Igloliorte cleared the four
on the basis that they honestly believe the ground where the base
is located belongs to the Eskimos.
   The Eskimos say the low-level flights are turning their
ancestral hunting grounds into a war zone. The North Atlantic
Treaty Organization flights are made by Canada, West Germany,
Britain, and the Netherlands.
   The military says the Eskimos are using the protests to pressure
the government in longstanding territorial disputes.
</TEXT>
