<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Iran-Contra 2ndLd-Writethru a0796 04-26 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Iran-Contra, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0796,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Ask Investigation into Why Iran-Contra Panel Didn't Get
Documents</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``White House...'' with 2 grafs to
add further details on Gray letter; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``Boren,
in...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three senior members of the Senate Iran-Contra
investigating committee asked Wednesday for an congressional
intelligence committee probe into why the panel did not receive
crucial Reagan administration documents that have come out at the
trial of Oliver North.
   An initial review by Senate staff members found that four
documents introduced as evidence in North's trial never were turned
over to congressional investigators in 1987 when they looked into
the administration's Iran arms deal and Contra support initiatives.
   Two other documents in the committee's files are similar to ones
released at the trial, but are missing important attachments or
notations.
   One document, an April 25, 1985, memo from then-National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane, recommends that Reagan telephone
Honduran President Roberto Suazo to reassure him of U.S. backing
for the Contras. Missing from the congressional copy is the
notation, ``cc Vice President,'' apparently signaling that George
Bush was sent a copy of the memo.
   ``These six documents are sufficient to raise questions about
the procedures followed by the executive branch in providing
documents to the Iran-Contra Committee and the completeness of its
compliance with agreements on the provision of documents,'' said a
letter asking for the investigation.
   The request was sent to Sens. David Boren, D-Okla., and William
Cohen, R-Maine, chairman and vice chairman of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, and was signed by Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, and Sens. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, and
Warren Rudman, R-N.H., the chairman and vice chairman of the
Iran-Contra panel.
   President Bush's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, told reporters
aboard Air Force One on Wednesday, ``We will cooperate in any way
we can, but otherwise we don't know much about it.
   ``This doesn't involve us directly,'' Fitzwater said. ``This is
between the senators and the intelligence committee. They're
looking into the last administration's procedures and it doesn't
relate to us. It's an internal matter for the Senate to look into.''
   White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray, in a letter to Mitchell,
said his office had contacted Arthur B. Culvahouse Jr., who was
Reagan's counsel during much of the time at issue, and that
Culvahouse has offered to review the matter and informally brief
the senators.
   ``We have confidence that the last administration followed the
agreed procedures (for releasing the material) and that its
representatives will be able to address your concerns,'' Gray's
letter said. ``We, of course endeavor to be as helpful as we
can...''
   Boren, in a statement, promised to ``look at this matter
expeditiously and in a businesslike, non-political manner.''
   The letter said some of the documents contain key evidence about
the way U.S. officials conducted policy in Central America in 1985
``and raise questions regarding ... possible efforts to circumvent
the provisions of the law'' which barred direct or indirect U.S.
aid to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   A similar request was made two weeks ago by Rep. Lee Hamilton,
D-Ind., who was chairman of the House Iran-Contra committee. An
aide to Hamilton said Wednesday that he had not yet received a
response to his request of White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray.
   The congressional committees, after an extensive investigation,
concluded that a ``cabal of ... zealots'' in the Reagan
administration seized control of policy in the affair which sent
weapons to Iran and profits from the sales to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   But documents and testimony during the North trial suggest that
senior officials up to and including Reagan and then-vice president
George Bush were more involved in the affair than the committees
knew.
   Among documents which the congressional panels did not receive
were a Feb. 19, 1985, memo outlining a plan to step up U.S. aid to
Honduras in return for that nation's support of the Contras, and a
memo dated the following day making it clear that the
administration knew it was forbidden from providing aid under those
circumstances.
   Also not turned over to congressional investigators was an Oct.
30, 1985, memo from North to McFarlane about reconnaissance of
Nicaragua and mentioning the air drop of two recoilless rifles to
the rebels.
   Mark Belnick, a New York attorney who was on the staff of the
Senate panel, said the documents clearly should have been sent in
response to congressional requests and would have been helpful in
the investigation. But he added, ``If this is the sum and
substance, ... they wouldn't have materially changed any of the
conclusions'' reached by investigators.
</TEXT>
