<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionProtests     04-26 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protests,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Around Nation As Supreme Court Hears Arguments in Abortion
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN W. OATIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   She was nervous, like thousands of young women who have gone
before her.
   Still, the 23-year-old woman made final arrangements Wednesday
for her abortion at the St. Louis clinic that challenged Missouri's
restrictions on the procedure.
   She said she was afraid the showdown in the U.S. Supreme Court
``might change things.''
   ``I wanted the services to be available to me legally,'' said
the woman, who asked that her name not be used. ``My finances won't
let me have another child. I think I should have the right to
choose.''
   While the tension at the Reproductive Health Services clinic was
subdued, thousands of protesters from California to Connecticut
staged demonstrations on both sides of the issue.
   ``This is a monumental day of reckoning for women's lives in the
U.S.,'' Victoria Lambert said in Atlanta, where about 800
pro-choice demonstrators marched at the Georgia Capitol.
   The St. Louis clinic initiated the case of Webster vs.
Reproductive Health Services by challenging restrictions in
Missouri's abortion law. The Supreme Court could use its ruling in
the case to tighten or even overturn its landmark 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision legalizing abortion.
   ``There were more concerns in the waiting room this morning,''
said Amelia McCracken, the clinic's director of community
education. ``There is an awareness, an edge today that I haven't
seen previously.''
   The increasingly bitter debate has made it even more difficult
for women coming to the clinic to make a decision, said Jody Sova,
director of counseling at the clinic.
   ``Abortion has always been a very serious, difficult choice for
women,'' Sova said. ``Anytime something like this is fought over in
public, it adds to the difficulty.''
   In Sacramento, Calif., about 2,000 pro-choice demonstrators
rallied at the state capitol as a half-dozen abortion opponents
rallied nearby.
   Placard-carrying abortion foes approached the rally, but were
surrounded by poster-toting pro-choice demonstrators. State police
separated the two groups, then stayed between them throughout the
protest.
   ``This is not a women's issue,'' actor Tim Busfield, who plays
Elliot Weston on ABC's ``thirtysomething,'' told the pro-choice
rally. ``It's a family issue. It's a human rights issue.''
   Nola Jones, who said she had two abortions before becoming an
abortion foe, told reporters that ``abortion is a major death
experience. Women cannot participate in the death of their own
child and not be psychologically impaired.''
   In Baton Rouge, La., state Rep. Woody Jenkins introduced a bill
declaring abortion centers public nuisances in the event the high
court overturns Roe vs. Wade.
   Jenkins, a Democrat, has drafted most of the state anti-abortion
laws that parallel Missouri's.
   In Raleigh, N.C., more than 800 pro-choice demonstrators shouted
slogans and carried white coat hangers dipped in red paint to
symbolize back-alley abortions.
   About 300 people attended a pro-choice rally at the University
of California at Berkeley in the culmination of an on-campus vigil
that has been going on for days.
   Rallies were also held in Albany, N.Y.; at Yale Law School in
New Haven, Conn.; Columbus, Ohio; and Fort Wayne, Ind.
   Operation Rescue, which has mounted a series of major
anti-abortion protests aimed at blocking access to clinics, is
planning protests in 65 cities Friday and Saturday, said
spokeswoman Barbara Magera in Binghamton, N.Y.
   She said the group would work for a ``human life amendment'' to
the Constitution, and would seek bans on abortion in individual
states in the event the Supreme Court overturns Roe vs. Wade.
</TEXT>
