<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Cabinet     04-26 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Cabinet,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Asks For Resignation of Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing military President Augusto
Pinochet asked for the resignation of all 15 of his Cabinet members
Wednesday to allow changes in some posts, a government spokesman
said.
   The measure coincided with local media reports that Gen.
Pinochet had disagreements with his interior minister, Carlos
Caceres, over proposed democratic reforms.
   No official explanation was given for the shake-up, however. The
government declined to say what portfolios would be changed.
   It is customary in Chile for all Cabinet ministers to hand in
letters of resignation even when only one or two changes are
planned.
   The government spokesman, army Gen. Jaime Garcia, told
journalists at the government palace that the resignations were
requested at a 70-minute meeting of Pinochet and his full Cabinet
late in the day.
   ``He expressed his intention of making changes in the current
Cabinet,'' Garcia said. He said Pinochet ``is evaluating the
current political situation'' and asked all government ministers to
hand in their resignations so the president would have ``freedom of
action.''
   Garcia did not say when the changes would be announced. ``There
is no date yet for swearing in the new Cabinet,'' Garcia said.
   According to some local news reports, Pinochet and Caceres have
differed over proposed amendments to the country's 1980
constitution and other legal reforms.
   According to the reports, Caceres wants to allow several
democratic reforms sought by opposition political groups before
scheduled Dec. 14 national elections to pick a successor to
Pinochet and a Congress. Pinochet has said he will remain army
commander after the elections.
   Pinochet, who seized power in a violent 1973 coup, was forced to
call the elections when he lost a yes-or-no referendum last October
on a proposal to extend his rule to 1997.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
