<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Airport     04-26 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Airport,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Okinawa Relocates Airport to Protect Reef</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Okinawa has decided to move the
proposed site of an airport to protect a rare blue coral reef,
officials announced Wednesday.
   The government of the Japanese prefecture, changing a 7-year-old
plan, decided to build the new airport 2.5 miles north of the
original site on the east coast of Ishigaki Island, Japanese
Environment Agency official Masaaki Sakurai said.The location is
1,140 miles southeast of Tokyo.
   Okinawa Governor Junji Nishime said the regional government
chose the new site as the best alternative to protect the coral
reef.
   Environmentalists had warned that under the original plan, the
coral would have been buried in concrete. They said there are about
130 species of coral in the reef.
