<FIRST>u i AM-Australia-FloodDeath 2ndLd-Writethru a0805 04-26 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Flood Death, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0805,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Professor Washed Away By Floodwaters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of Pawling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISBANE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American professor drowned when
floodwaters swept his four-wheel drive vehicle from a bridge over a
raging river, police said Thursday.
   Steve Johnson, 41, a former resident of Pawling, N.Y., was
trapped on the roof of his vehicle before being swept away
Wednesday by the rising waters of the swollen Little Nerang River.
   The vehicle apparently had stalled on the bridge, police said
Thursday. They later reported finding his body.
   Johnson was a professor at the Law and Business School at Bond
University in the Gold Coast region of Queensland state.
   Witnesses said fast-rising floodwaters had forced Johnson out of
his vehicle. They said they watched as he stood on the roof of the
vehicle, but were unable to reach him.
   ``We were hoping he would grab onto a tree or something,'' said
Kerry Anstey, an eyewitness. ``We saw him dragged under into a deep
hole in the creek. He surfaced again, then disappeared.''
   Johnson's vehicle later was discovered two miles downstream,
near where the body was discovered.
   Johnson was previously the coordinator of doctoral programs in
accounting at the Wharton School at the University of Pennsylvania
and at the Graduate School of Business of Columbia University in
New York, said Bond University spokesman Professor Don Watts. He
was married and had two children.
   Johnson was the second victim of bad weather that produced wild
storms and heavy seas along Queensland's southeast coast Tuesday
and Wednesday.
   A man was electrocuted Tuesday night north of Brisbane after
trying to start a generator during a blackout. Power lines were
damaged by a storm.
   At Lismore, in the north of New South Wales state, a man was
rescued by police early Thursday after he was swept away by
floodwaters and clung to a tree for two hours.
</TEXT>
