<FIRST>r a AM-AlteredResume     04-26 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Altered Resume,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Administrator Who Used False Resumes Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who officials say used bogus
resumes and references to land government jobs across the country
was ordered Wednesday to serve 90 days in jail and pay $18,000 in
restitution to an Alaska village.
   Carl Keyser Jr., 34, was sentenced on a first-degree theft
charge stemming from his brief tenure as Kake city administrator
last year. He pleaded no contest to the felony charge, which
alleged he took $28,000 in salary, benefits and expenses before he
was fired in December.
   Superior Court Judge Thomas Schultz placed Keyser on probation
for seven years, ordered him not to accept any government job
during that time and gave him credit for 60 days of jail time
already served.
   Schultz rejected Keyser's request to be freed without additional
jail time, and ordered him to write lettrs of apology to the towns
of Kake and Pikeville, Ky., as well as serve the final 30 days of
the sentence.
   ``This is pretty reprehensible conduct,'' the judge said of
Keyser's employment record.
   District Attorney Mark Ells said he will dismiss a
theft-by-deception charge filed against Keyser by officials in
Pikeville, where Keyser was employed briefly as city manager in
August. Keyser sent the city $707 in restitution Tuesday, and the
Pikeville prosecutor asked to drop the charge, Ells said.
   The Pikeville restitution represented expense money Keyser was
paid before he resigned amid allegations he faked his resume.
   ``What I did here was wrong,'' said Keyser, who is married and
has four daughters. ``I lied on my resume because I needed a job to
feed my family, and instead of doing it the right way ... I took
too many shortcuts.''
   Keyser said he would move once he finished serving his time in
jail, but was unsure where. His lawyer, Mary Treiber, said Keyser
was considering a move to Seattle.
   Schultz said Keyser could move out of Petersburg, where he has
been unable to find a job since posting bail. But the judge
expressed concern that Keyser would try to get a government job
again, and ordered him to check monthly with his probation officer
in Alaska.
   ``I'm not sure that Mr. Keyser is going to be able to make the
kind of money honestly that he made lying,'' the judge said.
   Schultz did not order Keyser to pay the $28,000 in restitution
the state requested, saying Kake did get some value from his work.
   Residents of Kake, a small fishing and timber town on the
northern tip of Kupreanof Island in southeast Alaska, became
suspicious of Keyser shortly after he arrived to take the
$44,000-a-year administrator's job.
   He bought a luxurious $66,000 double mobile home, rifles and
1,000 rounds of ammunition with city money, and refused to release
his resume for public inspection.
   A check of police records revealed the outstanding Kentucky
warrant in December, and he was arrested.
   Interviews with prosecutors and city officials in several states
revealed that at least 19 of Keyser's jobs since 1980 were with
city or county governments. Records and the interviews showed
Keyser used false information to obtain at least 11 of the jobs.
   Law enforcement officials said Keyser apparently earned a living
by cashing as many salary and expense checks as he could before his
bosses became suspicious and he either quit or was fired.
   Wednesday's sentence was the second time Keyser has been
convicted of a charge stemming from his false resumes.
   Keyser, a native of Huntington, W.Va., was placed on a year's
probation after pleading guilty to a misdemeanor perjury charge in
Oak Hill, Fla. The charge alleged he used false information to get
hired as Oak Hill police chief. He was fired after four months when
the discrepancies in his resume were reported in the news media.
   Other states in which Keyser allegedly applied or obtained jobs
under false pretenses include Idaho, Oregon, South Carolina, Texas,
West Virginia and Wyoming.
</TEXT>
