<SECOND>AM-Magazine Awards,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sports Illustrated Wins Top Magazine Society Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sports Illustrated, Vanity Fair, American
Heritage and The Sciences won National Magazine Awards on Wednesday
for general excellence in their circulation categories.
   ``There is no prize, no honor that is any greater,'' said Sports
Illustrated Managing Editor Mark Mulvoy during a ceremony at the
Waldorf-Astoria hotel. ``Thank you, thank you, thank you!''
   Outside the Waldorf, the Women and AIDS Network held a small
demonstration and passed out leaflets blasting Cosmopolitan
magazine, which had been nominated for general excellence with
Sports Illustrated, Reader's Digest and Parents in the category for
magazines with over 1 million circulation.
   Seventy finalists had emerged from among 1,225 submissions by
285 magazines.
   Tina Brown, editor-in-chief of Vanity Fair, accepted an award
for general excellence in the 400,000 to 1 million circulation
category. Her husband, Harold Evans, editor-in-chief of Conde Nast
Traveler, won the special interests category.
   The award winners were:
   _General Excellence, over 1 million circulation, Sports
Illustrated, Mark Mulvoy, managing editor.
   _General Excellence, 400,000 to 1 million circulation, Vanity
Fair, Tina Brown, editor-in-chief.
   _General Excellence, 100,000 to 400,000 circulation, American
Heritage, Byron Dobell, editor.
   _General Excellence, under 100,000 circulation, The Sciences,
Paul T. Libassi, editor.
   _Personal Service, Good Housekeeping, John Mack Carter,
editor-in-chief, for ``Child Care '88.''
   _Special Interests, Conde Nast Traveler, Harold Evans,
editor-in-chief, for ``The Ultimate Island Finder,'' ``Bush
Intelligence'' and ``Bring the Kids.''
   _Reporting, The New Yorker, Robert Gottlieb, editor, for ``A
Reporter At Large: Teheran Summer,'' by Robin Wright.
   _Feature Writing, Esquire, Lee Eisenberg, editor-in-chief, for
``The Transformation of Johnny Spain,'' by Chip Brown.
   _Public Interest, California, B.K. Moran, editorial director,
for two articles by Cindy Ehrlich on the prescription drug Halcion.
   _Design, Rolling Stone, Jann S. Wenner, editor and publisher,
Fred Woodward, art director.
   _Photography, National Geographic, Wilbur E. Garrett, editor.
   _Fiction, The New Yorker, Robert Gottlieb, editor, for ``White
Angel,'' by Michael Cunningham; ``I Read My Nephew Stories,'' by
Ethan Mordden; and ``We,'' by Mary Grimm.
   _Essays and Criticism, Harper's Magazine, Lewis H. Lapham,
editor, for ``The Urge For An End,'' by Edward Hoagland; ``Who Won
the West?'' by William Kittredge; and ``I'm Black, You're White,
Who's Innocent?'' by Shelby Steele.
   _Single-Topic Issue, Hippocrates, Eric W. Schrier, editor, for
``Choices of the Heart,'' about medical ethics.
