<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conditions shifted in U.S. society
between 1950 and 1970 and ``it is no longer natural, normal and
American to grow up Christian,'' says the Rev. William H. Willimon,
a Duke University professor.
   ``Paganism is in the air we breath and the water we drink,''
Willimon, a United Methodist, said in a lecture at Southern Baptist
Theological Seminary. ``If our children grow up in faith, we are
going to have to put them there.''
   He said the ``world has declared war on the church in the most
subtle ways.'' Therefore, he said, Christians must form strong
worshipping communities because ``being a Christian is too
difficult a way to walk alone.''
