<DOCNO> AP890426-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:Sanctuary Adv01   04-26 0967</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Sanctuary, Adv 01,0997</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance For Release Monday PMs, May 1, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sanctuary Workers Say Refugee Surge Could Revive Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Toney is cq in 25th graf, bgn, `What is ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rules of the border rarely change.
   Despite the ``Not Welcome'' signs, Central American refugees
keep coming. Despite the immigration service's recent crackdown and
new detention camps, they stream by the thousand to the United
States.
   And despite criminal convictions, waning interest around the
country and little money, Southside Presbyterian Church, home and
heart of the sanctuary movement, is still welcoming and
transporting refugees who want to make America home.
   This scraggly, pale blue barrio church spawned an international
underground railroad seven years ago by declaring itself a
sanctuary for illegal aliens. Now Southside is making another
statement.
   The church plans to break ground this summer on an addition that
will double its size and for the first time provide bedrooms for
aliens, who have slept on the chapel's floor over the past seven
years.
   The addition is a sign of the movement's uneasy truce with
federal authorities, its survival despite eight members' felony
convictions and its struggle to cope with the recent wave of new
business.
   ``It's a recognition that we're in it for the long haul, that
we're going through a transition from emergency assistance to
institutionalizing this thing,'' said Southside's lanky,
blue-jeaned minister, John Fife, the sanctuary movement's founder.
   ``We're still doing sanctuary, and we're doing so quite
publicly.''
   Fife, who is currently free on five years' probation, and others
here have continued to sneak refugees across the U.S.-Mexico border
about once a week, sheltering immigrants in Southside every night,
and helping move them along to other U.S. cities or Canada.
   In the last six months, church workers aiding aliens say they
have seen a new wave of Central Americans heading north to escape
war and economic troubles.
   The new flood of aliens and a resulting border crackdown in
south Texas by the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service may
well mean revival of the sanctuary movement, which federal
authorities have declared dead, Fife and others said.
   ``In the last six months, we've sent more individuals into
sanctuary congregations than the previous two years combined,''
Fife said.
   ``It's really picked up since the first of the year,'' agreed
the Rev. Gustau Shultz, head of the National Sanctuary Defense Fund.
   In Tucson, the sanctuary movement has chosen to ward off the INS
by staying out in the open. Federal officials are notified of all
actions _ even plans to construct a new building. When there are
mailings or notices, the INS is sent a copy.
   ``What we do on the border has become routine, almost
bureaucratic,'' said Jim Corbett, a Quaker who helped found the
movement with Fife and who was one of three acquitted in the Tucson
trial. Sanctuary workers send letters informing the INS of each
border crossing.
   Volunteers now fear stumbling into drug smugglers on the border
more than Border Patrol agents.
   Indeed, when the local jails or detention centers fill up, even
the authorities deliver aliens to Southside, where they know they
will be housed and fed. One night, three Tucson police squad cars
delivered 16 Guatemalans, Fife said.
   The federal government, which used informants and bugged Bible
study groups to build its case in Tucson, apparently pays the
movement little attention now, as the nationwide network of
sanctuary churches has largely faded away.
   Today, aliens prefer to slip into cities such as Los Angeles and
Miami or go on to Canada. Most volunteers have gone on to other
efforts.
   ``We're seeing a more contemporary manifestation of sanctuary,''
said Shultz. ``It's really turning much more to some direct
services, helping people find housing, assisting with medical care,
education, jobs.''
   Shultz said he recently polled some of the 500 congregations
that had publicly declared themselves part of sanctuary in the
mid-1980s. About 25 percent were still assisting some refugees. The
others were asked if they were still willing.
   ``Some said yes, some no. I'd say more were willing than were
not,'' Shultz said.
   Along the border in Texas, New Mexico and Arizona, only a
handful of sanctuary activists continue moving aliens on their own,
with help from established refugee shelters and a few churches.
Most, intimidated by the government's actions, prefer to remain
anonymous and secret.
   ``What is done here in New Mexico is done very quietly,'' said
Glen Remer-Thamert, an Albuquerque, N.M., Lutheran minister
acquitted of smuggling charges last year on the basis of former
Gov. Toney Anaya's 1986 state sanctuary declaration.
   Albuquerque has only one declared sanctuary church, and it
houses no refugees. A few people still secretly move refugees, but
most of the work focuses on direct social services, said Jane
Bergquist, New Mexico's Sanctuary Defense Fund representative.
   INS officials maintain those in Tucson and Albuquerque who faced
charges were smugglers. Although INS district director Bill
Johnston in Tucson meets with Corbett and others, he warned, ``If
somebody from my office encountered illegal activity, we would
still today arrest them.''
   Fife and Corbett believe that since they have continued their
activities and the INS has not acted, they have established
themselves as part of the quilt of U.S. immigration.
   ``I think what we've established simply by keeping on is de
facto acceptance of the church voluntarily protecting refugees and
functioning as a human rights organization on the border,'' Fife
said.
   As for the movement's relationship with the government, Corbett
doesn't think the INS will plant informants again.
   ``There's no reason for them to infiltrate,'' he said. ``They're
on our mailing list.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon May 1</NOTE>
