<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-26 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0871</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wages and salaries paid U.S. workers in
private industry rose 4.2 percent in the last 12 months, the
biggest jump in 3{ years, the government said in a report that
showed increasing inflationary pressures from tight labor markets.
   But the Labor Department's Employment Cost Index and other
economic reports issued Tuesday brought mixed predictions of
whether a recession is inevitable or could be averted by slower
growth in the record seventh year of the economy's expansion.
   Separately, the government reported that contracts settled
through collective bargaining in the past three months provided
workers average annual pay raises of 3.1 percent during the life of
the pacts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes dropped 4.3 percent in
March, the third straight monthly decline, as rising mortgage
interest rates made more inroads into the housing market, a real
estate trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Tuesday that sales of
existing single-family homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 3.33 million units in March, the slowest pace since
February 1988.
   Sales had dropped 2 percent in February and 9.4 percent in
January.
</TEXT>
