lawsuits and 1,300 claims ranging from $500 to $4 million in
connection with last month's Alaskan oil spill and expects further
suits as well as government fines.
   Top executives of the nation's biggest oil company said Tuesday
that Exxon already had paid $400,000 to settle smaller claims
brought mainly by fishermen and cannery workers whose jobs were
disrupted because of the March 24 spill that fouled hundreds of
miles of coastline.
   Exxon executives declined to put a dollar value on the existing
lawsuits or the claims.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. will sell about half
its retail brokerage business to Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
under a deal announced one week after the junk-bond giant disclosed
restructuring plans stemming from involvement in the Wall Street
insider trading scandal.
   Smith Barney would get 19 Drexel offices, including its largest
retail branches, and about 500 of Drexel's biggest-producing
account executives, Drexel said Tuesday.
   Neither firm disclosed a sale price, but Wall Street brokerage
experts have said the entire business is worth $50 million to $200
million.
