<FIRST>r f PM-IMC-ToucheRoss     04-26 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IMC-Touche Ross,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Sues Touche Ross For More Than $100 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida has filed suit against Touche
Ross &amp; Co. for more than $100 million in damages as the
court-appointed receiver for now-insolvent International Medical
Centers Inc.
   The lawsuit seeks to recover damages due to alleged gross
negligence, breach of fiduciary duty and negligent
misrepresentations by the auditor, according to a news release
Tuesday by the Florida Department of Insurance.
   IMC, once Florida's largest health maintenance organization, was
declared insolvent and placed in receivership May 14, 1987.
   ``As a regulator, we rely upon companies to submit audited
financial information that is accurate,'' State Treasurer and
Insurance Commissioner Tom Gallagher said. ``If it is not, we can't
do our job and carry out the law.''
   Robert W. Mannix, associate general counsel for Touche Ross at
the company's headquarters in New York, said the Big Eight
accounting firm had conducted IMC audits thoroughly and
professionally.
   Mannix also said that Florida's insurance department had been
conducting its own examinations and was fully informed of events
and developments at IMC before taking over the HMO.
   ``This phenomenon of regulators suing Big Eight accounting firms
in an effort to blame the accounting profession for the regulators'
own failings has become quite familiar lately,'' Mannix said.
   Miguel Recarey Jr., former president of IMC, fled the country in
1987 in the face of indictments on federal charges including
wire-tapping, bribery and embezzlement in the wake of the collapse
of IMC.
   The insurance department also sued Touche Ross in April 1988,
claiming that the firm should have informed the state that IMC was
due a $2.2 million federal income tax refund. The refund paid to
Recarey Enterprises eventually went to Miguel Recarey just before
he fled.
</TEXT>
