<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Tickets Bjt   04-26 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Tickets, Bjt,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Eastern Two Weeks to Work Out New Refund Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has been given two weeks to
reach an accord with travel agents on a new policy for
ticketholders seeking refunds due to the 7-week-old strike against
the carrier.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland, who is overseeing
Eastern's Chapter 11 reorganization, held a brief hearing Tuesday
on the matter. He then adjourned the session for two weeks.
   Zack Clement, an attorney representing Miami-based Eastern, said
the airline will try to reach an accord with the American Society
of Travel Agents and plans to propose a new refund plan to the
court in a few weeks.
   ASTA has petitioned the court to require Eastern to pay refunds
on unused tickets to travel agents, who would pass the refunds on
to their customers.
   The airline has said its debts include about $165 million in
unused tickets issued before its March 9 bankruptcy filing in the
New York court. Eastern estimates it sells 75 percent of its
tickets through travel agents.
   Under Eastern's current policy, consumers holding unused tickets
purchased before the Chapter 11 filing have several options but
must apply for any refunds directly from Eastern.
   The customers can use the tickets to fly their original
itineraries on existing Eastern flights where available _ the
carrier has been operating only about 10 percent of its pre-strike
schedule _ or on sister carrier Continental Airlines if seats are
available.
   Alternatively, consumers can apply for refunds from credit card
companies for tickets they charged on the cards or can apply to the
bankruptcy court as unsecured creditors.
   Although airlines generally honor each other's tickets, charging
a fee for the service, competitors stopped honoring Eastern tickets
after it filed for bankruptcy protection from creditors.
   ``There's a lot of hardship'' for Eastern ticketholders, James
Flug, an attorney representing Consumers Union, told Lifland. The
situation breeds ill-will toward the airline, Flug said.
   Consumers Union, the non-profit consumer advocacy group that
publishes Consumer Reports magazine, has joined the travel agents'
petition, seeking to broaden it to include passengers who purchased
tickets individually rather than through agents. The group has
asked the court to require Eastern to reimburse those passengers
before the company pays off other creditors.
   The Consumers Union request ``clearly requires the payment of
more than the company can afford to pay,'' Clement told Lifland.
   At an earlier hearing Tuesday, Brian Bradford, Eastern's
director of cash management and credit, said the airline has about
$183 million in cash on hand. That reserve is expected to drop to
about $107 million by the end of May, excluding proceeds from any
asset sales made before then, he said.
   Eastern, a unit of Texas Air Corp. of Houston, told its major
creditors Monday that it intends to sell its Northeast shuttle
service and its Philadelphia hub as part of a plan to rebuild as a
smaller carrier. Those two sales, which must be approved by
creditors and the bankruptcy court, would give Eastern a cash
balance of just under $500 million, Bradford said.
   Clayton Glasgow, the airline's director of financial performance
analysis, told the hearing that Eastern is losing about $1 million
a day.
   In a statement Tuesday, the Air Line Pilots Association
criticized Eastern's downsizing plan as unrealistic.
   The union, which represents Eastern pilots, most of whom have
walked off the job, said the plan cannot be realized because the
company won't be able to hire and train the 1,700 pilots it says it
needs. The union also questioned the carrier's belief that the plan
would lead to profitability since the airline still would be
saddled with high fixed costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel Bjt  04-26 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel, Bjt, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel Selling Half Its Retail Brokerage Business To Smith Barney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venerable Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. is
buying about half of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s retail brokerage
business in a deal Drexel hopes will help it shed the stigma of the
Wall Street insider trading scandal.
   The sale announced Tuesday came a week after the 157-year-old
firm, a leading purveyor of debt securities called junk bonds,
disclosed restructuring plans that included the sale of the retail
network and a 33 percent cut in staff.
   The restructuring was prompted partly by bad publicity due to an
intensive federal fraud probe of Drexel and the historic settlement
of securities fraud charges stemming from the scandal that surfaced
more than two years ago. The settlement raised the prospect that
Drexel could lose its broker license in some states.
   Smith Barney would get 19 Drexel offices, including some of its
largest retail branches, and about 500 of Drexel's
biggest-producing account executives.
   Neither firm disclosed a sale price, but Wall Street brokerage
experts have said the entire division was worth $50 million to $200
million.
   Drexel said it would sell the remainder of its 43-office
brokerage network piecemeal and ``will be working with our branch
people to assure the orderly transition of those offices.''
   Spokesman Steven Anreder declined to say whether any sales were
under negotiation or to elaborate on the fate of the 600 other
account executives in the unsold offices.
   For Smith Barney, a 115-year-old firm with a stodgy image
symbolized by television ads that its brokers ``make money the old
fashioned way _ they earn it,'' the addition of Drexel offices and
people would mark a major step in its effort to become a more
powerful force in the brokerage business.
   Smith Barney is a unit of Primerica Corp., a diversified
financial services company based in Greenwich, Conn. The brokerage
has said it wants to become bigger, more specialized and more
profitable.
   Primerica stock fell 25 cents Tuesday to close at $20.87{ a
share in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Drexel said the offices to be sold to Smith Barney include
branches in Manhattan; Boca Raton, Miami Beach and Miami, Fla;
Baton Rouge and New Orleans, La; Boston; Denver; Encino and Palo
Alto, Calif; Houston; Paramus, N.J.; Providence, R.I.; Rockville,
Md; St. Louis, Mo.; Scottsdale, Ariz; Washington, D.C.; and White
Plains, N.Y.
   Smith Barney will get the leases, furniture and fixtures in all
branches as part of the deal.
   Drexel was the biggest target of a federal investigation that
grew out of revelations provided by stock speculator Ivan Boesky,
the inside trader serving a three-year prison term.
   As part of an agreement to settle criminal and civil fraud
charges, Drexel agreed to pay $650 million in fines, plead guilty
to six felonies and subject itself to unprecedented federal
scrutiny of the way it does business.
   Drexel is privately owned and does not disclose earnings or
revenue figures, although it is considered one of Wall Street's
biggest and most profitable firms. Drexel has said the brokerage
unit accounts for only about 10 percent of overall business and
that its primary money-maker is the firm's leading role in the $175
billion junk bond market.
   The sale to Smith Barney came a day after three Drexel workers
affected by the restructuring filed a class-action suit accusing
the firm's top managers with breach of contract and violations of
their duties.
   The suit, filed in New York State Supreme Court in Manhattan,
contends that the sale of the unit will cost the brokers millions
of dollars because they will be forced to sell their Drexel stock
for far below its true value. Drexel officials have declined to
comment on the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TinyTelephone     04-26 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tiny Telephone,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Introduces Smaller Cellular Phone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. has introduced a dramatically
smaller cellular telephone that can be carried in a purse or coat
pocket.
   The device, half the size of any other portable cellular model,
is about as wide and long as a checkbook. It is about as thick as a
fat wallet at the earpiece while tapering down to half the
thickness of a deck of cards at the mouthpiece.
   The phone, introduced here Tuesday, has a shorter-than-usual
battery life. The 10.7-ounce model has a 30-minute rechargeable
battery, while the 12.3-ounce one has a 75-minute battery. It needs
no wires or base to operate.
   The device, called the Micro Tac Personal Telephone, is expected
to retail for $2,995 and be available six weeks after being
ordered. Motorola officials said they were taking orders
immediately.
   ``This is a new category of cellular _ the personal cellular,''
said Jim Bernhart, vice president and director of distribution for
Motorola's cellular subscriber group. ``We view it as the wave of
the future.''
   Officials of the Schaumburg, Ill.-based company would not reveal
development costs for the new device, but said the company had
invested about $350 million in development of cellular telephones.
   Bob Weisshappel, Motorola vice president and director of the
North American subscriber division, said the device has the
identical range to the company's larger, Dynatac portable.
   Cellular telephones work as radio transmitters and receivers.
Metropolitan areas offering cellular service are divided up into
sections called cells, with each cell containing a
receiving-transmitting antenna to connect many calls simultaneously
with the local phone system.
   According to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association, the United States has about 2 million cellular
subscribers. Nearly 839,000 subscribers were added in 1988, the
association said.
   In the last six months of 1988, cellular service revenues were
$1.07 billion, and the average monthly cellular phone bill was
$98.02, the association said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
