<HEAD>Keating Re-Elected Chairman Of AP Board, Emmerich Elected Vice Chairman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No period after H in Howard H (aim) Hays Jr., 9th graf, is correct.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Keating, president of the Detroit
Newspaper Agency, has been re-elected chairman of the board of
directors of The Associated Press. John O. Emmerich Jr. of The
Greenwood (Miss.) Commonwealth was elected vice chairman.
   Louis D. Boccardi was re-elected president and general manager.
   The reorganization meeting Tuesday included the seating of four
new directors.
   Other AP management officers re-elected for one-year terms were
James F. Tomlinson, vice president and secretary; Patrick T.
O'Brien, vice president and treasurer, and vice presidents Claude
E. Erbsen, Walter R. Mears, John W. Reid and Wick Temple.
   Also re-elected from the AP were assistant secretaries
Lieselotte Jedelhauser, Lee Perryman and James R. Williams, and
assistant treasurers Frederick R. Barberi, Paul H. Jenssen and
Roger P. Sturm.
   Four incumbent members of the AP board were re-elected and three
new members were elected Monday by the membership at the AP's
annual meeting.
   David R. Bradley Jr. of the News-Press@Gazette of St. Joseph,
Mo.; Frank A. Daniels Jr. of the Raleigh (N.C.) News &amp; Observer and
Times; Chairman Keating; and Harold R. Lifvendahl of The Orlando
(Fla.) Sentinel were re-elected to new three-year terms.
   William M. Boyd Jr., chairman of the board, president and
publisher of the Home News Publishing Co., New Brunswick, N.J.;
William R. Burleigh, senior vice president for newspapers and
publishing, Scripps Howard; and John G. Montgomery, president and
publisher of Montgomery Publications, Inc., Junction City, Kan.,
also were elected.
   Burleigh and Montgomery were chosen to succeed retiring
directors Howard H (Tim) Hays Jr. of The Press-Enterprise of
Riverside, Calif., and John M. Jones of The Greeneville (Tenn.)
Sun. Hays and Jones were not eligible for re-election because they
served the maximum three consecutive three-year terms on the board.
   Montgomery was elected to represent a city of under 50,000
population.
   Boyd was elected to fill the unexpired term of Katherine W.
Fanning, who resigned from The Chistian Science Monitor last year.
Her term on the board expires in 1991.
   The board of directors also appointed as a representative of the
broadcasting industry Francis A. Martin, president and chief
executive officer, Chronicle Broadcasting Co., San Francisco. Last
week the board reappointed Robert C. McKee Jr. of radio station
WPRW, Manassas, Va. Both will serve two-year terms.
</TEXT>
