<FIRST>r f PM-NCNB-C&amp;S     04-26 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NCNB-C&amp;S,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Chairman Explains Why Bank Dropped C&amp;S Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. may have lost its bid to take over
Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. of Atlanta, but Chairman Hugh McColl says
the North Carolina-based bank plans to continue its growth ``from
Baltimore to Miami.''
   ``It's a fact we're becoming a national company,'' McColl said
Tuesday. ``It's a fact that we're growing instead of dying.'' He
added that NCNB has no plans to expand outside the Southeast and
Texas.
   McColl predicted that large-scale mergers soon will become a
necessity in the banking industry.
   ``We plan to become a major banking company in the U.S.,''
McColl said. ``There will be far fewer players who are much larger.
We will survive.''
   McColl said NCNB has no intention of resubmitting an offer for
C&amp;S, calling his withdrawal of the $2.4 billion bid Monday ``the
end of the saga.''
   ``We have put this chapter behind us,'' he told reporters at a
news conference at NCNB's Charlotte headquarters.
   The C&amp;S takeover would have been the largest bank merger in U.S.
history, combining the assets of the biggest banks in North
Carolina and Georgia. With $76 billion in assets, the new bank
would have been the nation's sixth-largest. On March 30, NCNB,
which has more than $50 billion in assets, shocked the banking
industry by launching the stock bid for the Atlanta bank. When it
appeared the takeover attempt was about to turn nasty, McColl
dropped a bombshell on Monday by abruptly withdrawing the bid.
   ``We always wanted it to be a friendly deal,'' he said. ``We
never said we'd do a hostile deal. When we couldn't pull it off, we
decided to withdraw.''
   The withdrawal marked the second time that NCNB failed to gain a
foothold in the lucrative Atlanta banking market. The bank lost out
to rival Wachovia Corp. of Winston-Salem for First Atlanta Corp. in
1985.
   Meanwhile, NCNB took out full-page ads Tuesday in newspapers in
Charlotte and Atlanta and several other large North Carolina cities
in an apparent effort to explain its side of the takeover battle.
   ``If all you know about NCNB is what you've been reading in the
business section, you're missing a big, big part of what we're all
about,'' the advertisement said.
   ``For example, we at NCNB see a day when Southerners won't have
to go outside the region to secure the capital they need,'' the ad
said. ``We've already made loans that a few years ago no Southern
bank could make.
   ``The way we look at it, being big isn't a goal,'' it said.
``It's a result of doing the absolute best we can for employees,
customers, communities and shareholders.''
   McColl deferred questions about the purpose of the ads.
   Just four months ago, NCNB effectively doubled its size when it
was selected by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. to acquire the
largest bank in Texas, First RepublicBank Corp.
   Since 1982, NCNB has expanded aggressively into new markets in
Florida, South Carolina, Georgia and Tennessee. The First
RepublicBank move was the biggest until the C&amp;S offer.
</TEXT>
