<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Broker     04-26 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Broker,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Drexel Broker Pleads Innocent; Milken Trial Date Set</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. bond trader
has pleaded innocent to federal racketeering and fraud charges in
two major Wall Street securities cases.
   Also Tuesday, a federal judge tentatively set the trial of
former Drexel junk bond financier Michael Milken for June 30, but
also scheduled a more likely March 1990 date.
   The former bond trader, Bruce Lee Newberg, 32, denied all
charges made against him in a March 29 indictment that also
targeted Milken and charges in an August 1988 indictment of the
defunct securities firm Princeton-Newport Partners LP.
   The two cases are considered the most prominent pending trials
in the three-year government investigation of stock crimes
developed from information provided by by jailed inside trader Ivan
Boesky.
   Newberg already has agreed to set aside $1.6 million in assets _
equal to his 1987 salary _ to guarantee forfeitures he might have
to make if convicted in the Milken case under the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations act.
   Last year, Newberg posted $2.5 million with the government in
connection with the RICO forefeiture provisions in the
Princeton-Newport case, which also charged five partners of the New
Jersey securities firm.
   No bail was set in connection with the Milken indictment because
Newberg already remains free on $250,000 bond in the
Princeton-Newport case. His attorneys actually entered an innocent
plea for him in that case in August, but he made a personal plea on
Tuesday.
   Both pleas on Tuesday were entered before U.S. District Judge
Kimba Wood.
   Lawyers have called the dual RICO indictment of Newberg a
rarity. Defense attorneys have indicated they plan to seek
dismissal of all counts against Newberg based on the constitutional
prohibition of double jeopardy, which bars citizens from being
tried twice on the same charges.
   The charges in the 98-count Milken indictment and the 35-count
Princeton-Newport case parallel each other. They focus on a series
of alleged stock manipulations and so-called stock ``parking''
schemes involving Princeton-Newport, Drexel, Milken and Boesky.
   Defense attorneys claim Newberg was charged in both indictments
in an attempt to pressure him into cooperating with prosecutors.
   The Princeton-Newport trial is to begin June 5. At a hearing
Tuesday, Wood set the June 30 trial date for Newberg, Milken and
Milken's brother Lowell because of federal criminal law procedures,
but the additional March 1, 1990, date was considered more
realistic because of the complexity of the case.
   Milken and his brother have pleaded innocent to the charges, as
have the five other Princeton-Newport defendants.
   Newberg did not attend the original April 7 arraignment in the
Milken case because he was injured in a skiing accident.
   Newberg, who reported directly to Milken at Drexel's high-yield
bond division in Beverly Hills, Calif., was present for the
arraignment at Manhattan federal court. He made no remarks other
than to plead not guilty to the judge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
