<FIRST>r f PM-GAFRetrial     04-26 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GAF Retrial,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third GAF Trial Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has picked Nov. 6 for the start
of the third GAF Corp. stock manipulation trial.
   U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe, who twice declared
mistrials in the Wall Street corruption case, scheduled the
November date Tuesday after meeting with lawyers for both sides.
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys had agreed on a September
trial date but Lowe had to push the GAF trial back two months
because she is already scheduled to preside over the stock
manipulation trial of independent financial adviser Salim B. Lewis
in September.
   GAF Corp., a Wayne, N.J.-based chemicials and building materials
manufacturer, and its vice chairman, James T. Sherwin, are accused
of securities fraud and other criminal charges for an alleged
scheme to manipulate the price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in
October 1986.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and Sherwin, 55, of Princeton, N.J., were
indicted last July for allegedly trying to boost Carbide's stock
shortly before unloading millions of Carbide shares acquired in an
unsuccessful takeover attempt.
   They also were charged with securities fraud, wire fraud and
conspiracy.
   If convicted of all charges, GAF and the subsidiaries face
maximum fines totaling $12 million, or $500,000 on each of eight
counts. Sherwin faces up to 40 years in prison and fines totaling
$2 million, if convicted on all counts.
   Lowe declared a mistrial Jan. 10 _ four weeks into the first
trial _ because a prosecutor failed to disclose a report that
concluded a major piece of evidence had been altered.
   A second trial with a new jury began Feb. 1. But on March 23,
the second jury said it was deadlocked after 12 days of
deliberations, prompting Lowe to declare a second mistrial.
   The GAF trial is the first courtroom test of information
stemming from the insider trading scandals that rocked Wall Street
in 1986-87.
   The main prosecution witnesss was Boyd L. Jefferies, former head
of a Los Angeles-based brokerage who struck a plea bargain with
prosecutors after being implicated by master insider trader Ivan F.
Boesky.
</TEXT>
