<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NewInsecticide     04-26 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Insecticide,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Johnson Wax Launches New Insecticide Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   S.C. Johnson &amp; Co. Inc. plans to spend $100
million advertising its new major weapon in the battle for
dominance in the bug-killing market.
   The Racine-based company, popularly known as Johnson Wax,
unveiled Raid Max, its first major new line of insecticides since
it introduced Raid in 1956.
   The company promised the new product would zap cockroaches not
only on the prowl but in their nests and do the same to ants, fleas
and other pests.
   Johnson is No. 1 in the $500 million U.S. household-insecticide
business, with a roughly 47 percent share of the market. But in
recent years, it has seen its share threatened by competitors,
among them American Cyanamid Co.'s Shulton subsidiary.
   Shulton hopped into the roach market with Combat, a poison
contained in small adhesive-backed containers that prevents roaches
from digesting food. Since 1985, Combat has taken 12 percent of the
market, according to trade publications.
   Johnson Wax, however, thinks it has an answer.
   ``We've gone to the top chemical companies in the world and got
state-of-the-art technology. That's the reason were saying that
these are superior,'' Beth Pritchard, vice president of the
insect-control division of Johnson Wax, said Tuesday.
   ``This is a new generation of insecticides. The formulations are
unique. These formulas have been specifically put together for
heavy infestations.''
   The Raid Max line is positioned as a premium product, with
prices from $2.99 to $4.99 _ about $1 to $1.50 more than Raid
products. The new line has four products: a roach-and-ant spray
killer, a fogger, a roach bait and an ant bait.
   Pritchard said consumer tests in three southern states showed
that the products worked better than anything else available.
   Some analysts, however, were skeptical.
   ``They haven't brought out anything to date as good as Combat,''
said Harvey Sober, a Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. anaylst. He noted
Combat had $20 million in sales the first year on the market.
   It took Johnson Wax six years to develop Raid Max, and the
company is banking on it to stabilize its insecticide sales.
Raymond Farley, president and chief executive officer, acknowledged
earlier this year that sales were off about 8 percent in 1988
because of drought in several parts of the country.
   Johnson Wax, with annual sales of about $2 billion, is a
worldwide manufacturer of personal and homecare products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
