<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rising, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held firm in subdued European
trading this morning as the market remained bullish on the U.S.
unit despite potentially bearish factors.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they were surprised by the
dollar's strength despite bearish factors including last week's
hike in the West German Bundesbank's discount rate and Tuesday's
news that the West German government plans to repeal a 10 percent
witholding tax on interest income.
   Dealers added that the market was quiet ahead of today's
announcement of first-quarter U.S. gross national product figures.
If the figures indicate a slowing of the American economy, as
expected, the dollar will probably fall, they said.
   ``The dollar is still well-bid, although I don't really see
why,'' said a dealer at a European bank in Frankfurt. ``Based on
the fundamentals, the dollar should go weaker.''
   In London one British pound cost $1.6965 today, cheaper for
buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7030.
   Other mid-morning rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8702 West German marks, up from
1.8625; 1.6518 Swiss francs, up from 1.6435; 6.3303 French francs,
up from 6.3065; 2.1085 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1000; 1.1885
Canadian dollars, down 1.1910.
   The U.S. unit also stood at 1,370.50 lire, up from its late rate
of 1,366.00 Italian lire Tuesday in London. Italian markets were
closed for a holiday Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar closed at 131.47 yen, up from Tuesday's late 131.17.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383.75 a troy ounce,
down from $385.75 late Tuesday. At mid-morning, the city's main
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $384.40.
   Zurich gold was trading at a bid price of $384.30, down from
$385.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold dropped the equivalent of 98 cents to
close at $385.59.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $5.785 bid a troy ounce, down
from Tuesday's $5.81.
</TEXT>
