<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-26 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index, overcoming a
setback in early trading, shot up to a record high today, while the
dollar edged up against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar ended at 131.47 yen, up 0.30 yen from Tuesday's
131.17-yen close. It opened at 131.38 yen and fluctuated between
131.30 yen and 131.53 yen. The dollar had slipped 1.11 yen over the
three previous trading days.
   The dollar gradually rose against the yen in connection with
dollar-buying against the West German mark, said a trader with the
Bank of Tokyo. Many market participants remained on the sidelines
to await the release later today of the U.S. gross national product
figure for 1989's first three months, he added.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which gained 438.86 points Tuesday, added another 190.15
points, or 0.57 percent, closing today at 33,434.93, a new high.
   Profit-taking following Tuesday's gain sent the index down 51.39
points in morning trading but it rebounded as institutional
investors began buying up shares that had declined in the morning,
analysts said.
   ``Of course (Prime Minister Norobu) Takeshita's remarks (on his
resignation) yesterday wouldn't remedy the whole thing, but
investors expect that it at least will clear up some of the
uncertainties,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama with Nikko Securities in
Tokyo.
   Amid growing public distrust in his government, tainted by a
stock-profiteering and bribery scandal that surfaced last summer,
Takeshita announced Tuesday he would step down as soon as
Parliament passes the fiscal 1989 budget.
   Investors reacted positively to this indication that the budget
would be put through, Shimoyama said.
   ``Some may think it strange that share prices started rising
following the prime minister's announcement he would resign soon,
but it lightened up market psychology,'' he said.
</TEXT>
