<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 0928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     04-26 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incentives Give Car Sales A Lift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The big incentive packages introduced recently
helped boost car and light truck sales by 5.4 percent in mid-April,
but one analyst said automakers might have to cut production
further to pare excess inventories.
   The eight companies making cars and light trucks in North
America said Tuesday that they sold vehicles at an average of
41,380 a day during the April 11-20 period this year, compared with
a 39,257 vehicle-a-day rate in mid-April last year.
   Car sales were up 3.7 percent and truck sales rose 8.6 percent.
   ``I'm breathing easier today,'' said analyst Doug Laughlin of
Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. of New York City. ``The selling rate is up and
up against a good number a year ago, and it's part of what we need
to get the inventories back in line.''
   On Tuesday, Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. said they
had trimmed their second-quarter and early third-quarter production
schedules.
   The strategy is to combine sales inflated by incentives and
production cuts to reduce inventories before the companies change
manufacturing to the 1990 models later this year.
   ``It looks like they've made both of the necessary
adjustments,'' Laughlin said. ``It should put them in better
inventory shape when the model year rolls around.''
   But analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New
York wasn't so sure.
   ``I don't think the (production) cuts that have been made or 20
days of improved sales are going to be enough to solve the
inventory problem,'' he said, adding that the cuts may have to go
deeper and the incentives may have to be sweetened.
   ``I think the incentives are working,'' said analyst Charles
Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York. ``I would have been
surprised if it would have been anything else.''
   The mid-April sales increase wasn't evenly spread across the
major makers. Ford's car sales soared 14.5 percent, compared with a
1.5 percent decline for GM and a 10.3 percent drop for Chrysler
Corp.
   ``What you have here is the strength of Ford's product
momentum,'' Laughlin said. ``When you've got roughly comparable
incentives, this is what happens.
   ``Chrysler, that's a lot tougher one to look at. You've got a
lot of models which aren't in production right now'' and are
sitting on dealer lots, he added.
   Automakers were looking for rising sales rates this month when
they put on the newest incentive packages in late March and early
April. March and April traditionally are strong vehicle buying
periods, but last month proved to be weaker than expected.
   That prompted the Big Three to put on the new incentive
packages, a bit of a gamble since the costs of low-interest
financing and cash rebates come out of manufacturers' profits.
   For 1989, car and truck sales by the eight makers are running
3.9 percent behind the pace of last year, the second-best in
industry history. Car sales are off 6 percent. Light truck sales
are nearly even.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
