<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Northwest     04-26 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Gains Ground On Two Fronts To Ward Off Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines gained some ground on
two fronts in its battle with hostile suitor Marvin Davis as a
Delaware judge turned down Davis' effort to void some of
Northwest's defenses and the Minnesota commerce commissioner
ordered the oilman to provide more information on his plans.
   Chancellor William P. Allen of Delaware Chancery Court in
Wilmington rejected Tuesday Davis' request for an injunction that
would have barred NWA Inc., Northwest's parent, from issuing
``poison pill'' stock rights to shareholders before NWA's annual
meeting May 15.
   But the judge left the door open to another legal challenge of
the poison pill, which makes it more difficult and costly for a
group to take over a company. Allen indicated he would make a final
determination on the legality of the pill within 45 days of the
company's annual meeting.
   Allen ordered NWA to inform its shareholders that the pill might
be invalidated later.
   Davis is offering to buy Northwest for $2.7 billion, or $90 a
share. The NWA board has rejected the offer as inadequate.
   A spokeman for Davis said the oilman's investor group would have
preferred an injunction, but nonetheless was pleased by the judge's
order that shareholders be notified that the pill could be ruled
illegal.
   The decision means Davis could still succeed in acquiring the
nation's fourth-largest airline if he can win control of NWA's
board of directors.
   Tom Ryan, a Northwest spokesman, said he had not fully reviewed
the ruling and could not comment on it in detail, but ``It's fair
to say we're pleased with it.''
   Davis got another blow Tuesday night from Commerce Commissioner
Michael Hatch, who gave Davis' lawyers a Wednesday noon CDT
deadline to give further details on the takeover bid.
   ``The financial statements given to the bank, the lenders, I
think ought to be made available to the shareholders so at least
the offering becomes believable in terms of the ability of the
acquirer to operate an ongoing airline,'' Hatch said.
   Under a 1984 state law, the registration of the Davis offer must
be reviewed by the commerce commissioner. If Hatch decides that
Davis has not made a sufficient explanation of his plans, the
commissioner can order the offer be suspended.
   Davis attorney George A. Vandeman said after the hearing he
would try to convince Hatch that the disclosures of Davis'
financial plan for the Eagan-based airline are adequate and
accurate.
   Hatch said he would issue a ruling by 6 p.m. Wednesday if one is
needed. If he issues a suspension order, Davis would have a chance
to appeal it at a Thursday night hearing at the state Department of
Commerce, Hatch said.
   Vandeman said a suspension would not delay Davis' effort to
acquire Northwest.
   The NWA board of directors on Monday unanimously rejected Davis'
bid, charging that the offer is unfinanced and in part illegal
under securities laws. But the board said it is willing to
negotiate with Davis and other qualified bidders.
   In other developments, the NWA board decided, at least
temporarily, against a planned $1.6 billion order for new planes.
Instead, it authorized its plane-leasing subsidiary to buy 10 used
DC-10s and 14 used DC-9s to lease to Northwest and other carriers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
