<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today in an
innconclusive response to the latest data on the state of the
economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 5.50 to
2,3881.41 in the first half hour of trading.
   But gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 454 up, 309
down and 529 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.39 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
gross national product rose at a 5.5 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the first quarter of the year.
   Without the effects of last year's drought, however, the agency
said the growth rate would have been just 3 percent.
   So analysts concluded that the figures provided support for the
belief that economic growth lately has been losing momentum as the
Federal Reserve has sought to restrain inflation.
   But the inflation figures that accompanied the GNP report were
not so encouraging, brokers said, indicating that prices were still
rising at a 5 percent to 5.5 percent annual rate.
   USX rose [ to 33~. On Tuesday the company reported sharply
higher earnings for the first quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .30 to 171.30. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .05 at 343.02.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 15.77 points to
2,386.91.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 8 to 7 on the
NYSE, with 820 down, 681 up and 461 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 165.43 million shares, against 142.10
million in the previous session.
