<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-26 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Gain in Mixed Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade as forecasts for more rain forced down
wheat prices and increased demand for soybean meal in Europe pushed
up soybean prices.
   The higher soybean prices reversed a downward trend of the past
two days. The early rally was given a push by the resumption of a
strike by Brazilian dock workers.
   The Kansas wheat crop, damaged by drought, is expected to be
helped by forecasts for rain.
   Corn prices were firm, rising a half cent to a penny in early
trading, as farmers reduced their sales of corn stocks.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.11 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
} cent higher with May at $2.64{ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1{
cents higher with May at $1.90 a bushel and soybeans were 2 cents
to 5 cents higher with May at $7.37{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .80 cent higher, with June at 71.32
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .70 cent higher, with
May at 76.50 cents a pound; hogs were .23 cent to .40 cent higher
with June at 47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .60 cent to
.77 cent higher with May at 32.35 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mixed Tuesday, while pork futures were
higher.
</TEXT>
