<SECOND>PM-Fusion Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru,1005</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher Say They are Seeking to End Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 24 grafs new, picking up at pvs 11th graf, Many experts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers told Congress today that they are
taking measures to resolve the controversy and skepticism
surrounding their cold-fusion experiment by having government
investigators observe in their laboratory.
   Stanley Pons, a University of Utah chemist who announced the
cold-fusion process to produce energy last month, said his
laboratory has arranged experiments duplicating the process and
have invited scientists from the Los Alamos National Laboratories
to observe.
   ``We have 19 experiments being set up now, including a
demonstratiion for Los Alamos,'' Pons told the House Committee on
Science, Space and Technology.
   Pons said that once the experiment is operating satisfactorily,
the Los Alamos scientists will take it back with them to the
federal laboratory for a detailed analysis.
   Pons and his collaborator, Martin Fleischmann of the University
of Southampton in England, announced at a news conference March 23
that they had achieved fusion at room temperature by using simple
laboratory equipment.
   The Utah researchers said they placed electrodes of platinum and
palladium in a flask of deuterium oxide, or heavy water, and then
applied an electrical current to the electrodes. They said the
setup split the heavy water into atoms of deuterium and oxygen and
forced deuterium nuclei into the crystal lattice structure of the
palladium metal.
   After operating for a number of hours, the researchers said, the
experiment caused deuterium to become so compressed within the
metal that the nuclei fused. This reaction, they said, produced
heat energy equal to about four times the amount of energy used to
cause the fusion.
   The announcement stunned the international physics community,
which has spent millions of dollars over the last 25 years
attempting to achieve fusion using massive, multimillion-dollar
machines filled with plasmas heated to temperatures of up to 100
million degrees.
   Pons and Fleischman appeared before the House committee today in
a room packed with spectators, journalists and representatives of
other laboratories.
   The two defended their work before sharp questioning by
committee members who probed not only the findings of the
experiment but the manner in which the researchers announced their
work.
   Fleischmann said follow-up articles detailing how the experiment
is being conducted will be published in scientific journals.
   Pons said part of the controversy revolves around the different
way in which chemists and physicists announce the results of their
work. The Utah experiments have come under heavy criticism from
fusion experts because the precise details needed for duplication
of the work have not been released.
   Pons said that typically physicists will circulate a
pre-publication copy of their research to colleagues, who will
informally review it.
   ``For chemists, it is done in a different way,'' he said. ``The
review is left up to the journal.''
   Fleischmann said that in one experiment researchers have been
able to cause water to reach the boiling point. He added, however,
there was still much work yet to be done to develop a way of
harvesting useful energy from this process.
   The Utah researchers said they built their initial experiment
for about $100,000, but Fleischmann said ``production of a scale-up
device will cost about 10 times that'' and that the next phase,
where useful energy was actually developed, ``would cost millions.''
   The researchers also said it could take years to turn the
cold-fusion process into a useful energy source. ``We think it is
feasible but it will require a very high effort,'' Fleischmann said.
   One of the elements to be investigated, said Fleischmann, is the
metal that can be used in cold fusion. The palladium used by the
Utak researchers is an expensive metal that is available in only a
few places on Earth.
   Fleischmann said other experiments are under way to find if
other metals can be used. ``Palladium may be the best choice but
there may be also other possible choices,'' he said.
   The University of Utah was planning to use today's hearing to
request $25 million from the federal government toward a $100
million institute devoted to commercializing the process, The New
York Times reported today.
   While such lobbying for funds is not new, it is highly unusual
for researchers to seek congressional support before their findings
have been confirmed, the newspaper said.
   The day-long hearing was to include at least three nuclear
physicists who have reported that they have been unable to
duplicate the Utah experiments.
   In testimony released to the committee, scientists from the Oak
Ridge National Laboratory, Princeton University and Massachusetts
Institute of Technology all expressed strong and sharp skepticism
and doubt about the Utah experiments actually achieving nuclear
fusion.
   Researchers in Texas, California and Washington have reported
what may be fusion reactions, but many other laboratories have
reported failed efforts. Scientists in the Soviet Union and Hungary
reported experiments with reactions that may be fusion.
   Many experts believe fusion to be the ultimate energy source.
The nuclear process is the opposite of the fission reaction that
now powers atomic generating plants. Fission occurs by splitting
atoms and the process leaves behind highly radioactive spent fuel.
   Fusion derives its energy by forcing atoms of deuterium or
hydrogen together. The reaction produces an atom of helium, a burst
of energy and a neutron. Experts believe fusion energy would
produce a much smaller amount of radioactive waste, and that fusion
power plants could be operated with deuterium oxide, or heavy
water, a chemical that can easily be extracted from seawater.
   Natural fusion energy is the power that causes the sun and the
stars to shine. Stellar fusion is created when the massive force of
gravity in stars forces hydrogen atoms to fuse, giving off heat,
light and helium. Most ``hot'' fusion research is an attempt to
duplicate the pressure and heat process seen on the sun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
