<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston, 1st Ld - Writethru,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrests Piling Up in UMW Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with about 100 more union members
arrested, crowds interfering with police bus. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, `State
Police ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested about 100 striking union
members today for trying to block a coal mine, and hundreds of
supporters interfered with buses taking the miners away, officials
said.
   Members of the United Mine Workers were arrested at the entrance
to the Pittston Coal Group's Lambert Fork Mine, said State Police
Lt. J.D. Willis.
   ``We took them away in buses and tried to disembark them for
processing at several places in Dickenson County but were turned
away because of crowd control problems,'' Willis said. He would not
disclose where the bus ended up.
   Strike supporters at a Clintwood elementary school continued a
rally after turning away buses, Willis said.
   ``Everbody's dressed in camouflage, there're hundreds of people
standing there clapping and cheering at the miners in the buses,''
said a woman in the county clerk's office who would not give her
name. ``You'd never know this many people lived in Dickenson
County.''
   The escalation in the union's 3-week-old strike against Pittston
has resulted in hundreds of arrests and a walkout by about 150 high
school students since Monday.
   State Police said at least 200 miners and relatives were
arrested Tuesday for sitting in the entrance and blocking traffic
to and from a coal preparation plant. Union officials estimated the
number at 380.
   State Police made several trips with at least four buses and
several vans before they could remove the protesters and reopen the
truck entrance to the plant. Some pickets were dragged across the
road to the waiting buses.
   About 200 miners were arrested Monday during a sitdown at
Pittston's McClure mine, touching off a daylong rally at the
Dickenson County Courthouse by the miners' friends and relatives
that closed downtown Clintwood.
   On Tuesday, about 150 students walked out of class at high
schools in Dickenson and Wise counties to join the rally. Many of
the youngsters wore camouflage, the strike uniform worn by the
miners, and waved signs at passing cars and trucks.
   Despite the threat of suspension, Kim Childers, a senior at
Clintwood High School, said she expects the protest to continue.
   About 1,700 UMW members have been on strike at Pittston mines in
Virginia and West Virginia since April 5.
   The miners had been working without a contract for 14 months,
and the union accused Pittston of engaging in unfair labor
practices during negotiations, a claim Pittston denies.
</TEXT>
