<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today in a
inconclusive response to the latest data on the state of the
economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.65 to 2,388.56 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers and losers ran about even in nationwide trading of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 670 up, 668 down and 554
unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
gross national product rose at a 5.5 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the first quarter of the year.
   Without the effects of last year's drought, however, the agency
said the growth rate would have been just 3 percent.
   So analysts concluded that the figures provided support for the
belief that economic growth lately has been losing momentum as the
Federal Reserve has sought to restrain inflation.
   But the inflation figures that accompanied the GNP report were
not so encouraging, brokers said, indicating that prices were still
rising at a 5 percent to 5.5 percent annual rate.
   USX rose ] to 34[ in active trading. On Tuesday the company
reported sharply higher earnings for the first quarter.
   By contrast, Compaq Computer fell 2 to 77\ even though the
company posted a substantial increase in its first-quarter profits.
   Other technology issues also were generally weak. International
Business Machines dropped ] to 114[; Digital Equipment ] to 95{,
and Apple Computer } to 39\ in the over-the-counter market.
   McGraw-Hill fell 2[ to 75{. The company said it has no plans to
merge with any other party.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.06 to 171.66. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .10 at 343.17.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.51 million shares with two
hours to go.
