<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   04-26 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Rise As Fears Of Rate Hike Ease</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: updates with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices closed sharply higher on the London Stock
Exchange Wednesday as favorable British trade figures helped to
calm the market's fears of an imminent rise in interest rates.
   The trade report propelled the key Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100-stock index briefly above the 2,100-point level, the
top of the recent trading range and an important level both
psychologically and for those charting the market's progress.
   But the index later drifted back as buying interest wasn't
sustained.
   At the close, the index was up 22.2 points, or 1.1 percent, at
2,093.4.
   Volume was relatively high, with 567.7 million shares changing
hands, compared with 577.7 million shares on Tuesday.
   The government reported that Britain had a current account
deficit in March of 1.19 billion pounds, or $2 billion. This was
considerably lower than February's deficit of 1.7 billion pounds,
and well below market expectations of a 1.5 billion-pound gap.
   Analysts cautioned, however, the report might merely have bought
some time, noting that inflationary pressures in the economy could
still force official interest rates higher at a later point.
</TEXT>
