<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     04-26 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rising In Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended higher against all major
currencies except the Canadian dollar in European trading
Wednesday. Gold prices declined.
   Foreign exchange dealers said sentiment toward the dollar
remains bullish, although trading was not affected by the latest
U.S. economic figures released Wednesday.
   The U.S. government said the gross national product figures
expanding at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.5 percent,
larger than expected.
   ``I have no explanation for the dollar's rise but people want to
buy dollars,'' said Swiss bank dealer Peter Kane at Credit Suisse.
   The British pound rose initially on the narrowing of the trade
deficit in March to $2 billion from $2.8 billion in February, since
a larger deficit had been expected. But the pound eased with the
consequent lessening of pressure for an upward revision of British
interest rates as a counter-inflationary measure.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6932 late Wednesday,
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7030.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Tuesday's late rates: 1.8770 West German marks, up from 1.8625;
1.6555 Swiss francs, up from 1.6435; 6.3395 French francs, up from
6.3065; 2.1150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1000; 1,374.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,366.00; and 1.1900 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1910.
   Earlier, in Tokyo, the dollar rose to 131.47 Japanese yen from
131.17 Tuesday. In London late Wednesday the dollar traded higher
at 132.00 yen.
   Gold bullion prices fell. The late gold bid price in London was
$384.25 a troy ounce, down from $385.75 late Tuesday. The Zurich
late bid price was $383.50 an ounce, down from $385.00.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.55 an ounce, down
from $385.65.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.77 a troy
ounce, down from $5.81.
 
</TEXT>
