<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BlimpieLites     04-26 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blimpie Lites,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blimpie Goes After Health-Conscious Consumers With New Low-Cal Menu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blimpie is going skimpy on calories.
   The fast-food restaurant known for submarines heaped with meats
and mayo said Wednesday it is expanding the menu to include
low-calorie sandwiches and salads in an attempt to woo
calorie-conscious consumers who might otherwise be avoiding fast
food.
   Industry analysts and nutritionists say the additions _ which
include seafood, turkey, chicken and low-calorie mayonnaise _ is a
response to increased public interest in healthier food, even
though such traditional fast-foods as hamburgers and french fries
remain king.
   But experts also said past attempts at healthier fast food have
produced mixed results, even though most chains now offer salads or
other ``light items.''
   ``We feel there's a mounting hunger for variety among the
public,'' said Tony Conza, chairman of New York-based Astor
Restaurant Group Inc., Blimpie's parent.
   ``The Blimpie Lites appeal to those customers we feel have
abandoned fast food because of the calories,'' Conza said.
   Conza and other Astor executives were in Atlanta to unveil the
new menu to Georgia franchise operators. The Blimpie Lite menu will
be test marketed in Georgia beginning in June and will be
introduced in the chain's 14 other states later in the year.
   Blimpie's regular menu, including 12 sandwiches as well as
salads, will remain in effect at the chain's 350 outlets.
   The new items, developed with the Boston-based Diet Workshop
chain of weight-control facilities, each have less than 300
calories. They include tuna, seafood and crab, chicken, turkey and
tova fish stuffed into whole wheat pita bread or spread on a salad.
The sandwiches will have low-calorie mayonnaise and the salads will
have vinegar dressing.
   ``It fits in with the whole movement in the food industry, not
just fast food, to offer good-tasting, low-calorie, low-fat
items,'' said Jay Freedman, who follows the industry for the
investment firm Kidder Peabody.
   Freedman said introduction of such items in fast food outlets
has produced mixed results, with a major flop being D'Lites, a
Norcross, Ga.-based nutritious fast food chain that filed for
bankruptcy in 1986.
   ``People think about eating healthy, but they do little about
it,'' he said. ``Clearly, there hasn't been an across-the-board
ramp-up of people buying only low-calorie, healthy foods.
   ``My guess is the demographics of the average Blimpie customer
won't fit into someone who is calorie- or fat-conscious.''
   Chris Rosenbloom, associate professor in the Department of
Nutrition and Dietetics at Georgia State University, said consumer
demand has forced the fast food industry to offer alternatives to
its basic menu items.
   Mrs. Rosenbloom also credited consumer groups, such as the
Center for Science in the Public Interest, for alerting people to
the content of fast food and noted many chains such as McDonald's
now have registered dietitians at the corporate level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
