<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-26 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0230</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices recovered modestly from
two days of steep declines on the Chicago Board of Trade on
Wednesday as traders who sold the market earlier in the week bought
in again.
   Corn futures prices increased and wheat futures dropped slightly.
   Soybean prices rose amid talk that a strike by Brazilian dock
workers could go on for some time.
   ``The strike may provide the United States with some export
business, although it hasn't so far,'' said Joel Karlin an analyst
for Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   ``The market has assimilated most of the bearish news about
weather,'' he said, referring to forecasts for increased rain in
key crop-producing states.
   The Agriculture Department is trying to decide whether to
subsidize additional grain sales to the Soviet Union as talks
continue in Washington with Soviet representatives.
   The department is expected to announce its decision after talks
end Thursday.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.10{ per bushel; corn was { cent
to 1} cents higher, with May at $2.65} per bushel; oats were 4\
cents to 5} cents lower with May at $1.83\ per bushel; soybeans
were 2\ cents to 7 cents higher with May at $7.39{ per bushel.
