<DOCNO> AP890426-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Asia-AirlineCompetition Adv30   04-26 1002</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asia-Airline Competition, Adv 30,1028</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Asian Airlines Compete For Booming Pacific Travel Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK1 of April 24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A travel boom in the Asia-Pacific region has
touched off a scramble among U.S. and Asian airlines for business
in a market growing at twice the pace elsewhere.
   There's a competitive atmosphere in which government policy and
underlying trade friction can have as much to do with an airline's
bottom line as the allure of Singapore Airlines' romantic
advertising or the upgraded, Japanese-speaking service touted by
United Airlines.
   Some Asian airlines complain at what they call unfair advantages
enjoyed by United and Northwest but they want equal privileges in
the U.S. market rather than to retaliate against the far-flung
networks of the big U.S. carriers.
   ``We don't fear the size of these big U.S. carriers but we're
worried about the frequency of their stops in the Southeast Asia
and Pacific region,'' said Nares Hovatanakul of Thai Airways
International in Bangkok. ``We would like to see reciprocity, not
retaliation, because that would not be fair business.''
   The Thai spokesman said U.S. government negotiators refused to
permit more than five weekly flights by the Thai carrier to Seattle
via Tokyo's Narita international airport. ``They won't lift this
restriction and we feel that fair competition is halted,'' he said.
   Everyone wants more landing rights, especially in the United
States and Japan. The Japan-U.S. routes are the most lucrative,
heavily used by business travelers as well as by the fast-growing
number of Japanese tourists.
   U.S. airlines, meanwhile, complain in varying degrees about poor
Japanese facilities and hindrances by the Japanese government.
   ``Narita is the most congested airport in the world,'' said
Clyde McAvoy, Continental Airlines' vice president for the Far
East. He said Narita, only 10 years old, and a new airport under
construction at Osaka were structured ``as very sophisticated
non-tariff barriers.''
   ``By pleading a lack of facilities, Japan in effect is in a
position to curtail competition,'' he said.
   Continental's tactic is to use the island of Guam as a hub
rather than Narita. To avoid Narita's crowded check-in area, the
airline will pick up first- and business-class passengers at their
Tokyo hotels and drive them to Narita in luxury vans, checking them
in during the ride.
   Such competitive wrinkles _ United offers a concierge to
shepherd business- and first-class passengers _ reflect the
scramble for well-heeled Japanese travelers. ``They are a wonderful
consumer to do business with once you earn their loyalty,'' said
McAvoy.
   Statistics from 1987, the most recent year obtainable, show 12.5
million people arriving and departing Japan on routes to the U.S.
mainland, Hawaii, Micronesia and Southeast Asia including Hong
Kong. The number of Japanese travelers to the United States totaled
1.7 million in 1986 and 2.4 million in the first 11 months of 1988.
   An economic boom that extends to Southeast Asia is behind the
increase in travel, and it's fueled by decisions in South Korea and
Taiwan to permit their citizens to travel abroad more freely.
   ``We see overall Pacific travel growing 10 to 12 percent a
year,'' said Bill Speicher, United's senior vice president for
Pacific operations, ``and we believe it will continue indefinitely
in the future, while air traffic in the rest of the world is
forecast to grow about 5 percent a year.''
   United has aggressively sought permission to fly the
Chicago-Tokyo route nonstop but was recently turned down by the
U.S. Transportation Department. The issue will come up in
U.S.-Japan talks on air rights scheduled for mid-May.
   What will Japan's attitude be? Norifumi Ide, deputy director for
international air transport in Japan's Ministry of Transport, said
the two countries' airlines are now balanced on the route: Japan
Air Lines and Northwest each can fly Chicago-Tokyo nonstop.
   Ide hinted Japan will reject United's request, though there
might be some flexibility if Washington permits Japanese cargo
flights on the Chicago route.
   ``U.S. companies, Flying Tigers and Northwest, have enjoyed a
monopoly for many years in that important cargo market,'' Ide said.
``We always table it (in U.S.-Japan negotiations). It is a symbol
of the imbalanced relationship in favor of the U.S.''
   United's Speicher, speaking in a telephone interview from
Hawaii, implied a willingness to see more competition than the U.S.
government now permits.
   ``We will have to find ways in negotiations to accommodate both
sides.'' Speicher said
   Japan Air Lines, which carried 1.2 million trans-Pacific
passengers in the first half of fiscal 1988, a 10.3 percent
increase over the comparable period a year earlier, urges that
competition not be unleashed as happened in the deregulated U.S.
aviation market.
   ``The industry would be dragged into the chaos of price wars and
oversupply,'' JAL board member Yoshiyasu Mayumi warned in a recent
speech.
   The Transport Ministry has a chart showing U.S. airlines with
all the advantages: 19 U.S. gateway cities to 11 permitted to
Japanese carriers; five points in Japan to three used by Japanese
trans-Pacific flights; nine ``beyond points'' in Asia for U.S.
carriers but only one (Rio de Janeiro) permitted to Japanese
airlines flying to the United States; seven U.S. airlines compared
with three Japanese; 380 U.S. flights in and out of Japan each week
to 210 for Japanese airlines.
   One Transport Ministry official, asking not to be named,
criticized what he called ``predatory American carriers coming in
and ripping off our backyard.''
   The Americans disagree. Northwest's Tokyo spokesman, Doug
Killian, said that Japan Air Lines ``also uses Narita for a hub to
Southeast Asia and other points, so there is a similar route
pattern (to the U.S. airlines). We don't feel like everything is
balanced in favor of the U.S. carriers.''
   Northwest is embarking on what it calls its ``most aggressive
single-year route expansion'' in the 42 years it has operated in
the Pacific, launching six new Pacific routes. It was the first to
bring the new Boeing 747-400 jumbo to Tokyo, where it was blessed
by a Shinto priest.
   End adv for Sunday, April 30
</TEXT>
</DOC>
