<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GoldFields     04-26 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gold Fields,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorco Wins A Majority Stake In Gold Fields, Has Another 21 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA said Wednesday enough shareholders have
accepted its hostile $6 billion bid for Consolidated Gold Fields
PLC to give the South African-controlled bidder a majority stake
and another three weeks to proceed with the offer.
   If it hadn't won the majority stake, Minorco's offer, the
equivalent of 3.5 billion pounds, would have expired at 1 p.m.
Wednesday.
   ``We are naturally pleased at the market's judgement and will
now consider very carefully what action to take,'' said Chairman
Sir Michael Edwardes said.
   Gold Fields Chairman Rudolph Agnew responded, ``We don't believe
that it is in the interests of Gold Fields and its shareholders for
Minorco to gain control. We don't intend to be swayed from our
responsibilities by the bully-boy tactics of Minorco.''
   The takeover of the British gold mining giant would be Britain's
largest corporate acquisition ever. The battle has been a
protracted and expensive one.
   Minorco, the Luxembourg-based investment arm of the South
African Oppenheimer family's gold and diamond mining interests,
said it had counted acceptances from holders of 53.21 million Gold
Fields shares, representing 24.9 percent of all Gold Fields' stock.
   Together with the nearly 30 percent already owned by Minorco,
the acceptances bring its stake to 54.84 percent, or 117.16 million
shares.
   That means that under British takeover regulations, Minorco now
has 21 days to clear up any other outstanding conditions on the bid.
   Principal among these is the lifting of a preliminary injunction
issued by a U.S. court that bars Minorco from purchasing more than
30 percent of Gold Fields shares.
   On Monday, the U.S. court refused to lift the injunction, which
arose from an antitrust suit.
   ``The (U.S. antitrust) litigation will proceed to a full
trial,'' Agnew said Wednesday.
   Minorco has twice sweetened its offer since it first launched it
in September. It currently is offering half a Minorco share and
11.75 pounds in cash for every Gold Fields share.
   Gold Fields has fought the offer vigorously, offering its
shareholders a special dividend if it doesn't meet it own earnings
targets. It has raised concerns about the concentration of control
over the world's gold supplies and potential harmful effects to
Gold Fields from being owned by a South African-controlled company.
   Minorco is 60 percent owned by Anglo American Corp. and De Beers
Consolidated Mines Ltd., the Oppenheimers' gold and diamond mining
giants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-QuietTypewriter     04-26 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quiet Typewriter,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>On Secretary's Day, Xerox Announces Quietest Ribbon Typewriter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. chose National Secretary's Day to
unveil what it calls the world's quietest ribbon typewriter, a
machine nearly as quiet as a computer keyboard.
   The typewriters introduced Wednesday use a patented technology
that gives the printer heads the vibrational characteristics of a
hammer weighing nearly 35 pounds, Xerox said. That makes them
vibrate at a pitch nearly six octaves lower than usual, almost
inaudible to the human ear.
   The quiet typewriters could help Xerox take some business from
International Business Machines Corp., the market leader in
top-of-the-line typewriters for Fortune 1000 companies, said Julie
Voss, a consultant at Venture Development Corp. in Natick, Mass.
   The big question is whether customers will pay the extra $300
Xerox is asking for the feature, said Anthony Polifrone, a vice
president of Buyers Laboratory in Hackensack, N.J.
   ``There's no doubt that the machine is incredibly quiet,'' he
said.
   Xerox is the traditional No. 2 in the big-business market,
although it fell to third in 1988 because of a big federal
government order to an importer of Japanese-made typewriters.
   The Xerox 62 Series typewriters have six patents and five more
pending, which should make it impossible for competitors to copy
the noise-reducing characteristics, said Andrew Gabor, the inventor.
   Gabor is the co-inventor of the daisywheel printer system, which
was brought to market in 1972 when he was at Diablo Systems. His
company was acquired by Xerox a short time later. He is a senior
research fellow at Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center in Silicon
Valley.
   Gabor at a news conference Wednesday demonstrated a 1960s-era
IBM Selectric with a golf ball-type head (noisy), two earlier
models of Xerox Memorywriters with daisywheels (quieter), and the
new 62 Series (soft clacking).
   Thermal printing typewriters, in which marks are burned onto the
page, are even quieter than the new Xerox models, but they have
drawbacks such as the inability to handle carbons and multi-part
forms. Xerox said its research found 65 percent of all secretarial
typing involves multi-part forms.
   The 6225 model is $1,995 and the 6240 model, which includes a
disk drive for memory storage, is $2,595. Xerox said those prices
are about $300 above corresponding models that are noisier.
   Xerox said the 62 Series produces 52 decibels at 20 characters
per second, which it said is 15 decibels less than other designs.
Ms. Voss, using different decibel numbers, said the Xerox models
would displace Canon's AP 800 as the quiet champion.
   The lower vibrational pitch is achieved by rigidly connecting
the print tip to several heavy elements inside the typewriter,
including a connecting rod and print bail. The greater mass
produces a lower tone, much as a thick, long piano wire produces a
lower tone than a thin, short one.
   Gabor said patent examiners were so incredulous about the
achievement that they demanded a demonstration, which Gabor and
others gave in a hotel conference room in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890426-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Pickens     04-26 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Pickens,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koito Questions Pickens' Share Ownership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Koito Manufacturing Co. demanded
Wednesday that U.S. takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens Jr.
disclose whether he is the real owner of the shares he is using to
claim management rights as Koito's largest shareholder.
   Three weeks ago, Pickens bought 20.2 percent of the shares of
Koito, an auto parts manufacturer closely linked with Toyota Motor.
In a highly publicized visit to Tokyo last week, he demanded
management rights as a shareholder in a direct challenge to deeply
entrenched Japanese business convention, which generally abhors
anything that smacks of a hostile takeover.
   In a letter to Pickens, Koito President Takao Matsuura said,
``Substantial questions have been raised concerning the nature of
Boone Co.'s ownership of Koito shares _ questions which you have
pointedly declined to answer in your recent statements to the
press.''
   Matsuura noted that speculation ``concerning whether Boone Co.
is in fact the real owner of these shares subject to the full
economic risk of its investment.''
   In the letter, Matsuura declined to answer Pickens' earlier
written request for three seats on Koito's board of directors until
Pickens disclosed whether he had an option, repurchase or security
agreement with a Japanese shareholder.
   The Japanese press has speculated Pickens may have an agreement
to sell back the block of shares he bought from Kitaro Watanabe's
Azabu Motors Co., to bring profits both to himself and the company.
   Such an agreement would allow Watanabe to use Picken's
internationally known name to up the ante in a greenmail bid
against Toyota Motor, which owns 19.1 percent of Koito, the press
reports suggested.
   An agreement for Azabu Motors to buy back the shares at a fixed
price would protect Pickens from a loss.
   In corporate greenmail, an investor aqcuires a large block of a
company's shares, threatening to take it over. The greenmailer then
profits when a friendly company saves the target company by buying
the shares at a higher price.
   Pickens has denied any greenmail effort in the Koito share
purchase.
   Analysts say the negative reaction of the Tokyo markets to
Pickens' action is reflected in the share price of Koito, which
closed Wednesday at 4,350 yen, or $33.21, down from a 5,470 yen
high the week before Pickens' purchase and below the 4,830 yen
price shortly after the purchase was announced.
   In the United States, share prices usually rise when there is a
greenmail attempt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
