<FIRST>r f AM-GoodmanFielder     04-26 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goodman Fielder,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goodman Fielder Wattie Rejects Ranks Hovis Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Goodman Fielder Wattie
Ltd. said Wednesday it had rejected as inadequate a $2.4 billion
takeover offer from Ranks Hovis McDougall PLC of Britain.
   The directors said in a statement the bid ``doesn't reflect the
underlying value of the company.''
   They also said a takeover by Ranks Hovis would result in the
loss of effective Australasian control over ``vital elements of the
local food industry.'' Goodman Fielder Wattie is the biggest food
processor in Australia and New Zealand.
   The board also called the offer highly conditional, and
criticized the fact it is denominated in British pounds and would
expose shareholders to exchange-rate movements.
   The directors also said Ranks Hovis has not clarified its
intentions about possible asset sales and the future of Goodman
Fielder Wattie's 20,000 employees.
   Ranks Hovis said Wednesday it had raised its stake in Goodman
Fielder Wattie to 14.9 percent through purchases on stock markets
in Australia and London.
   The British company's offer to buy Goodman Fielder Wattie is
worth 3.1 million Australian dollars.
   Ranks Hovis said it would offer stock valued at 3.07 Australian
dollars per share for Goodman Fielder. The offer is four new Ranks
Hovis shares for every 11 Goodman Fielder shares and a cash
alternative of 2.71 Australian dollars a share on the full bid.
   Ranks Hovis' offer was conditioned on it gaining acceptance for
at least 50 percent of Goodman Fielder shares and Australian
government approval.
</TEXT>
