<FIRST>r f AM-UMW-Pittston     04-26 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>100 More UMW Members Arrested In Pittston Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 striking United Mine Workers
members were arrested Wednesday and other UMW members used their
cars to block entrances to a coal preparation plant in the third
day of civil disobedience aimed at shutting down Pittston Coal
Group operations.
   The miners were arrested when they tried to block the entrance
to Pittston's Lambert Fork mine near Dante, said Lt. J.D. Willis of
the Virginia State Police.
   ``We took them away in buses and tried to disembark them for
processing at several places in Dickenson County but were turned
away because of crowd control problems,'' Willis said.
   Miners also blocked both entrances to Pittston's Moss No. 3
preparation plant by parking their cars on both sides of the road,
leaving space for passenger cars but not coal trucks. State police
sealed off the road and called two tow trucks, whose drivers
refused to tow away the cars.
   At least 600 miners have been arrested since the civil
disobedience tactics _ largely blocking roads and mine entrances _
went into effect Monday.
   About 1,700 UMW members have been on strike at Pittston mines in
Virginia and West Virginia since April 5. The miners had been
working without a contract for 14 months, and the union accused
Pittston of engaging in unfair labor practices during negotiations,
a claim Pittston denies.
   The UMW was joined Monday by 750 Westmoreland Coal Co. workers
the union called off the job for three of the 10 ``memorial days''
_ or personal days _ permitted under their contract.
   The union also has called selective strikes Monday at three
non-Pittston operations in West Virginia. About 100 miners are
striking Gilbert Imported Hardwoods Inc. and Lynn Land Co. in Mingo
County and Belva Coal Co. in Logan County.
   Those also miners had been working without a contract since
February 1988.
   ``We're looking closely at several other independent companies
that have also failed to negotiate successor agreements,'' said UMW
District 17 President Bob Phalen in Charleston, W.Va.
   Phalen refused to say whether there will be additional walkouts.
</TEXT>
