<HEAD>Transamerica Reports First Quarter Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transamerica Corp.'s earnings more than
doubled in the first quarter because of a one-time charge that
reduced earnings in the year-earlier period, the company said
Wednesday.
   Transamerica had first-quarter earnings of $70.8 million, or 89
cents a share, compared to $30.7 million, or 36 cents per share in
the same quarter of 1988, the financial services company said.
   Revenue totaled $1.59 billion, up from a restated $1.53 billion
a year earlier.
   However, the company pointed out in a statement that results for
1988 included a $36.9 million one-time reduction for ``the
cumulative effect of a change in accounting for income taxes.''
   Operating income for the three months ended March 31 was $70.8
million, or 89 cents a share, up 5 percent from $67.6 million, or
85 cents per share, a year ago.
