<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-26 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar pushed higher Wednesday against all
major currencies in brisk trading after the government released its
latest data on economic growth.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a troy ounce of gold at $384.50 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down 25 cents
from late Tuesday.
   Currency traders said that sentiment toward the dollar remains
strong and escalated after the Commerce Department's gross national
product report was released.
   The agency said the economy, as measured by GNP, expanded at a
robust annual rate of 5.5 percent the first three months of 1989,
the fastest pace in over a year.
   About half of that increase came from a catch-up from last
year's drought. Without the farm sector, the growth rate would have
been just 3 percent, down from a 3.5 percent non-farm growth rate
in the 1988 fourth quarter.
   Robert Ryan, senior trader for Irving Trust Co., said the
currency market interpreted the report as bullish for the dollar,
nonetheless, because it meant interest rates probably would remain
firm in the near term to combat signs of inflation.
   Ryan said technical factors and rising oil prices, particularly
in wholesale gasoline, also helped push the dollar higher.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose to 131.47 Japanese yen from 131.17 Tuesday.
The dollar traded higher in London at 132.00 yen, and in New York
at 132.105 yen, up from 131.475 yen late Tuesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6932 late Wednesday,
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $1.7030. Sterling fetched
$1.6900 in New York, down from $1.69945.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's levels, included: 1.8793 West German marks, up from
1.86655; 1.6580 Swiss francs, up from 1.64625; 1.18955 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.18925; 6.3595 French francs, up from 6.3175; and
1,377.375 Italian lire, up from 1,367.20.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Tuesday's rates
included: 1.8770 West German marks, up from 1.8625; 1.6555 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6435; 6.3395 French francs, up from 6.3065;
2.1150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1000; 1,374.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,366.00; and 1.1900 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1910.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $385.30 a troy ounce from $385.70 late Tuesday.
   The late gold bid in London was $384.25 an ounce, down from
$385.75 late Tuesday. The Zurich late bid was $383.50 an ounce,
down from $385.00.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $384.55 an ounce, down
from $385.65.
   Silver prices also lost ground. On the New York Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery was bid at $5.763 a troy ounce, down
from $5.789. Silver fell in London to $5.77 an ounce from $5.81.
</TEXT>
