<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-UnionCarbide     04-26 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Union Carbide,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Carbide Addresses Bhopal Settlement at Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. shareholders on Wednesday
soundly rejected a proposal that the company provide humanitarian
relief to Bhopal, India, where a 1984 gas leak from a company plant
killed more than 3,000 people.
   ``That should be the last of the direct financial effects of the
Bhopal tragedy,'' Robert D. Kennedy, chairman and chief executive
officer of Union Carbide, said after an orderly two-hour meeting.
   In their first meeting since the company reached a $470 million
damage settlement with the Indian government in February,
shareholders also approved formation of a holding company and
establishment of its domestic and plastics business as a
wholly-owned subsidiary.
   But most of the focus Wednesday was on the settlement, which
protesters decried as inadequate.
   The Dec. 2-3, 1984, leak of poisonous methyl isocyanate gas from
a Union Carbide chemical plant in Bhopal left an estimated 20,000
people injured, according to government statistics. Activist groups
cite figures of 4,000 dead and 200,000 injured.
   The Supreme Court of India on Feb. 14 directed the Danbury,
Conn.-based company to pay $470 million ``in full settlement of all
claims, rights and liabilities related to and arising out of the
Bhopal gas disaster.''
   Minority shareholders, including church-affiliated groups, had
introduced a resolution urging that the company take additional
steps to provide immediate humanitarian relief to India, but it was
rejected by 93 percent of the voting shareholders.
   Shareholders also rejected a resolution to sell Union Carbide's
South African holdings.
   Kennedy said the company had attempted to provide additional,
direct aid to the people of Bhopal, but the government rejected the
effort. Protesters, including three Bhopal victims touring the
country to draw support for their cause, said the settlement amount
was inadequate.
   About a dozen protesters displayed banners and distributed
information outside before the meeting and several shareholders
called for additional company aid during the meeting.
   ``We are here to tell that this settlement has been rejected by
the people of Bhopal,'' said Satinath Sarangi, who later was
arrested along with three others for trying to enter the Hyatt
Regency Hotel and distribute contradictory reports on the accident.
   ``They do not accept it because they know that this amount is
insufficient to meet the health care requirements (of victims),''
Sarangi said. ``To accept such a settlement is to accept certain
death, and they are not prepared to accept it.''
   The settlement is on appeal and its distribution is being
withheld by the government, Union Carbide said.
   Kennedy said the company was securing the protesters' release
from jail and was not involved in their arrests. He apologized for
the incident and offered to meet with them later.
   ``The end of litigation does not mean that Bhopal is
forgotten,'' Kennedy said. ``Although we have evidence to prove
that a Bhopal employee of Union Carbide India Ltd. sabotaged the
plant, we know the tragedy will always be linked in people's minds
with Union Carbide Corp.''
   The shareholder-approved restructuring, designed for more
efficient use of Union Carbide's multinational operations, creates
a subsidiary to be called Union Carbide Chemicals and Plastics
Company Inc. It joins two other core subsidiaries created in
January: Union Carbide Industrial Gases Inc. and UCAR Carbon
Company Inc.
   The change was approved by more than 85 percent of the voting
shares.
   Kennedy said the restructuring would give management at each
subsidiary more flexibility and authority to respond to changing
markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
