<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-26 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platinum Prices Rise As Confidence In Market Grows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices surged on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on Wednesday following published reports in Japan that
prices could regain the $600 an ounce levels of late 1988.
   On other markets, gasoline prices rose sharply while crude oil
and heating oil prices fell; pork prices rallied but cattle were
little changed; grain and soybeans were mixed, and cocoa prices
plunged.
   Platinum settled $9 dollars higher across the board, with July
at $557.30 a troy ounce.
   Platinum prices were trading near $600 an ounce last year, but
the market collapsed in mid-December after the Ford Motor Co.,
announced its development of a platinum-free catalytic converter.
   Platinum is a key component in most of the automobile
pollution-control devices, which account for a third of the metal's
use worldwide.
   ``A constructive story on platinum in Japan saying the market
could rise to near $600,'' keyed the surge in platinum prices, said
Bernard Savaiko, an analyst with PaineWebber, Inc., in New York.
   Platinum demand is expected to outstrip production into the
1990s, and the market has been rising lately as traders
increasingly focus on supply and demand.
   Gold settled at 40 cents to $1 lower, with June at $388.20 a
troy ounce; silver was 3.2 cents to 3.6 cents lower, with May at
$5.763 a troy ounce.
   Gasoline prices soared on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
hectic activity as traders holding contracts for delivery of
gasoline in May scrambled to escape that obligation ahead of the
contract's expiration this Friday. Crude oil and heating oil prices
fell.
   Crude oil settled 12 cents to 33 cents lower with June at $21.19
a barrel; heating oil was 1.09 cents to 1.43 cents lower with May
at 50.98 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline oil was .30 cent to 1.96
cents higher with May at 78.12 cents a gallon.
   Pork futures rallied strongly for a second day on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange amid speculation that hog marketings will
subside in early May. Cattle futures were little changed.
   Hog slaughters typically slack off and prices typically rise
during May in a normal seasonal pattern. But signs of a seasonal
decline have not surfaced yet, so the market's recent strength has
been almost entirely speculative, said Chuck Levitt, an analyst in
Chicago with Shearson Lehmann Hutton Inc.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June
at 70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .33 cent lower to .25
cent higher with May at 75.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .03
cent lower to .45 cent higher with June at 46.77 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .65 cent to 1.10 cents higher with May at
32.65 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures prices recovered modestly from two days of steep
declines on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders who sold the
market earlier in the week bought contracts to take profits. Corn
futures prices increased and wheat futures dropped slightly.
   Soybean prices rose amid talk that a strike by Brazilian dock
workers could continue for some time.
   ``The strike may provide the United States with some export
business, although it hasn't so far,'' said Joel Karlin an analyst
for Research Department, Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents lower with May at $4.11 per
bushel; corn was { cent to 1} cents higher, with May at $2.65} per
bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 5} cents lower with May at $1.83\ per
bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 8 cents higher with May at $7.40{
per bushel.
   Cocoa futures fell sharply on the New York Coffee, Sugar and
Cocoa Exchange in response to weakness on the London market and to
greater availability of cocoa.
   Cocoa settled $22 to $45 lower with contract for delivery in May
at $1275 a metric ton.
</TEXT>
