<SECOND>AM-NCNB, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0262,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB May Bid For Texas Banks, McColl Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CORRECT that NCNB is considering bid for
former MCorp banks, not MCorp itself.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. Chairman Hugh McColl said Wednesday
that his bank may bid for 20 troubled banks formerly owned by
Dallas-based MCorp, two days after dropping its unsolicited offer
for Citizens and Southern Corp.
   At a news conference following NCNB's annual shareholders'
meeting, McColl said the company had been invited by the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. to enter the bidding for the troubled Texas
banks, which were placed in federal receivership last month
following heavy real estate and energy losses. MCorp itself still
operates five banks in Texas.
   ``We don't think we have an edge, but we already have 1,100
people running a bank for the FDIC,'' McColl said. ``We feel we
could do the same for some of their other asset problems.''
   Just four months ago, NCNB effectively doubled its size when it
was selected by the FDIC to acquire the largest bank in Texas,
First Republicbank Corp., also of Dallas. It renamed the bank NCNB
Texas National Bank.
   Francis ``Buddy'' Kemp, chairman of NCNB Texas National Bank,
said acquiring the former MCorp banks was one of several
possibilities for NCNB to expand into new markets in Texas.
   ``There are several markets in which we would like to build on
our strength,'' he said. ``Houston and San Antonio are areas where
we'd like to have more strength.''
   Tim Hartman, a vice chairman of NCNB Texas, said NCNB remained
``several weeks away from making a bid'' for the former MCorp banks.
   NCNB is North Carolina's largest bank with more than $50 billion
in assets.
   If the deal with Citizens and Southern had gone through, it
would have been the largest bank merger in U.S. history and created
a bank with more than $70 billion in assets.
   NCNB launched its $2.4 billion stock-swap bid for Citizens and
Southern on March 30, but it withdrew the offer Monday after
running into a solid wall of resistance from the Atlanta bank's
board of directors.
   ``They rejected our offer for reasons I'm sure were entirely
clear to them,'' McColl told shareholders, ``although they're not
entirely clear to me.''
</TEXT>
