<FIRST>r f AM-HollyFarms     04-26 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Considers Leveraged Recapitalization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. renewed its resistence
to a $1.15 billion takeover bid Wednesday and told shareholders an
overall refinancing of the company is being considered.
   Holly Farms has opposed a takeover by rival poultry processor
Tyson Foods Inc. since October. Holly shareholders voted last week
to reject a management-backed move to merge their company with
ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   In a statement announcing a quarterly dividend of 38 cents a
share, Holly managers said a ``leveraged recapitalization'' is
under consideration.
   Such a refinancing would involve mortgaging company assets to
pay dividends to stockholders, said Ted Bailey, a Holly Farms vice
president.
   ``It would just get some current value out to our shareholders.
It doesn't have anything to do with blocking Tyson,'' Bailey said.
   Bailey said he did not know how many company assets or which
ones might be mortgaged.
   Napoleon Overton, an analyst with Morgan Keegan &amp; Co. in
Memphis, said Holly Farms is in good financial shape and the
recapitalization could be a way to keep shareholders loyal to Holly
managers.
   ``Holly Farms management believes that a leveraged
recapitalization is now a viable alternative to either a merger
with ConAgra or an acquisition by Tyson Foods,'' Overton said.
   The recapitalization would greatly increase Holly Farms' debt,
he said. A debt increase often is used as a tool to fight off an
unwanted suitor.
   Jim Blair, general counsel for Tyson Foods of Springdale, Ark.,
said Holly managers should consider their shareholders' vote on the
ConAgra deal as a call to sell to Tyson.
   ``It looks to me a little like they're in the process again of
telling their shareholders what's best for them rather than
listening to their shareholders,'' Blair said.
   Tyson is offering Holly stockholders $63.50 a share in cash,
while the proposed merger with ConAgra was worth about $60 a share
in a stock swap.
   Holly Farms stock closed Wednesday at $60.75 a share, down 25
cents, in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
