<SECOND>AM-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0292,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Begins NWA Proxy Solicitation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs on Minnesota commerce commissioner's demand of
Davis.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil mogul Marvin Davis on Wednesday began his
proxy campaign to unseat the board of NWA Inc., mailing letters
seeking shareholder support for replacing the board with nominees
who would sell the airline company to Davis.
   ``We believe that a failure to elect our nominees will give the
NWA board an excuse to continue to pursue alternatives which do not
result in a prompt sale of the company,'' the letters read.
   NWA, parent of Eagan-based Northwest Airlines, has rejected
Davis' $90 a share tender offer valued at $2.7 billion but has
pledged to explore alternatives to maximize shareholder value.
   Davis, who owns about 2.8 percent of NWA's 29.1 million shares,
wrote in his letter that he is skeptical of the claim.
   He cited the company's refusal to withdraw its ``poison pill''
takeover defense plan and a requirement that Northwest suitors sign
a restrictive confidentiality agreement.
   ``Ask yourself whether NWA is truly seeking the best price for
you when they insist that we, the only announced bidder, sign an
agreement calling for us to consent to a standstill, abandon this
proxy contest, abandon our tender offer and abide by whatever
course or alternative the NWA board unilaterally approves,'' Davis
wrote.
   Northwest closed down 25 cents at $100 a share Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Eleven board members are up for election at NWA's annual meeting
May 15.
   A group of dissident shareholders are attempting to change the
record date for the vote, which now is limited to shareholders of
record as of March 17.
   Hennepin County District Judge Delila Pierce said Wednesday that
the request deserves a hearing next week and denied a request by
NWA to refuse the change.
   Karl Cambronne, an attorney for the shareholders, said more than
65 percent of Northwest stock has changed hands since March 17.
Rivard said new owners of Northwest stock probably are takeover
speculators and would be more likely to vote for Davis' slate of
nominees.
   Lawyers for Northwest also asked Pierce to suspend the rest of
the Minnesota shareholders' lawsuit, saying jurisdiction in
shareholder matters belongs in the courts of Delaware, where
Northwest is incorporated.
   Pierce took that request under advisement without saying when
she would rule.
   NWA's poison pill would prevent Davis' proposed board from
selling the company for six months after getting control. A
Delaware judge on Tuesday denied Davis request to invalidate the
provision.
   Also Wednesday, Minnesota Commercer Commissioner Michael Hatch
said Davis must make supplemental disclosures to Minnesota
shareholders by 2 p.m. CDT Thursday to explain how he would operate
the airline in light of the large amount of money he proposes to
borrow to complete the purchase.
   If the ``objective facts'' are not supplied by the deadline, the
tender offer in Minnesota will be suspended, Hatch said. But the
commissioner also left open the possibility of another hearing on
the matter for Thursday night if Davis requests it.
   There was no immediate comment from Davis, said his spokeswoman,
Mary Conway.
</TEXT>
