<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-NorthSeaGas 1stLd-Writethru f031s-3P 04-26 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-North Sea Gas, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0318,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closure Of Terminal Curtails Britain's North Sea Gas Supplies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with officials now saying shutdown
only affects 7 percent of gas supplies, sted third.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7 percent of Britain's North Sea
gas supplies were halted following the shutdown Wednesday night of
the onshore St. Fergus gas terminal operated jointly by the Shell
and Esso oil companies, British Gas PLC said.
   The terminal near this east Scottish oil port city handles gas
from 16 production platforms in the British sector of the North Sea
oil and gas field.
   It was shut down after routine inspection revealed defects in
equipment that ``could be of a serious nature,'' Shell said.
   Shell initially reported that the shutdown involved the whole of
the terminal, which a spokesman for the Scottish sector of British
Gas PLC said handled about a third of Britain's North Sea gas
supplies. British Gas is the monopoly company responsible for gas
supplies to homes and industry throughout Britain.
   But a Shell spokesman subsequently said that only part of the
terminal had been shut and that this part accounted for about 7
percent of Britain's North Sea gas supplies.
   The shutdown is the second North Sea setback in eight days. The
North Sea's Brent oil field has been shut since April 18 when a gas
leak and explosion on Shell's Cormorant Alpha platform halted
production of 472,000 barrels of oil a day, or nearly a quarter of
the British sector's oil production.
</TEXT>
